export const VIBE_PAGES = [{"id":"vibe1","n":1,"g":"W","title":"The Vibe Coding Loop","tagline":"By the end of this page you'll understand the exact four-step rhythm that lets anyone build real, working software just by talking to an AI in plain English, no coding experience required.","intro":"Here is the single most important idea in vibe coding: you are not writing code, you are having a conversation. You describe what you want in everyday words, an AI writes the actual code, you run it to see what happens, and then you tell the AI what to fix. Then you do it again. That back-and-forth is called the Vibe Coding Loop, and once you internalize it, building an app feels less like engineering and more like directing a very fast, very literal assistant. This page walks a complete beginner through every stage of that loop, with concrete examples you can copy today, and it is honest about where the AI will trip you up so you're never caught off guard.","sections":[{"heading":"The one mental shift: it's a conversation, not a command","paras":["Most people imagine that building software means typing a magic spell, hitting enter, and getting a finished product. That's not how vibe coding works, and expecting it to work that way is the number one reason beginners give up. Vibe coding, a term coined by AI researcher Andrej Karpathy, means building software by describing what you want in plain English and letting an AI write the code, then improving it through an ongoing conversation. The keyword is 'ongoing.' Your first request almost never produces exactly what you pictured. That's not failure, that's the process working as intended.","Think of it like ordering a custom cake over text messages. You don't send one message and get a perfect wedding cake. You say 'I want a chocolate cake for about 20 people.' The baker sends a photo. You say 'great, but can the frosting be white instead of brown, and add my daughter's name?' They send another photo. You say 'perfect, but the name is spelled wrong.' Each message gets you closer. Vibe coding is that exact rhythm, except the baker works in seconds and never gets tired of your revisions.","This means your job is fundamentally different from a traditional programmer's. You are the director, the architect, the person holding the vision and the judgment. The AI is the implementer, the pair of hands that actually types the code. You do NOT need to read or understand every line the AI produces. You judge the result, the thing you can see and click and use, and you give feedback in normal human words: 'the button is too small,' 'it crashes when I upload a photo,' 'make the whole thing look more modern.' If you can describe what's wrong to a friend, you can steer an AI.","A quick reality check that will save you frustration: AI-written code is like work from an eager, talented intern on their first day. It's usually functional, often impressively so, but it is unverified. The intern is fast and enthusiastic but occasionally confidently wrong. It might build a feature that looks perfect but breaks in a way it didn't think to test. Your judgment, running the thing and noticing what's off, is the quality control the AI cannot do for itself. That partnership, tireless AI hands plus your human eyes and taste, is the whole game."]},{"heading":"The four stages of the loop, in detail","paras":["Every vibe coding session, whether you're changing one button or building an entire app, cycles through the same four stages. Learn these four words and you'll always know where you are and what to do next: Intent, Generate, Execute, Refine. Then loop back to Intent and go again. Let's walk through each one slowly, because the whole method lives here.","Stage 1, INTENT: You describe, in plain English, what you want to build or change. This is you talking. No code, no jargon, just a clear description of the outcome you're after. The clearer and more specific you are, the better the result, but you don't need to be perfect, because you'll refine later. Example intent from a freelance photographer: 'Build me a simple web page where potential clients can see my photo galleries organized by category (weddings, portraits, events) and fill out a contact form to request a quote.' That single sentence is a complete Stage 1.","Stage 2, GENERATE: The AI writes or edits the actual code. This is the AI's turn. You wait a few seconds while it produces real, working files, the HTML that structures the page, the styling that makes it look good, the logic that makes the form work. You don't touch anything here. On some tools you literally watch the code stream out; on others it quietly writes files behind the scenes. Either way, the output of this stage is a thing that can actually run.","Stage 3, EXECUTE and TEST: You run it and see what actually happens. This is the moment of truth, and beginners often skip it, which is a mistake. 'Running' the code means opening the result and using it like a real person would. You click the buttons. You fill out the form. You upload a weird file on purpose. You resize the window. You are hunting for the gap between what you imagined and what the AI actually built. Maybe the galleries look great but the contact form doesn't send anything. Maybe it's beautiful on your laptop but unreadable on your phone. You can only find these things by trying it.","Stage 4, REFINE: You tell the AI what's wrong, missing, or should change, and it revises. This is you talking again, armed with what you just discovered in Stage 3. 'The contact form doesn't do anything when I click submit, please make it send the message to my email.' 'On my phone the photos are cut off, make it responsive so it looks good on small screens.' 'The wedding gallery should come first, not last.' Then the AI generates again (back to Stage 2), you test again (Stage 3), you refine again (Stage 4), and you keep looping until it's genuinely right. Most real features take three to ten laps around this loop. That's completely normal."]},{"heading":"Where you'll actually do this: the tools","paras":["The loop is the method; the tools are just different rooms you can run the loop in. You do not need all of them. Pick one that matches how comfortable you are, and know that they all do the same fundamental thing, let you describe what you want and get code back. Here's the honest landscape, from 'never touch a code file' to 'run everything on your own computer.'","The gentlest on-ramp is a plain chat assistant with a live preview. In Claude (at claude.ai) you can ask for a small app and it appears in a panel called Artifacts that you can actually click and use right next to the conversation. In ChatGPT (chat.openai.com) the similar feature is called Canvas. Google Gemini works this way too. You never see a code file if you don't want to; you just chat, watch the preview update, and refine. This is the friendliest place for your very first loop.","When you're ready to build something bigger that lives in real files, you graduate to an AI code editor, also called an AI IDE (Integrated Development Environment, which is just the professional program where code lives). The standout is Cursor (cursor.com, and free for students), which looks like a normal editor but has an AI chat built into the side that can write and change files across your whole project on command. GitHub Copilot is an AI assistant that plugs into an editor and is free for verified students and teachers at education.github.com, otherwise around ten dollars a month. Windsurf is another AI editor in the same family. Claude also offers Claude Code, a version of the agent that works right in your terminal (the black text window where you type commands) and can create files and run things across an entire project while you steer.","If you don't want to install anything at all, browser builders let you create apps entirely on a website: Replit (build and even publish from your browser), Bolt.new, and Google AI Studio all let you go from idea to running app without touching your own machine. And on the privacy end, if you want AI that runs entirely on your own computer with nothing sent to the internet, Ollama and LM Studio let you download and run AI models locally, which is slower and more technical but completely private and free to run."],"table":{"headers":["Tool","What it is","Best for a beginner who wants to..."],"rows":[["Claude (Artifacts)","Chat assistant with a live clickable preview","Chat and see a small app appear instantly, zero setup"],["ChatGPT (Canvas)","Chat assistant with a side-by-side editing panel","Draft and refine in a document-like view"],["Cursor","AI code editor (free for students)","Build a real multi-file project with an AI beside you"],["GitHub Copilot","AI helper inside an editor (free for verified students/teachers)","Get AI suggestions while working in a real editor"],["Replit / Bolt.new","Build entirely in the browser","Create and publish without installing anything"],["Ollama / LM Studio","Run AI models on your own computer","Keep everything private and offline"]]}},{"heading":"The loop scaled up: the 3-step project method (PRD, Build, Test)","paras":["The four-stage loop is perfect for one change at a time. But how do you build a whole project without it turning into chaos? You use the same loop, just zoomed out to the scale of a full project. This is the core three-step method, and it maps cleanly onto Intent, Generate, and Execute/Refine: first you write a PRD, then you build it with an AI editor, then you test and refine.","Step 1 is writing a PRD, which stands for Program Requirements Document. Don't let the fancy name scare you, it's simply a plain-language blueprint of what you're building: what the app does, who it's for, what the main screens are, and what each feature should do. It's the 'Intent' stage for your whole project, written down so the AI has the full picture instead of guessing. A small-business owner building an appointment booker might list: 'a calendar customers can see, the ability to pick an open time slot, a form for their name and phone number, and an email to me when someone books.' That's a PRD in miniature.","Here's a pro move that dramatically improves results and is worth doing every single time: PLAN the PRD with a DIFFERENT AI than the one you code with. Use one AI (say, Claude or ChatGPT in a normal chat) purely to help you think through and write a thorough PRD, asking it to poke holes, suggest features you forgot, and organize your thoughts. Then take that finished PRD to your coding tool (say, Cursor) to actually build. Why two AIs? Because the planning AI acts as a fresh, critical thinking partner, and a detailed plan gives the coding AI far less room to wander off and guess wrong. It's the difference between handing a contractor a full set of blueprints versus describing your dream house one sentence at a time.","Step 2 is Build: you hand your PRD to an AI editor and let it generate the project, feature by feature. Step 3 is Test and Refine: you run the app, use it like a real customer, find what's broken or ugly or missing, and loop back with specific feedback, exactly the four-stage loop from before, now operating on a real project. This has grown into what people call 'agentic engineering,' where AI agents don't just write code but can create files, run commands, and test across your whole project on their own while you supervise and steer. You stay the director; the agent just handles more of the busywork between your decisions."],"prompt":{"label":"Copy-paste starter to plan your PRD (paste into Claude or ChatGPT, not your coding tool)","text":"I want to build a simple app and I have never written code before. Act as my product planning partner and help me write a clear Program Requirements Document (PRD) in plain English. Here is my idea: [describe your app in a sentence or two]. Ask me any questions you need to fill in the gaps, point out features I probably forgot, and then produce a well-organized PRD I can hand to an AI coding tool. Keep it beginner-friendly and avoid jargon."}},{"heading":"How to give feedback that actually works","paras":["Since the whole method is a conversation, the quality of your results depends heavily on the quality of your feedback. Good news: you already have this skill, because it's the same skill as describing a problem clearly to a human. The trick is to be specific about the observation, not the solution. You don't need to know HOW to fix something, you just need to describe precisely WHAT is wrong.","Vague feedback like 'it doesn't work' or 'make it better' forces the AI to guess, and it'll often guess wrong. Specific feedback gives it a target. Compare these. Weak: 'the page looks bad.' Strong: 'the text is too small to read on my phone, and the blue background makes the black text hard to see, please increase the font size and use a lighter background.' The strong version names the exact thing you saw and where you saw it. That's all it takes.","When something breaks outright (programmers call this a bug, an error that makes the software behave wrong or stop working), describe exactly what you did and exactly what happened. 'When I fill out the contact form and click Submit, nothing happens and the page just sits there' is a fantastic bug report. If the tool shows you a scary red error message, you don't need to understand it, just copy the entire message and paste it to the AI with 'I got this error, what does it mean and how do we fix it?' The AI reads error messages fluently even when you can't.","A few more feedback patterns that work beautifully once you get the rhythm: 'That's close, but change X' keeps a good result and tweaks one thing. 'Undo that last change, it made things worse' is a completely valid instruction, the AI will revert. 'Before you write any code, explain your plan in plain English so I can check it' catches misunderstandings before they become code. And 'add a feature that lets users do Z' extends what you've built. You are always one clear sentence away from your next improvement."],"prompt":{"label":"A reliable refine-stage template you can reuse every loop","text":"Here's what I did: [the exact steps you took]. Here's what I expected to happen: [what you wanted]. Here's what actually happened instead: [what you saw, including any error message pasted in full]. Please explain what went wrong in plain English, then fix it."}},{"heading":"Staying safe and shipping it to the world","paras":["Two practical things separate a fun experiment from something you can actually share: keeping your secrets safe, and putting your finished app online. Both are easy once you know the rules, and skipping the first one can genuinely cost you money, so read this part.","The security rule you must never break: never let the AI put passwords, secret keys, or API keys directly into your code. An API key is a private password that lets your app use an outside service (for example, a key that lets your app send emails, or use an AI service, or charge a credit card). If that key gets exposed publicly, strangers can run up charges on your account or abuse the service in your name. AI tools, being eager interns, will sometimes cheerfully paste a key straight into a code file where it doesn't belong. The safe pattern is to store secrets in a separate file called a .env file (short for 'environment,' a plain text file that holds your private values) and then add that file's name to another file called .gitignore, which is a list telling the system 'never upload these files anywhere.' If you're unsure, you can literally ask your AI: 'make sure no secret keys are hardcoded, put them in a .env file and add it to .gitignore.'","Once your app works and your secrets are safe, publishing it (putting it on the public internet so anyone with a link can use it, which programmers call 'deploying') is free and takes minutes. GitHub Pages hosts simple websites for free. Netlify and Vercel are free services that take your project and give it a live web address, often with nothing more than connecting your project and clicking a button. Replit can publish directly from the browser where you built the app. You can ask your AI to walk you through any of these step by step, and it will.","Keep your expectations calibrated and you'll love this process. AI coding is astonishingly capable and getting better fast, but it is not magic and it is not always right. It will occasionally build something that looks finished but hides a flaw only testing reveals, it can get stuck repeating the same broken fix (when that happens, start a fresh conversation or rephrase your request from scratch), and it works best on small, clearly-described pieces rather than one giant vague wish. Respect those limits, run the loop with patience, and you will build things this week that would have taken a professional developer months to teach you to build the old way. The best time to run your first loop is right now, so pick a tiny idea and start talking."],"prompt":{"label":"Copy-paste safety check to run before you share anything","text":"Please review this project for security before I publish it. Make sure no passwords, secret keys, or API keys are hardcoded anywhere in the code. Move any secrets into a .env file and add .env to .gitignore so it never gets uploaded. Then explain, in plain English, how to deploy this for free using GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, or Replit, step by step for someone who has never done it."}}],"keyTerms":[{"term":"Vibe coding","def":"Building software by describing what you want in plain English and letting an AI write the code, then improving it through back-and-forth conversation."},{"term":"The Vibe Coding Loop","def":"The repeating four-stage cycle of Intent (describe it), Generate (AI writes code), Execute/Test (you run it), and Refine (you say what to fix)."},{"term":"PRD (Program Requirements Document)","def":"A plain-language blueprint of what you're building, who it's for, and what each feature should do, written before you build."},{"term":"IDE (Integrated Development Environment)","def":"The program where code is written and edited; an AI IDE like Cursor has an AI assistant built in that can write and change your files."},{"term":"Terminal","def":"The black text window on a computer where you type commands instead of clicking buttons; some AI tools like Claude Code work here."},{"term":"Bug","def":"An error that makes software behave incorrectly or stop working, which you find by testing and describe to the AI to get fixed."},{"term":"API key","def":"A private password that lets your app use an outside service, which must be kept secret so no one else can run up charges in your name."},{"term":".env file and .gitignore","def":"A .env file safely stores your secret keys separately from your code, and listing it in .gitignore ensures those secrets never get uploaded to the internet."},{"term":"Deploy","def":"To publish your finished app to the public internet so anyone with the link can use it, which free services like Netlify, Vercel, GitHub Pages, and Replit make easy."},{"term":"Agentic engineering","def":"AI agents that can create files, run commands, and test across your whole project on their own while you supervise and steer the vision."}],"tips":["Start absurdly small. Your first loop should be something like 'make a page with my name and a button that shows a random compliment.' Winning fast teaches the rhythm better than a big project that stalls.","Always run and click the result before refining. Reading the code tells you nothing useful as a beginner; using the app tells you everything. The Execute stage is where all the real information is.","Plan with one AI, build with another. Draft your PRD in Claude or ChatGPT, then hand that finished blueprint to a coding tool like Cursor. A critical planning partner plus a detailed plan produces dramatically better results.","When the AI gets stuck in a loop repeating the same broken fix, stop refining and start a fresh conversation, or rephrase your request from scratch. A clean slate almost always breaks the logjam.","Before you ever share your app, ask the AI to confirm no secret keys are hardcoded and that any secrets live in a .env file listed in .gitignore. This one habit protects your money and your accounts."]},{"id":"vibe2","n":2,"g":"W","title":"Step 1 — Write Your PRD (Your Blueprint)","tagline":"Turn a fuzzy idea in your head into a crystal-clear blueprint an AI can build from — before you write a single line of code.","intro":"Every great build starts with a plan, not with code. In vibe coding — the practice of building software by describing what you want in plain English and letting an AI write the actual code — that plan is called a PRD, a Program Requirements Document. Think of it as the architectural drawings for a house: nobody pours concrete before the blueprints are drawn, and you shouldn't ask an AI to build your app before you've written down exactly what it is. This page walks you, a complete beginner who may never have opened a code editor, through creating your first PRD from scratch — using a friendly chat AI, in plain conversation, in about twenty minutes.","sections":[{"heading":"What a PRD actually is (and why it's the whole game)","paras":["A PRD — short for Program Requirements Document — is a plain-language written description of the software you want to build. There is no code in it, no technical jargon you have to invent, and no special software needed to write one. It's a document, written in ordinary sentences, that answers questions like: What does this thing do? Who is it for? What should happen when someone clicks this button? What should it look like? If you can describe your idea to a friend over coffee, you can write a PRD.","The name sounds intimidating, so here's the honest translation: a PRD is a blueprint. When an architect designs a house, they don't just start stacking bricks and hope it works out. They draw detailed plans first — where the kitchen goes, how many bedrooms, where the plumbing runs — so that the builders know exactly what to make. Your PRD is that set of plans, and the AI is your builder. The clearer your plans, the closer the finished building matches what you pictured in your head.","Writing a PRD first does four powerful things. First, it forces you to actually think through your idea — you'll discover questions you never considered, like 'wait, should people be able to edit an entry after they save it?' Second, it saves you enormous time: without a plan, you tend to build half of something, realize it's wrong, and start over — sometimes three or four times. Third, it gives the AI clear, unambiguous instructions, which is the single biggest factor in whether the AI builds something good. Fourth, it becomes documentation you can hand to any AI (or any person) later and say 'here's what this is,' so you never lose the thread of your own project.","Here's the mindset shift that makes this click for beginners: you are not the builder, you are the client. A client doesn't need to know how to lay bricks — they need to know what they want and be able to describe it well. Your entire job in vibe coding is to describe clearly and then react honestly to what the AI produces. The PRD is where the describing starts."]},{"heading":"The golden rule: plan with a DIFFERENT AI than the one you build with","paras":["This is the one piece of advice that separates smooth first projects from frustrating ones, so read it twice. You should write your PRD using one AI — a general-purpose chat assistant — and then build your project with a completely different AI tool later. Do not do both in the same place. This sounds fussy, but there's a concrete reason rooted in how these AIs work.","Every AI has something called a context window — its short-term memory, the amount of conversation it can 'hold in its head' at one time. Picture it like a small whiteboard: the AI can only fit so much on it, and when the whiteboard fills up, older notes get wiped to make room for new ones. When you eventually build your app, the coding AI needs that whiteboard almost entirely free to keep track of your files, your code, and your instructions. If you also used it for the long, winding conversation of designing your PRD, half the whiteboard is already crowded with brainstorming before it even starts building — and it starts forgetting things it shouldn't.","So the workflow is: brainstorm and write the PRD in a friendly chat AI — Claude at claude.ai, ChatGPT at chat.openai.com, or Google Gemini all work perfectly for this and have free tiers. Save the finished PRD as a file. Then, in a separate tool built for building — an AI code editor like Cursor (cursor.com, free for students), or Claude Code, or Replit (which builds in your browser) — you hand over the clean PRD and say 'build this.' The coding AI reads your blueprint fresh, with all its memory available for the real work.","A simple analogy: you meet with an architect to design your house (the planning AI), you walk away with a clean set of blueprints (your saved PRD), and then you hand those blueprints to a construction crew (the coding AI). You would never expect the crew to also sit through every design meeting — you just give them the finished plans. Same idea here."]},{"heading":"Step 1 of 5: Start the conversation and let the AI interview YOU","paras":["Open your chosen chat AI — let's say Claude or ChatGPT — in a fresh conversation. Instead of dumping a vague idea and hoping for the best, you're going to flip the script: you'll ask the AI to interview you. This is the secret sauce. A good interview pulls details out of your head that you didn't even realize mattered, and it does it one gentle question at a time so you're never overwhelmed.","Copy the prompt below exactly and paste it in as your very first message. A 'prompt' is just the text you type to an AI — think of it as your instruction or request. Fill in the bracketed part with a short description of what you want to build. For example, replace [TYPE OF PROGRAM] with 'invoice generator for my small business,' or 'personal habit tracker,' or 'wedding-guest RSVP tracker.' Keep it to a phrase — the whole point is that the AI will ask you the rest.","When you send this, the AI will reply with a single question — maybe 'Who is the main person who'll use this?' — and then wait for your answer before asking the next one. That one-at-a-time rhythm is deliberate and calming. You're having a conversation, not filling out a giant form."],"prompt":{"label":"Paste this as your first message (fill in the bracket)","text":"I want to create a [TYPE OF PROGRAM]. I'd like you to help me create a detailed Program Requirements Document (PRD). First, please ask me clarifying questions about what it should do, who will use it, what features it needs, how it should look and feel, and any technical preferences. Please ask 5-10 questions, one at a time, and I'll answer each."}},{"heading":"Step 2 of 5: Answer honestly — and never fake understanding","paras":["Now the AI asks its questions, one by one, and you answer each in plain words. There's no wrong way to answer and no vocabulary you need to know. If it asks 'What features do you need first?', you might say for a habit tracker: 'I want to add a habit, check it off each day, and see a little streak counter of how many days in a row I've done it.' That's a perfect answer — specific, concrete, in your own words.","The most important rule here: if the AI asks something you don't understand, do not guess or nod along. Just say, in your own words, that you're lost. A phrase that works beautifully is 'Explain that like I'm 10 years old.' The AI will happily re-explain without any jargon. For instance, if it asks 'Do you want this to persist data between sessions?' and that means nothing to you, reply 'Explain that like I'm 10 years old' — and it'll come back with 'Do you want your saved habits to still be there tomorrow when you reopen the app, or is it okay if everything disappears when you close it?' Now you can answer easily.","Lean into specifics wherever you can, because vague answers produce vague software. Compare 'make it look nice' (the AI has to guess) with 'clean, modern look, mostly white with blue accents, big friendly buttons' (the AI knows exactly what to build). Reference things you already know: 'the entry form should feel like a simple Google Form' or 'the dashboard should look like the front of a banking app.' These familiar comparisons are gold — they pack a ton of design detail into a few words the AI understands instantly.","And you don't need to worry about the technical plumbing. If the AI asks about databases, hosting, or programming languages and you have no preference, just say 'I don't have a preference — please pick sensible defaults and keep it as simple as possible.' Filling in good technical choices is exactly what the AI is for. Your job is the what and the why; the how is its job."]},{"heading":"Step 3 of 5: Ask for the last questions before you generate","paras":["After you've answered its round of questions, don't rush straight to producing the document. Give the AI one more chance to catch anything it's still unsure about. This tiny extra step routinely surfaces an important detail that would otherwise have been missed — like whether a freelancer's invoice tool needs to handle more than one currency, or whether your RSVP tracker should let guests note a food allergy.","Send exactly this short message. If the AI says it has everything it needs, wonderful — you're ready to generate. If it asks two or three more questions, even better; answer them the same honest way, and you'll end up with a richer blueprint."],"prompt":{"label":"Send this before generating the PRD","text":"Are there any other questions before we create the PRD?"}},{"heading":"Step 4 of 5: Generate the actual PRD document","paras":["Now you tell the AI to turn your whole conversation into a clean, organized document. Paste the prompt below exactly. It asks for the PRD in Markdown — Markdown is just a simple way of formatting plain text with headings and bullet points using ordinary symbols like # and -, and it's the standard format that coding AIs read most comfortably. You don't have to write any Markdown yourself; you're only asking the AI to produce it, and it will.","Notice the seven sections it requests: Project Title and Overview, Target Audience, Goals and Objectives, Core Features (detailed), User Interface Description, Technical Requirements, and Success Criteria. Each one earns its place. 'Core Features' is where the real substance lives — the specific things your app does. 'User Interface Description' captures the look and layout. 'Technical Requirements' is where the AI fills in the plumbing you didn't have to know. 'Success Criteria' is your finish line — a plain list of 'this app is done when it can do X, Y, and Z' — so you'll actually know when you're finished instead of tinkering forever.","The last sentence of the prompt is the quiet hero: it tells the AI to make the document detailed enough that another AI agent can read it and know exactly what to build. That instruction is what makes your PRD portable — good enough to hand off to a totally different coding tool later, which is exactly the different-AI workflow from earlier. Read the result over once. If a feature is described wrong or something's missing, just say so in plain words ('actually the streak should reset if I miss a day') and ask it to update the document."],"prompt":{"label":"Generate the PRD","text":"Great! Now create a detailed PRD in Markdown with these sections: 1. Project Title and Overview, 2. Target Audience, 3. Goals and Objectives, 4. Core Features (detailed), 5. User Interface Description, 6. Technical Requirements, 7. Success Criteria. Make it detailed enough that another AI agent can read it and know exactly what to build."}},{"heading":"Step 5 of 5: Save it as project-prd.md in a new project folder","paras":["The AI will output your finished PRD as text on screen. Now you need to save it as a file so you can hand it to your coding tool later. Create a new folder on your computer just for this project — on Windows, right-click your desktop or Documents, choose New then Folder, and name it something like 'invoice-generator' or 'habit-tracker.' Keeping each project in its own dedicated folder is a small habit that pays off hugely; your code, your PRD, and everything else for this build lives together in one tidy place.","Inside that folder, save the PRD with the exact filename project-prd.md. The .md on the end stands for Markdown — that's the file type you asked the AI to produce, and it's just a plain text file. The simplest way: highlight and copy all the PRD text from the chat, open a basic text editor (Notepad on Windows works fine), paste it in, then use Save As, type project-prd.md as the filename, and make sure it saves as a plain text file rather than a Word document. Many chat AIs also have a download or copy button right on the response to make this even easier.","That single file is now your blueprint, and it's worth treating as precious — it's the distilled result of all your thinking. When you move to Step 2 of the overall vibe-coding workflow (building the app in an AI code editor), the very first thing you'll do is point the coding AI at this file and say 'read project-prd.md and build it.' A clean, well-written blueprint at this stage is the difference between an AI that builds the right thing on the first try and one that guesses and wanders."]},{"heading":"Tips, pitfalls, and honest expectations","paras":["Start smaller than you think you should. It is deeply tempting to describe your dream app with every feature imaginable, but a huge PRD leads to a sprawling, buggy first build. Pick the smallest version that would still be genuinely useful — the 'core' — and put everything else in a short 'Future Features' note at the bottom of the PRD for later. A freelancer's invoice tool that just creates and downloads one clean invoice is a triumphant first project; the client portal and automatic tax calculations can come in version two.","Be concrete about look and feel, because 'nice' means nothing to a computer. Name colors ('white background, navy blue buttons, a touch of green for success messages'), name a vibe ('minimal and calm, like a meditation app' versus 'bold and energetic'), and reference apps or forms you already like. Every specific detail you provide is one fewer thing the AI has to guess — and guesses are where disappointing results come from.","Finally, keep honest expectations about what comes next. AI-written code is like the work of an eager, talented intern: it's usually functional and produced impressively fast, but it is unverified — it can contain mistakes, take shortcuts, or misunderstand you, and it needs you to test it and push back. A great PRD dramatically reduces those misunderstandings before they ever happen, which is exactly why this step is worth the twenty minutes. You're not just planning your app; you're teaching your future builder precisely what 'right' looks like."],"bullets":["Do the whole PRD conversation in ONE chat session, so the AI keeps full context of everything you told it.","If an answer feels hard, it usually means you've found a real decision worth making — sit with it for a moment rather than skipping it.","Reuse the exact same 5-prompt process for every future project; it works for any kind of software, from a calculator to a full web app.","Never put real passwords, credit card numbers, or private customer data into your PRD — it's a plan, not a place for secrets."]}],"keyTerms":[{"term":"PRD (Program Requirements Document)","def":"A plain-language written blueprint describing exactly what your software should do, who it's for, and how it should look — with no code in it."},{"term":"Vibe coding","def":"Building software by describing what you want in plain English and letting an AI write the actual code, then refining it through back-and-forth conversation."},{"term":"Prompt","def":"The text instruction or request you type to an AI to tell it what you want it to do."},{"term":"Context window","def":"An AI's short-term memory — the limited amount of conversation it can hold at once, which fills up and starts forgetting older details when overloaded."},{"term":"Markdown","def":"A simple way of formatting plain text with ordinary symbols like # for headings and - for bullets, and the standard format coding AIs read most easily."},{"term":"AI code editor (IDE)","def":"A program built for writing software that has an AI assistant baked in — like Cursor or Replit — where you'll actually build your app in Step 2."},{"term":".md file","def":"A plain text file saved with a .md ending, which simply means its contents are written in Markdown formatting."},{"term":"Project folder","def":"A single dedicated folder on your computer where everything for one app — its blueprint, its code, its files — lives together in one tidy place."}],"tips":["Write your PRD in a general chat AI (Claude, ChatGPT, or Gemini), then build in a separate AI code editor — never both in the same tool, so the coding AI's memory stays clear for building.","When the AI asks something confusing, reply 'Explain that like I'm 10 years old' instead of guessing — a wrong guess now becomes a wrong feature later.","Trade vague words for specific ones: say 'clean and modern, white with blue accents, big friendly buttons' instead of 'make it look nice,' and reference familiar things like 'like a simple Google Form.'","Ship the smallest useful version first and park every extra idea in a 'Future Features' note at the bottom of the PRD — a small finished app beats a giant half-built one.","Save the finished blueprint as project-prd.md inside a brand-new folder named for your project, so in Step 2 you can just tell the coding AI 'read project-prd.md and build it.'"]},{"id":"vibe3","n":3,"g":"W","title":"Step 2 — Build It With AI","intro":"You wrote a plan in Step 1. Now comes the moment that feels like magic: you hand that plan to an AI that can actually write software, talk through it in plain English, and watch a working app take shape in front of you. You will not type a single line of code yourself. Your job is to describe, review, and steer — the AI does the typing. This page walks you through exactly what to download, what to click, what to say, and what to expect, minute by minute, as a complete beginner.","tagline":"Turn your written plan into a real, working app by talking to an AI that writes all the code for you.","sections":[{"heading":"What an \"AI IDE\" actually is (and why you need one)","paras":["Up to now you may have used a regular AI chat window like Claude or ChatGPT. Those are wonderful for planning, but they live in a browser tab and can only hand you text to copy. To actually BUILD software, you want a tool that can create files, save them into a folder on your computer, and run them — all while an AI assistant sits right beside your work. That tool is called an IDE.","IDE stands for \"Integrated Development Environment.\" Think of it as Microsoft Word, but for writing code instead of letters. Just as Word gives you a page to type on plus spellcheck and formatting buttons, an IDE gives you a place to write code plus helpful tools for running and organizing it. A regular IDE still expects a human to type the code. An \"agentic IDE\" adds an AI assistant that can read your instructions, write the code itself, and explain what it did. \"Agentic\" just means the AI can take actions on its own — create a file, edit it, fix an error — rather than only chatting.","The most popular agentic IDE for beginners is Cursor. It looks like a normal code editor with a chat panel on the side, and that chat panel is where all your conversation happens. You will never need to understand the code on the screen; you talk to the assistant, it changes the code, and you tell it whether the result is what you wanted. Other good options work the same way: Windsurf is a very similar AI editor, Replit and Bolt.new let you build entirely inside a web browser with nothing to install, and GitHub Copilot is an AI assistant that plugs into editors. For this guide we will use Cursor because it is free for many people and beginner-friendly, but every step translates to the others."]},{"heading":"Setting up Cursor, step by step","paras":["Setting up takes about five minutes and involves nothing scarier than downloading an app. First, open your web browser and go to cursor.com. Click the download button — the site detects whether you are on Windows or Mac and gives you the right file. When the file finishes downloading, double-click it and follow the prompts, exactly like installing any other program. When it is done, open Cursor. You will be asked to sign in; you can create a free account with an email address, and if you happen to have a student email, cursor.com/students gives extended free access, though a free account is plenty to start.","Now the single most important setup step: opening the RIGHT folder. A \"folder\" (also called a \"directory\") is just the same kind of folder you already use to organize documents on your computer. In Step 1 you created a folder for this project and saved your plan inside it as a file called project-prd.md. \"PRD\" stands for Product (or Program) Requirements Document — it is your plain-language blueprint describing what you want built. The .md ending just means it is a simple text file. You need to point Cursor at that exact folder so the AI can read your plan.","To do that, in Cursor look at the top menu and click File, then \"Open Folder.\" A window pops up letting you browse your computer. Navigate to your project folder — the one containing project-prd.md — select it, and confirm. Cursor now \"lives\" inside that folder: any files the AI creates will be saved there, neatly in one place, and the AI can see your plan. On the left side you will see a list of files in that folder; you should spot project-prd.md there. If you do, you are ready. If the folder looks empty, you likely opened the wrong one — just do File then Open Folder again and pick the correct one."]},{"heading":"Starting the coding conversation the right way","paras":["Here is where the real work begins, and the way you start matters enormously. A common beginner mistake is to say \"build me an app\" and let the AI charge ahead making dozens of assumptions. Instead, you want the AI to slow down, read your plan, and ask you questions BEFORE it writes anything. That one habit prevents most of the frustration people run into.","Find the chat panel in Cursor (usually on the right side; if you do not see it, there is a chat icon or you can press the keyboard shortcut it shows you). Paste in the exact prompt below, replacing the bracketed part with a one-line description of your project — for example, \"a simple website where customers can book a haircut appointment\" or \"a tool that turns my messy expense spreadsheet into a clean monthly report.\" Then press Enter and let the AI read.","Notice what this prompt does: it tells the AI where your plan lives, asks it to read carefully, and explicitly forbids it from coding until you are both clear. This is you being the boss — a calm, prepared boss who wants a conversation first. The AI will typically respond with a short summary of your plan (a great way to confirm it understood you) followed by a handful of questions."],"prompt":{"label":"Paste this first to kick off the build","text":"I want to build [BRIEF DESCRIPTION]. I've created a PRD called 'project-prd.md' in this folder. Please read it carefully, then ask me any clarifying questions before you start coding. Important: do NOT start writing code until we're both clear on all requirements."}},{"heading":"Answering the AI's questions (even when you have no idea)","paras":["The AI will now ask you technical-sounding questions. Do not panic — you are allowed to not know the answers, and there is a magic phrase for exactly that situation. The questions usually fall into a few predictable buckets, and knowing what they mean turns them from intimidating into easy.","One classic question is \"should this be a website that runs in a web browser, or a desktop app you install?\" For most beginners, a website is simpler and easier to share, so if you are unsure, that is usually the safe answer. Another is \"do you need to store information in a simple file, or in a database?\" A database is just an organized filing system for data — you need one if many people will use your app or you will store lots of records; a simple file is fine for small, personal projects. A third is \"should people need to log in with accounts, or is it open to anyone?\" Accounts add complexity, so skip them unless your idea truly requires knowing who is who.","When you have a real preference, state it specifically: \"Yes, a website, and I want it to work on phones too.\" When you genuinely do not know — which is completely normal — use the phrase below. This hands the decision to the AI while making sure it picks something appropriate for a first-timer, and it will explain its choice in plain language so you learn as you go.","A useful example: imagine a freelancer building a small invoice generator. The AI asks whether to use a database. The freelancer has no idea, types the \"I don't know\" phrase, and the AI replies: \"For a personal invoice tool used by one person, I'll store data in a simple file — it's easier to set up and back up, and we can upgrade to a database later if you ever need it.\" That is exactly the kind of guided decision you want."],"prompt":{"label":"Say this whenever a question stumps you","text":"I don't know — what do you recommend for a beginner?"}},{"heading":"Telling the AI to build — and how to keep it explaining itself","paras":["Once the questions are settled, it is time to let the AI actually write the code. But you want it to narrate its work so you are never lost. The prompt below does three things at once: it green-lights the build, and it asks the AI to explain each major step, show you the files it creates, and pause when it needs something from you. Paste it in when you are ready.","As the AI works, you will see files appearing in that left-hand list — things with names like index.html, style.css, or app.js. You do not need to understand their contents. The names roughly mean: an .html file is the structure and words of a web page, a .css file controls how it looks (colors, sizes, spacing), and a .js file (JavaScript) makes it do things when clicked. If a file confuses you, just ask the AI \"what does this file do?\" in plain English and it will tell you.","The AI is also creating the \"file structure\" — the arrangement of folders and files that makes up your app. Think of it like the AI setting up a tidy filing cabinet before putting documents in it. You will watch this happen live. Every so often the AI will stop and say something like \"I've built the booking form — please open the preview and tell me if the layout looks right.\" That pause is your cue to look and react."],"prompt":{"label":"Paste this to start the actual build","text":"Great, I'm ready. Please build the project per the PRD. 1) Explain what you're doing at each major step, 2) show me the files you create, 3) tell me when you need input or something to test."}},{"heading":"Your job while the AI codes: review, react, and test","paras":["You are not a passive spectator — you are the director. Your role has four simple parts, none of which require any coding knowledge. First, READ the AI's explanations as they scroll by; you do not need to grasp every detail, just the general story of what is being built. Second, ASK when confused — typing \"what does this file do?\" or \"why did you choose that?\" is not a dumb question, it is exactly how you stay in control and learn.","Third, GIVE FEEDBACK in plain English, the same way you would talk to a designer you hired. You do not describe code; you describe outcomes. Perfectly valid instructions include \"make the buttons bigger,\" \"use a light gray background,\" \"move the total to the top,\" or \"this text is too small on my phone.\" The AI translates your everyday words into the code changes needed. A marketer building a landing page might say \"make the headline bolder and the sign-up button bright orange so it stands out,\" and the AI just does it.","Fourth, TEST when asked. The AI will hand you things to try — usually a preview of your app. Click around like a real user would: fill in the form, press the buttons, try to break it. If something looks wrong or does nothing, describe what happened: \"I clicked Submit and nothing happened\" or \"the date picker shows last month by default.\" That plain-language bug report is all the AI needs to fix it. Here is the honest truth to keep in mind: AI-written code is like work from an eager, fast intern — it is usually functional but unverified, so YOUR testing is what turns a rough draft into something trustworthy. Never assume it works just because it looks finished; click everything yourself."]},{"heading":"How long it takes, saving your work, and one safety rule","paras":["Expectations keep you calm, so here is the honest timeline. A simple project — a one-page website, a small calculator, a tidy report generator — often comes together in ten to thirty minutes. A medium project with a few connected pages or some data storage might take one to three hours. A complex project with many features can span several sessions across days. That is completely normal, and you do not have to finish in one sitting.","This is the beautiful part: your work saves automatically into your project folder, so you can close Cursor and come back whenever you like. When you return, just open Cursor, use File then Open Folder to reopen the same project folder, and pick up the conversation right where you left off. Because everything lives in that one folder, nothing gets lost between sessions. A hobbyist building a personal recipe site might do the layout on a Saturday morning, walk away, and add search the following weekend without missing a beat.","One safety rule matters even at this early stage, so learn it now. Some apps need a \"password\" or an \"API key\" — a secret code that lets your app talk to another service, like a key to a locked door. NEVER let the AI paste a real password or key directly into the code, because code often gets uploaded to the internet later and anyone could read it. Instead, ask the AI to store secrets in a special file called .env (short for \"environment\") and to add that file to another file called .gitignore, which tells the computer \"never upload this.\" You do not need to understand the mechanics — just say the prompt below if your project involves any keys or passwords, and the AI will set it up safely."],"prompt":{"label":"Say this if your project uses any passwords or keys","text":"This project uses a secret key. Please store it in a .env file and add .env to .gitignore so it never gets uploaded. Do not put the key directly in the code."}}],"keyTerms":[{"term":"IDE (Integrated Development Environment)","def":"An app for writing and running code, like Microsoft Word but for software instead of documents."},{"term":"Agentic IDE","def":"An IDE with a built-in AI assistant that can create and edit files and fix errors on its own, not just chat."},{"term":"Cursor","def":"A popular beginner-friendly agentic IDE, downloadable free from cursor.com, where you talk to an AI in a side panel and it writes the code."},{"term":"Folder (directory)","def":"An ordinary place on your computer for organizing files; your project folder holds your plan and all the code the AI writes."},{"term":"PRD (project-prd.md)","def":"Your plain-language blueprint describing what you want built, saved as a simple text file the AI reads before coding."},{"term":"Database","def":"An organized digital filing system for storing lots of data, useful when many people use your app or you keep many records."},{"term":"API key","def":"A secret code that lets your app connect to another online service, which must be kept private and never written directly into code."},{"term":".env and .gitignore files","def":"A .env file safely holds secret keys, and listing it in .gitignore tells the computer never to upload that file to the internet."}],"tips":["Always plan your PRD with a DIFFERENT AI than the one you build with — for example, plan in Claude or ChatGPT, then build in Cursor. A fresh set of eyes catches gaps the coding AI would have just accepted.","Make the AI slow down. The single best habit is forcing it to ask questions before coding; a rushed AI that assumes wrong wastes far more time than a five-minute Q&A up front.","When you do not understand something, type the exact phrase 'explain that like I've never seen code before.' You are allowed to ask for a simpler explanation as many times as you need — the AI never gets tired.","Test like a suspicious user, not a hopeful one. Click every button, submit empty forms, and try to break it — AI code is a functional first draft, and your clicking is what actually proves it works.","Save small milestones by telling the AI 'this version works, please don't change these files unless I ask.' It gives you a safe point to return to if a later change breaks something."]},{"id":"vibe4","n":4,"g":"W","title":"Step 3 — Test, Refine & Troubleshoot","intro":"You've described what you want (Step 1, the PRD) and an AI has written the code (Step 2). Now comes the part that turns \"some code the AI produced\" into \"a thing that actually works\" — you run it, you test it, and you fix what's broken by talking to the AI. This is where most of the real building happens, and the good news is you don't need to understand a single line of code to do it well. Think of the AI as an eager intern who works fast and never gets tired but never double-checks their own work: the code they hand you is usually functional but always unverified. Your job here is to be the tester and the manager, not the programmer.","tagline":"Learn how to run your project, test every feature, and fix anything that's broken just by describing the problem clearly to an AI — no coding required.","sections":[{"heading":"First, actually run it — ask the AI exactly how","paras":["Before you can test anything, you have to see your project running. \"Running\" software just means making it actually go — turning the code the AI wrote into a working thing on your screen, like a webpage you can click or an app you can type into. Right now your project is probably just text files sitting on your computer; running it brings them to life. The single most useful move here is to let the AI tell you how, because the exact steps depend on what you built and which tool you used.","Paste the prompt below to whichever AI wrote your code, then follow its steps literally, one at a time. The AI knows what it built, so its instructions will match your specific project. Do not skip a step because it looks obvious — for a beginner, \"obvious\" is where things quietly go wrong.","Depending on your setup, the answer will be something simple. If you built a plain website, it may just say \"double-click the file named index.html and it will open in your web browser\" (the browser is Chrome, Safari, Edge, or Firefox — the program you use to visit websites). If you're using Replit (a tool that builds and runs projects entirely inside your web browser, so nothing gets installed on your machine), the instruction is usually just \"click the green Run button at the top.\" If you're using Cursor (a free-for-students AI code editor at cursor.com/students — an editor is the program where code lives and gets edited) or Claude Code (an AI agent that works inside the terminal), the AI might tell you to run a command in the terminal.","The terminal is the black-or-white text window where you type commands instead of clicking buttons — it looks intimidating but it's just a place to paste the exact line the AI gives you and press Enter. A very common one for web projects is a command that starts a tiny local web server (a program that shows your site at a web address only your computer can see, usually something like localhost:3000). When the AI gives you a terminal command, treat it exactly like a prompt: copy it, paste it, press Enter, and if anything looks wrong, copy whatever the terminal printed back and paste that to the AI. A fast shortcut for many web projects: Claude's Artifacts feature (claude.ai) and ChatGPT's Canvas both show a live preview of a webpage right beside the chat, so you can see it running instantly without touching a terminal at all."],"prompt":{"label":"Ask the AI how to run and test your project","text":"The code looks good! How do I run and test it? Give me the exact steps for my setup, assume I have never done this before, and tell me what a successful result should look like on screen."}},{"heading":"Build a testing checklist straight from your PRD","paras":["\"Testing\" is not mysterious: it means you use every part of your project like a real person would and check whether each part does what you promised it would do. The best source of what to test is the PRD you already wrote in Step 1 — your Program Requirements Document, the plain-language blueprint that lists every feature. Go through it line by line and turn each feature into a yes/no question. That list is your testing checklist, and you don't check a project off as \"done\" until every box is a confident yes.","A good checklist mixes four kinds of checks. First, does it load without errors — does the thing open and appear on screen without a blank page, a frozen screen, or a scary red message? Second, does every button and control work — click every button, fill in every box, toggle every switch, and confirm each one does the thing it's supposed to. Third, is the logic correct — if your project does any math or decisions, verify the answers by hand. If a freelancer builds an invoice tool, they should type in two items at $50 each and confirm the total says $100, not trust that it looks about right. Fourth, does it look good and work everywhere — especially on a phone, since most people will open it there.","Test on a real phone, not just your computer. Open the project on your phone's browser (or, in Replit and similar tools, use the preview and shrink the window narrow to fake a phone screen). A layout that looks perfect on a wide laptop can be a jumbled, unusable mess on a narrow phone, and you'll only catch that by looking. A hobbyist sharing a recipe site, or a marketer sharing a landing page, will have most visitors arrive on a phone — so phone testing isn't optional.","Be systematic and a little bit mean to your own project. Try the wrong things on purpose: leave a required box empty and hit submit, type letters where a number goes, click the same button five times fast, enter a giant number. Real users will do all of this, and it's far better that you find the broken spots now than that a customer finds them later. Every problem you uncover just becomes the next item you hand to the AI to fix."],"bullets":["Loads cleanly? Opens with no blank screen, no freeze, no red error message.","Every button works? Each button, link, form field, and toggle does exactly what the PRD says.","Numbers correct? Any total, calculation, or decision produces the right answer when you check it by hand.","Good on a phone? Text is readable, nothing overflows the screen, buttons are tappable, nothing overlaps.","Survives misuse? Empty fields, wrong input types, and rapid clicks don't crash it or give nonsense."]},{"heading":"The refinement loop: the heartbeat of vibe coding","paras":["Here is the single most important idea on this page: you almost never get a perfect project on the first try, and that is completely normal. Real building happens in a loop. You test, you find one issue, you describe that issue clearly to the AI, the AI fixes it, you re-test to confirm the fix worked, and then you repeat — over and over — until every item on your checklist is a yes. This is called the refinement loop, and it's the actual craft of vibe coding. Professional developers work in exactly this loop; you're just doing it in plain English instead of code.","Change one thing at a time. It is tempting to dump five problems on the AI at once, but if you do and something breaks, you won't know which fix caused it. Fix one issue, re-test, confirm it's better, then move to the next. This discipline is what separates a smooth build from a frustrating one where the project seems to get worse with every message. Slow is smooth, and smooth is fast.","The quality of a fix depends almost entirely on the quality of your description. This is the skill to develop, and it's a communication skill, not a technical one. A vague complaint like \"it's broken\" or \"the button doesn't work\" gives the AI almost nothing to work with, and you'll get a vague guess back. A specific report gives the AI everything it needs to fix the problem on the first try. Good feedback answers three questions every time: what did you do, what did you expect to happen, and what actually happened instead — plus any exact error text and which device and browser you were on.","The most powerful thing you can hand the AI is an error message copied word for word. Many projects have a hidden diagnostics panel called the console — a behind-the-scenes log where a webpage records its own errors. In any browser you open it by pressing the F12 key (or right-click the page, choose Inspect, then click the Console tab). If something isn't working, glance at the console: red text there is the project literally telling you what went wrong, in a language the AI reads fluently. Copy that red text and paste it into your report. You don't need to understand it — the AI does."],"prompt":{"label":"A well-formed bug report to paste to the AI","text":"When I click Submit nothing happens. I expected it to save my entry and show a confirmation message. Instead the screen just sits there. I'm on Chrome on an iPhone. Here's the error from the browser console: [paste the exact red error text here]. Please fix this and tell me in plain English what was wrong."}},{"heading":"The 10 troubleshooting scenarios (part 1): communication and errors","paras":["Almost every problem a beginner hits falls into one of ten familiar situations. Learn to recognize which one you're in and you'll always know what to say next. Here are the first five, which are mostly about communicating with the AI and dealing with error messages.","Scenario 1 — the AI misunderstands what you want. The fix is to be more specific and to give a concrete example of something that already exists. Instead of \"make the quiz more fun,\" say \"make it work like Kahoot, where each question has a countdown timer and points for answering fast.\" Naming a well-known thing the AI already knows (\"like Kahoot,\" \"like a Google Form,\" \"like the Spotify player\") is a shortcut to a shared picture. If it still misses, break your request into one tiny step at a time instead of one big change.","Scenario 2 — you get an error message. Do not panic and do not just type \"there's an error.\" Copy the full error text, exactly and completely, and paste it along with what you were doing when it appeared. The wording of an error is the single most valuable clue there is; truncating it or paraphrasing it throws away the exact information the AI needs. Pair it with context — \"this appeared right after I clicked Save on the second form\" — and the AI can usually pinpoint the cause immediately.","Scenario 3 — it works on your computer but not on your phone. This is about \"responsive\" design, which means a layout that automatically rearranges itself to fit whatever screen it's on. Just ask for it directly. Scenario 4 — the AI wrote code you don't understand and it makes you nervous. That's fine and expected; ask it to explain in plain terms. There's no shame in this — asking is how you stay in control of your own project instead of blindly trusting output you can't read.","Scenario 5 — the AI keeps making the same mistake no matter how you rephrase. Sometimes the conversation itself gets stuck in a rut, because the AI keeps re-reading its own earlier wrong answers in the chat and repeating them. Three cures: start a brand-new chat with a clean slate and describe the goal fresh; be forcefully explicit about what to avoid and why (\"Do NOT use a pop-up alert; use an inline message on the page, because pop-ups get blocked\"); or simply take the same request to a different AI entirely. If Claude is stuck, paste the exact same problem into ChatGPT or Google Gemini — a fresh model often sees the fix instantly."],"prompt":{"label":"Scenario 3 — make it work on phones","text":"This looks great on my computer but it's broken and overlapping on my phone. Please make it fully responsive so the layout adjusts and works well on mobile screens, and tell me how to double-check it on my phone."}},{"heading":"The 10 troubleshooting scenarios (part 2): changes, breakage, and understanding","paras":["Scenario 6 — you want a feature that wasn't in your original PRD. Building often gives you new ideas, and that's a good thing, not cheating. You don't have to rewrite the whole plan; just describe the new feature plainly and say why you want it, so the AI understands the goal and not only the literal request. \"Add a button that copies the result to the clipboard, because my users will want to paste it into an email\" tells the AI both the what and the why, and the why helps it make better choices.","Scenario 7 — a change broke something that used to work. This is the classic one and it's why you change one thing at a time. If the last edit clearly broke a feature, the fastest fix is to undo just that change. Ask the AI to revert its last change (revert means put it back the way it was before). This is also exactly what version control saves you from — if you connected your project to GitHub (a free website that stores your project and keeps a full history of every saved version), you can restore the previous working version with a couple of clicks even if the AI can't. Saving a version to GitHub at each point where the project works is like a video-game checkpoint you can always return to.","Scenario 8 — everything seems to work but you're not sure the code underneath is actually any good. Remember the eager-intern rule: functional is not the same as well-built. Ask the AI to review its own work for quality and to explain its suggestions, so you learn something and can decide what's worth doing. Scenario 9 — you hit a word or concept you simply don't understand, whether in an error, in the AI's explanation, or in this very guide. The rule here is absolute: always ask. Never nod along past a term you don't know. Asking the AI to define it with an example from your own project is the fastest way to learn, and it costs nothing.","Scenario 10 — you share it and other people can't figure out how to use it. Something obvious to you, the builder, is often a mystery to a first-time visitor. The fix is to add guidance right on the screen: clear instructions, helpful placeholder text in boxes, and tooltips (the little hint that appears when you hover over something). A small-business owner who builds a booking tool should have it tell a first-time customer exactly what to do, with no verbal explanation from them required. If people need you standing next to them to use it, it isn't finished yet."],"prompt":{"label":"Scenario 7 — revert a change that broke a feature","text":"That last change broke [name the feature that stopped working] — it was working before. Please revert that last change so [feature] works again, and leave everything else exactly as it was."}},{"heading":"When you're stuck: fresh chats, second opinions, and never guessing","paras":["Two habits will rescue you from almost every dead end. The first is the fresh chat. AI chats have a kind of short-term memory of everything said so far, and once a conversation has gone in circles, that memory works against you — the AI keeps anchoring to its own earlier wrong turns. Opening a new chat wipes the slate. Restate the goal cleanly, paste the current code and the specific problem, and you'll often get in two messages what twenty messages in the old chat couldn't produce.","The second habit is the second opinion. You are not married to one AI. If Claude keeps missing, hand the identical problem to ChatGPT, Google Gemini, or a browser tool like Replit or Bolt.new (a tool that builds a working web app from a description right in your browser). Different models have different strengths, and a stubborn bug that one can't crack often falls in seconds to another. Switching is free and fast — treat it as a normal move, not an admission of failure.","Above all, never guess past something you don't understand — always ask. This is the golden rule of the whole loop, and it applies to error messages, to the AI's own explanations, and to any jargon you meet. Curiosity here is a superpower, not a weakness. Every question you ask makes you a more capable builder, and the AI will happily explain the same idea five different ways until it clicks. The prompt below works for literally any unfamiliar word.","One security habit belongs in every refinement loop, because it's easy to get wrong and painful to fix later: never let the AI put a password or an API key directly into your code. An API key is a secret password that lets your project use an outside service (like an AI model, a maps service, or a payments provider), and if it ends up in your code and that code gets uploaded to GitHub, strangers can find it and run up charges in your name. The safe pattern is to keep secrets in a separate file called .env and to add that file to a list called .gitignore, which tells GitHub to never upload it. If any AI ever writes a real key straight into your code, stop and ask it to move the key into a .env file and add .env to .gitignore instead."],"prompt":{"label":"Scenario 9 — ask what any unfamiliar term means","text":"What is a [term you don't understand]? Explain it simply, like I'm brand new to programming, and give me an example of how it's being used in this specific project."}},{"heading":"How you know you're actually done","paras":["\"Done\" is not a feeling; it's a set of conditions you can check off. You are finished when four things are all true at once. Every feature in your PRD works — you went down the whole checklist and each item is a confident yes, not a hopeful maybe. It looks polished — the spacing, colors, and text feel intentional and clean, not like a rough draft. You've tested thoroughly — on a computer and on a phone, with normal input and with deliberately wrong input, and it held up. And other people can use it without your help — you handed it to someone cold and they figured it out from the on-screen guidance alone.","Notice what \"done\" does not require: it does not require that you understand every line of code, and it does not require that the code be flawless by some professional standard. For a project you built to solve your own problem or share with your audience, working, polished, tested, and usable is a genuine finish line. You can always keep improving later, but you've crossed from \"a thing I'm building\" to \"a thing that works.\"","When you reach that line, publish it so the world (or just your customers, or your friends) can actually use it. Free hosting — a service that puts your project on the real internet at a shareable web address for nothing — is one prompt away. GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, and Replit all do this, and you can ask your AI to walk you through whichever fits your project, step by step, exactly the way you asked it to help you run the project at the start of this page. The same clear-communication habit that carried you through testing will carry you through launch.","Then celebrate, because you did something most people assume is impossible for a non-programmer: you shipped working software by describing what you wanted in plain English and refining it through conversation. That's the whole promise of vibe coding, and you just proved it works. The next project will be faster, because now you know the loop."],"prompt":{"label":"Ask the AI to help you publish it for free","text":"My project is finished and tested. I want to publish it online for free so others can use it. Recommend the simplest free hosting option for this project (like GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, or Replit) and walk me through every step, assuming I've never deployed anything before."}}],"keyTerms":[{"term":"Running (a project)","def":"Making your code actually go — turning the text files the AI wrote into a working webpage or app you can see and interact with on screen."},{"term":"Terminal","def":"The plain text window where you type or paste commands and press Enter instead of clicking buttons; the AI gives you the exact line to run."},{"term":"Console","def":"A hidden diagnostics panel in every web browser (open it with F12) where a webpage logs its own errors — red text there is the project telling you exactly what went wrong."},{"term":"Error message","def":"The text a program shows when something goes wrong; copied word-for-word and pasted to the AI, it's the single most valuable clue for getting a fast fix."},{"term":"Refinement loop","def":"The core rhythm of vibe coding: test, find one issue, describe it clearly to the AI, let it fix, re-test, and repeat until everything works."},{"term":"Responsive design","def":"A layout that automatically rearranges itself to fit any screen size, so a site that looks right on a laptop also looks right on a phone."},{"term":"Revert","def":"Undoing a change to put the project back exactly the way it was before — the fastest fix when a recent edit broke something that used to work."},{"term":"GitHub","def":"A free website that stores your project and keeps a full history of every saved version, so you can always restore an earlier version that worked, like a checkpoint."},{"term":".env file and .gitignore","def":"A .env file holds secrets like passwords and API keys separately from your code, and listing it in a .gitignore file tells GitHub never to upload it, keeping your secrets private."},{"term":"Free hosting","def":"A service such as GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, or Replit that puts your finished project on the real internet at a shareable web address at no cost."}],"tips":["Change one thing at a time, then re-test. If you fix five things at once and something breaks, you won't know which fix caused it — and the project can quietly get worse with every message.","Copy error messages in full, never paraphrased. Open the browser console with F12, copy the exact red text, and paste it to the AI with a note about what you were doing when it appeared.","Always test on a real phone, not just your laptop. Most people will open your project on a phone, and a layout that's perfect on a wide screen can be an unusable mess on a narrow one.","When the AI gets stuck in a rut, start a fresh chat or switch AIs entirely. A clean conversation or a different model (Claude, ChatGPT, Gemini) often cracks a bug the old thread kept missing.","Save a version to GitHub every time the project works. It's a checkpoint you can always return to — if a later change breaks everything, you restore the last good version in a couple of clicks.","Never let the AI write a real password or API key straight into your code. Have it store secrets in a .env file and add .env to .gitignore, so your secrets are never uploaded when you publish."]},{"id":"vibe5","n":5,"g":"W","title":"Step 4 — Save, Share & Publish","intro":"You built something with AI, and right now it lives in a folder on your computer where only you can see it. This is the step where you give it a safety net and then a front door: a safety net so a bad AI edit can never wipe out your working version, and a front door so anyone in the world can use your project by clicking a link. You will not memorize commands. You will describe what you want in plain English, let the AI do the technical parts, and click a few buttons. By the end you will have a live web address you can text to a friend, put on your business cards, or link in your bio.","tagline":"Turn the project sitting on your laptop into a live link the whole internet can open, and never lose a working version again.","sections":[{"heading":"Why you save before you share (and what a 'time machine' really means)","paras":["Here is a story that happens to almost everyone who vibe codes. Your app works. You are thrilled. You ask the AI for 'one more small change,' and something breaks. You ask it to fix the break, and now two other things are broken. Ten minutes later you would give anything to go back to the version that worked twenty minutes ago, but it is gone. This step exists so that never costs you more than one click.","The fix is called version control, and the honest way to picture it is a time machine for your project. Instead of one folder that silently changes every time the AI edits a file, version control keeps a numbered stack of saved snapshots. Every snapshot is frozen and permanent. If today's work turns into a mess, you calmly say 'take me back to yesterday's snapshot,' and your project rewinds to exactly how it was, down to the last comma. Nothing is lost, because nothing was ever overwritten.","If you have ever used Track Changes in Microsoft Word, or looked at the version history of a Google Doc, you already understand the feeling: a running record of every change, with the power to undo any of them and see who changed what and when. Version control is that same idea, built for the files that make up software, and far more powerful because it can rewind your entire project at once, not just one document.","The tool that creates these snapshots is called Git (rhymes with 'sit'). Git runs quietly on your own computer and does the actual snapshotting. You will almost never type Git commands yourself; your AI does that. What matters is the mental model: Git is the machine that takes the photographs of your project. Where those photographs get stored safely off your laptop is the next piece."]},{"heading":"The five words that unlock everything: repo, commit, push, pull, branch","paras":["Version control has a small vocabulary, and once these five words click, every tutorial and every AI reply about saving your work suddenly makes sense. None of them are complicated; they just have nerdy names. Read this table once, then keep moving. You will pick the words up for real by using them, not by studying them.","The most important pairing to remember is commit and push. A commit is a snapshot saved on your own computer. A push copies your saved snapshots up to the internet so they are backed up and shareable. You can commit ten times on a plane with no Wi-Fi; the moment you land and reconnect, one push sends all ten snapshots up at once. Commit = save a photo. Push = mail copies of your photos to the vault in the cloud.","That cloud vault is GitHub, a free website at github.com. GitHub is where your project's folder-plus-history lives online so it is safe if your laptop dies, and so other people (or free publishing services) can reach it. A quick name clarification that trips up every beginner: Git is the tool on your computer; GitHub is the website in the cloud. They work together and sound alike, but they are two different things. There are competitors like GitLab and Bitbucket, but GitHub is the biggest and the one every AI tool assumes by default, so start there."],"table":{"headers":["Word","Plain-English meaning","Everyday analogy"],"rows":[["Repository (repo)","Your project folder plus its entire saved history, treated as one unit.","A photo album: the pictures and the order they go in, all in one book."],["Commit","One saved snapshot of your project at a moment in time, with a short note describing it.","Snapping and labeling one photo: 'Added the contact form.'"],["Push","Upload your saved snapshots from your computer to GitHub in the cloud.","Mailing copies of your photos to a safe-deposit box."],["Pull","Download the latest snapshots from GitHub back to your computer.","Getting fresh copies mailed back to you so you're up to date."],["Branch","A safe parallel copy of your project where you can experiment without touching the version that works.","A sandbox draft of your book you can scribble in, then keep or throw away."]]}},{"heading":"The easiest setup on earth: let the AI do all of it","paras":["Here is the part that makes this genuinely painless. You do not need to learn Git. You do not need to understand the commands. You open the same AI coding tool you have been building with (Cursor, Claude Code, Replit, Windsurf, or whichever you chose) and you paste one clear request. The AI runs the commands for you in the terminal, explains each one in plain language, and stops if it needs a decision from you.","The terminal, by the way, is the plain black-or-white text window where typed commands are run instead of clicking buttons. Your AI tool has one built in. When the AI 'runs a command,' that is where it happens. You will watch text scroll by; you do not have to type into it yourself. If a website called github.com opens and asks you to log in or approve a connection, that is normal and expected, just say yes.","Paste the prompt below into your AI coding tool. It handles all five setup jobs at once: it turns your folder into a repo, creates a protective list of files that should never be uploaded, saves your first snapshot, creates the matching project on GitHub, and pushes everything up. Notice it explicitly asks the AI to explain each step, so you learn a little as you go instead of watching mystery text fly by.","One line in that prompt deserves special attention: the .gitignore file (said 'git-ignore'). This is a small text file that lists things Git should pretend do not exist and never upload, things like giant temporary folders, and, crucially, any file holding your secret passwords or API keys. An API key is a private password that lets your app talk to a paid service like an AI provider or a payment processor; if you accidentally publish one to GitHub, strangers can run up charges on your account within minutes. The .gitignore is your seatbelt against exactly that, which is why it is step 2, before anything gets uploaded."],"prompt":{"label":"Paste this into your AI coding tool to set up version control","text":"I want to set up version control with GitHub. Please help me: 1) initialize a Git repository here, 2) create a .gitignore file so we don't upload junk or secrets, 3) make my first commit, 4) connect it to a new GitHub repository, 5) push my code. Explain each step."}},{"heading":"Prefer buttons over typed commands? Use GitHub Desktop","paras":["If watching a terminal scroll makes you tense, there is a friendlier path that never asks you to type a single command. GitHub Desktop is a free app from GitHub itself (download it at desktop.github.com; the current version as of mid-2026 is 3.6). It gives version control a normal window with buttons. Saving a snapshot becomes: type a short note, click a blue Commit button. Backing it up online becomes: click Push. That is genuinely the whole thing.","The typical rhythm looks like this. You make changes to your project in your AI tool. You switch over to GitHub Desktop, which shows you a clean side-by-side of exactly what changed, old text in red, new text in green, so you can see the AI's work at a glance. You type a plain note like 'Added the pricing page,' click Commit to save the snapshot, then click Push to send it to the cloud. Repeat whenever you finish something that works. There is no wrong moment to commit; more snapshots means more places you can safely rewind to.","A realistic example: a freelance photographer builds a portfolio site with AI. Every time she adds a gallery she likes, she pops into GitHub Desktop, commits with a note like 'Added the wedding gallery,' and pushes. Two weeks later an AI edit mangles her homepage layout. Instead of panicking, she opens the history in GitHub Desktop, finds the snapshot from before the mess, and restores it. Ten seconds, zero commands, disaster averted. The visual app and the AI-driven terminal approach do the exact same thing under the hood, so pick whichever feels calmer to you; you can even use both."]},{"heading":"Free premium tools worth grabbing (student pack and Copilot)","paras":["GitHub gives away a surprising amount of paid software for free through a program called the GitHub Student Developer Pack (education.github.com), and despite the name it is worth a look for a wider audience than you might think. Once GitHub verifies you, the pack unlocks free access to a long list of tools that normally cost money, things like extra cloud hosting credit, domain names, design apps, and developer services. If you qualify, it is one of the best free-stuff deals on the internet, and it takes about ten minutes to apply.","The headline perk is GitHub Copilot, an AI assistant that lives inside your code editor and suggests or writes code as you go, essentially autocomplete on steroids that can draft whole chunks of your project from a plain-English comment. Copilot normally runs about ten dollars a month, but it is free for people who verify through GitHub's education program. Even outside that program there is now a free Copilot tier with monthly limits, so you can try it at no cost before deciding whether the paid plan earns its keep.","Two more free options in this neighborhood are worth knowing. Cursor, a popular AI code editor, offers free access for verified students at cursor.com/students. And you never need any of these to succeed; the free chat tools you already use, like Claude at claude.ai and ChatGPT at chat.openai.com, are more than enough to vibe code a real project from start to finish. Think of the pack and Copilot as nice upgrades, not requirements. Grab them if you qualify, shrug and move on if you do not."]},{"heading":"Publishing your project: from private folder to public link","paras":["Publishing, also called deploying, means putting your finished project on the internet at a real web address so anyone can open it in a browser with nothing to download and nothing to install. This is the moment your project stops being a thing on your laptop and becomes a thing in the world. You send someone a link like your-project.netlify.app and it just works on their phone, their laptop, anywhere. For most beginner projects, this is completely free.","The magic trick that makes modern publishing effortless is called continuous deployment, and it is worth understanding because it turns updating your live site into a non-event. You connect a hosting service to your GitHub repo one time. From then on, every time you push a new snapshot to GitHub, the host automatically notices, rebuilds your site, and updates the live version within a minute or two, no re-uploading, no re-publishing. You fix a typo, push, and the public site fixes itself. Your GitHub push becomes the single button that both backs up and publishes your work.","There are four solid free hosts, and the right one depends on what you built. GitHub Pages is the simplest and is perfect for a plain website (a personal page, a portfolio, a small business landing page); if your project is already on GitHub, turning on Pages is a couple of clicks. Netlify and Vercel are a small notch more capable and are the go-to choice for interactive web apps; you connect your GitHub repo, and both give you that automatic-publish-on-every-push behavior on a genuinely free tier (roughly 100 GB of monthly traffic, plenty for a project finding its first users). And if you built your project inside Replit in the browser, Replit can host it directly, so you never leave the tool you started in.","Do not agonize over the choice. Describe your project to your AI and let it recommend and walk you through the best fit. The prompt below does exactly that; fill in the bracket with a one-line description of what you made ('a one-page site for my bakery with my menu and hours,' 'a tip-splitting calculator,' 'a searchable list of my favorite hiking trails'). The AI will name the best free host for your specific case and give you click-by-click directions, including how to connect GitHub so future updates publish themselves."],"prompt":{"label":"Paste this into your AI to deploy your project for free","text":"Help me deploy this online for free. The project is [description]. Recommend the best free host and walk me through it step by step."},"table":{"headers":["Free host","Best for","Standout feature"],"rows":[["GitHub Pages","A plain website or portfolio already on GitHub","Simplest possible setup; a few clicks if your code is already there"],["Netlify","Interactive web apps and small tools","Connect your repo once; auto-publishes on every push, great free tier"],["Vercel","Web apps, especially fast, modern ones","Same push-to-publish magic; polished dashboard and instant previews"],["Replit","Projects you built in the Replit browser tool","Host straight from where you built it, no move required"]]}},{"heading":"The honest guardrails: treat AI code like an eager intern's work","paras":["Everything above makes shipping feel effortless, and it mostly is, but a little honesty here will save you real pain. AI-written code is best thought of as work handed in by an eager, fast, tireless intern: usually functional, occasionally confidently wrong, and always worth a second look before you trust it in front of real people. It compiles and it runs, which is not the same as it being correct or safe. Before you share a link widely, click through your live site yourself and try to break it the way a stranger would.","The single most important safety rule bears repeating because the consequences are the harshest: never let the AI write passwords, API keys, or any secret directly into your code files. If it offers to, stop it and ask it to use a .env file instead. A .env file (said 'dot-e-n-v') is a separate little file that holds your secrets, kept out of your code and, critically, listed in .gitignore so it is never uploaded to GitHub. Publishing a secret to a public repo is the classic beginner disaster; bots scan GitHub for exposed keys constantly and can drain a linked account fast. Ask your AI point-blank: 'Are there any secrets, passwords, or API keys hardcoded in this project? If so, move them to a .env file and make sure .gitignore excludes it.'","A few smaller pitfalls round this out. When something breaks after an edit, resist the urge to pile on more fixes; that is how one broken thing becomes three. Instead, use the safety net you built: rewind to your last working snapshot and try again from there. Commit often and with honest little notes, because a snapshot named 'Working checkout page' is a lifeline six edits later, while ten snapshots named 'update' are useless. And remember free tiers are generous but not infinite; if a project unexpectedly goes viral you may hit a monthly traffic limit, which is a wonderful problem to have and a five-minute upgrade to solve. None of this should scare you off. Save early, keep secrets out, verify before you brag, and you will ship something real today."]}],"keyTerms":[{"term":"Version control","def":"A system that saves numbered snapshots of your whole project over time so you can undo mistakes and return to any earlier working version."},{"term":"Git","def":"The tool that runs on your own computer and actually creates the saved snapshots of your project; your AI usually operates it for you."},{"term":"GitHub","def":"A free website (github.com) that stores your project and its history online so it's backed up and shareable, and where free hosts connect to publish it."},{"term":"Repository (repo)","def":"Your project's folder together with its entire saved history, treated as one bundle that lives both on your computer and on GitHub."},{"term":"Commit","def":"A single saved snapshot of your project at one moment, tagged with a short note describing what changed."},{"term":"Push / Pull","def":"Push uploads your saved snapshots from your computer to GitHub; pull downloads the latest snapshots from GitHub back to your computer."},{"term":"Terminal","def":"The plain text window where typed commands run instead of clicking buttons; your AI tool has one built in and types into it for you."},{"term":".gitignore file","def":"A small text file listing things Git should never upload to GitHub, such as junk folders and any file containing secret passwords or API keys."},{"term":"API key","def":"A private password that lets your app use a paid outside service; if published by accident, strangers can run up charges, so it must be kept secret."},{"term":".env file","def":"A separate file that stores your secrets (keys and passwords) away from your code and is listed in .gitignore so it is never uploaded."},{"term":"Deploy / Publish","def":"Putting your finished project on the internet at a real web address so anyone can open it in a browser with nothing to download."},{"term":"Continuous deployment","def":"A setup where connecting a host to your GitHub repo once makes your live site auto-update every time you push a new snapshot."}],"tips":["Commit early and often with honest little notes ('Working contact form,' not 'update'). Each named snapshot is a place you can safely rewind to; a wall of vague 'update' commits is useless when you actually need to go back.","Before sharing your live link, click through the whole site yourself on a phone and try to break it. AI code runs like an eager intern's work: functional but unverified, so you are the quality check.","Ask your AI point-blank before publishing: 'Are any secrets, passwords, or API keys hardcoded here? Move them to a .env file and make sure .gitignore excludes it.' A leaked key on a public repo can drain a linked account within minutes.","When an edit breaks something, don't stack more fixes on top. Restore your last working snapshot and start that change again from clean ground; that one habit prevents most vibe-coding meltdowns.","Connect your host to GitHub once so pushing becomes your single publish button, then bookmark your live URL and re-open it after each push to confirm the update actually went live."]},{"id":"vibe6","n":6,"g":"T","title":"Vibe Coding With Cursor","tagline":"By the end of this page you'll be able to download one free app, describe the thing you want to build in plain English, and watch an AI write real, working software for you.","intro":"\"Vibe coding\" means building software by describing what you want in ordinary English and letting an AI write the actual code, then improving it through back-and-forth conversation — no prior programming knowledge required. (The term was coined by AI researcher Andrej Karpathy.) The single best tool for a complete beginner to do this is Cursor, a free app that is basically a smart writing surface for code with a powerful AI assistant living right inside it. This page is a slow, hand-held, click-by-click walkthrough: what Cursor is, how to install it, how to talk to it, and how to go from a blank folder to a working app — assuming you have never opened a code editor or typed a command in your life. Every unfamiliar word is explained the first time it appears, and gathered again at the bottom for quick reference.","sections":[{"heading":"What Cursor actually is (in plain language)","paras":["Cursor is a free program you install on your computer, from the website cursor.com. Its official label is an \"agentic IDE.\" Let's unpack that phrase because it sounds intimidating and isn't. An IDE (Integrated Development Environment) is just the professional name for the window where people write and organize the files that make up a piece of software — think of it as a supercharged version of a plain text editor like Notepad or Microsoft Word, but built for code instead of essays. The word \"agentic\" means it has an AI assistant that can act on your behalf — not just answer questions, but actually create files, write code into them, change code that's already there, and fix its own mistakes when you point them out. So an agentic IDE is a code workshop with a capable AI helper built directly into it.","Cursor is built on top of a widely used, free editor from Microsoft called VS Code (short for Visual Studio Code). That matters for one comforting reason: VS Code is the most popular code editor in the world, so Cursor inherits a decade of polish, and almost anything you ever read online about VS Code also applies to Cursor. Cursor's creators took that solid foundation and wove an AI assistant through every part of it. You are not learning some fragile experiment — you're using a mature, familiar tool with a modern brain bolted on.","Here is what the AI inside Cursor can do for you, in concrete terms. It can read and understand your entire project at once — every file, and how they connect — which is a genuinely big deal, because most chat tools only see the words you paste into them. It can generate brand-new code from a plain-English request (\"make a page that shows my bakery's menu with prices\"). It can edit existing code across several files at the same time when you ask for a change. It can explain any piece of code back to you in beginner language (\"what does this line do?\"). And as you type, it quietly autocompletes — it guesses the next line and offers it to you in faint gray text, which you accept by pressing the Tab key. You will rarely need that last feature as a pure vibe coder, but it's there.","A useful mental model for the whole experience: the AI is like an eager, fast, tireless intern who has read every programming manual ever written but has never met you or your project before. It will happily produce a working result in seconds — but that result is unverified. Interns make confident mistakes. Your job in vibe coding is not to write code; it's to describe clearly, then look at what came back and say \"that's not quite right, the button should be blue and it should also send me an email.\" The conversation is the work."]},{"heading":"Why Cursor is the top pick for a total beginner","paras":["There are several AI coding tools, and this Lab covers many of them — GitHub Copilot (an AI helper that plugs into VS Code, free for verified students and teachers at education.github.com, otherwise about $10 a month), Claude at claude.ai (which can build small live-previewing mini-apps called Artifacts and also has a terminal-based agent called Claude Code), ChatGPT at chat.openai.com (with a side-by-side editing view called Canvas), Google Gemini, and browser-based builders like Replit, Bolt.new, and Windsurf where you never install anything. They're all good. But for someone who has never coded, Cursor hits a rare combination that makes it the recommended starting point.","First, it was designed from the ground up for AI coding, so the AI is not an add-on you have to configure — it's the main event, sitting in a panel on the right, ready the moment you open the app. Second, it's genuinely free to get started: everyone gets a free tier (roughly 2,000 autocompletions plus around 50 \"slow\" premium AI requests per month at the time of writing — enough to build real things and decide if you love it), and students get free access to the paid features through cursor.com/students by verifying with a student email. If you're not a student, the paid plan called Pro is $20 a month for effectively unlimited use — but you do not need to spend a cent to follow this entire page. Third, the experience is clean and seamless: the app reads your whole project automatically, so you're not constantly copying and pasting code back and forth between a chat window and an editor the way you would with a general chatbot.","To be honest about the trade-off: because Cursor is a real desktop app, you do have to download and install it, and you'll be looking at a screen with panels and files rather than a single chat box. Browser tools like Replit or Bolt.new skip the install entirely and can feel friendlier for a five-minute experiment. But the moment your project grows past a single file — the moment you want the AI to see your whole app and make coordinated changes across it — Cursor's ability to understand the entire project is exactly what you'll wish you had. It's the tool you won't outgrow, which is why it's worth the small setup cost up front."]},{"heading":"Before you open Cursor: plan with a PRD (and use a different AI to write it)","paras":["The single most important habit in vibe coding is this: plan before you build. You do that by writing a PRD, which stands for Product Requirements Document (you'll also see it called a Program Requirements Document — same idea). Don't let the formal name scare you. A PRD is simply a plain-English blueprint of what you want — a description a smart friend could read and understand exactly what you're trying to make. It's an ordinary document, written in normal sentences, saved as a file. That's it.","Why bother? Because an AI builds exactly what you describe, and a vague description produces a vague, wrong app. Ten minutes spent writing down \"here is what this thing is, here is who uses it, here is every screen, here is what each button does\" saves you an hour of frustrated back-and-forth later. A freelance photographer who wants a simple portfolio site should write down the sections (Home, Gallery, About, Contact), the vibe (\"clean, lots of white space, big photos\"), and the must-haves (\"works on phones,\" \"a contact form that emails me\") before a single line of code exists. That document becomes the shared understanding between you and the AI.","Here's the key technique that beginners miss: plan the PRD with a DIFFERENT AI than the one you'll build with. Open a regular chatbot — Claude at claude.ai, ChatGPT, or Google Gemini — and have a conversation to develop your idea into a solid PRD. Then take that finished PRD to Cursor to actually build it. Using two different AIs gives you a second perspective; the planning AI catches gaps and asks questions the building AI would have just plowed past. Think of it as one AI acting as your thoughtful project manager and a second one as your fast-typing developer. Below is a prompt you can paste into any chatbot to generate your first PRD — just replace the description in brackets with your own idea.","Once the chatbot gives you a PRD you're happy with, save it as a plain text file named project-prd.md. The .md ending stands for Markdown, which is just a simple way of writing formatted text (using symbols like # for a heading and - for a bullet) that both humans and AIs read easily. You can create this file inside Cursor itself in a moment, or save it from any text editor — the content matters, not the tool you typed it in."],"prompt":{"label":"Paste into Claude, ChatGPT, or Gemini to generate your PRD","text":"I want to build a small app and I have never written code before. Act as my product manager. I'm going to describe my idea, and I want you to help me turn it into a clear Product Requirements Document (PRD) written in plain English that I can hand to an AI coding tool.\n\nMy idea: [describe your app in a few sentences — what it is, who it's for, and the main thing it should do].\n\nBefore you write the PRD, ask me any clarifying questions you need. Then produce a PRD that includes: a one-paragraph overview, who the users are, a list of every screen or page and what's on it, exactly what each button or feature does, the look and feel I want, and anything it must do (like working on phones). Keep the language simple and avoid technical jargon."}},{"heading":"Installing Cursor and opening your first project, step by step","paras":["Now the hands-on part. These steps take about ten minutes and you only do them once. Take them slowly; there's no way to break anything.","Step 1 — Download and install. Go to cursor.com in your web browser and click the big download button. It automatically offers the right version for your computer (Windows or Mac). When the file finishes downloading, open it and follow the prompts, exactly like installing any other app. Step 2 — Open it and sign in. Launch Cursor. It will ask you to sign in or create an account; do it with your email. If you're a student, use your student email and first activate the free student access at cursor.com/students so your account is upgraded automatically. There's a short first-run setup where it asks about your preferences — you can safely accept the defaults and change things later.","Step 3 — Make a folder for your project. On your desktop or in your Documents, create a normal new folder and give it a clear name, like bakery-website. A \"folder\" here means exactly what it means everywhere else on your computer — a container. Everything that makes up your app will live inside it. Step 4 — Put your PRD in the folder. Drop the project-prd.md file you made earlier into that folder (or you'll create it inside Cursor in the next step). Step 5 — Open the folder in Cursor. In Cursor, go to the File menu at the top and choose Open Folder, then select the folder you just made. Cursor now \"has\" your project: you'll see the folder's contents listed down the left side in a panel called the Explorer, which is just a file browser showing everything in your project.","Step 6 — Open the AI chat. Look for the AI panel, usually on the right side of the window (if you don't see it, there's a chat or sparkle icon to toggle it, or you can press Ctrl+L on Windows / Cmd+L on Mac). This panel is where the entire conversation happens — it's the beating heart of vibe coding in Cursor. Step 7 — Point the AI at your PRD and let it lead. This is the crucial move: don't ask it to build everything at once. Paste the prompt below, which tells the AI to read your blueprint and ask you questions before writing any code. A good AI will come back with smart questions — answer them, and only then let it start building. From here, you're in the loop: it builds a piece, you look at it, you test it, you describe what to change, and you repeat."],"prompt":{"label":"Paste into Cursor's AI chat as your very first message","text":"Read the project-prd.md file in this project. Before writing any code, ask me any questions you have about what I want, and point out anything in the PRD that's unclear or missing. Once we've cleared that up, propose a simple plan for building this step by step. Assume I have never written code before — explain what you're doing in plain language as you go, and build the simplest working version first so I can see it before we add more."}},{"heading":"The three key features that make Cursor feel like magic","paras":["Once you're chatting, three specific features turn Cursor from \"a chatbot next to an editor\" into something that feels genuinely powerful. Learning just these three is enough to build real projects.","The first is the AI chat, sometimes called Composer, and its ability to make multi-file edits. When you ask for a change like \"add a Contact page and a link to it from every other page,\" a plain chatbot would hand you disconnected snippets and leave you to figure out where each one goes. Cursor's chat instead edits all the relevant files itself and shows you the changes highlighted in green (added) and red (removed) so you can review before accepting. You click a button to apply the changes or reject them. You are always in control — nothing changes in your project until you approve it.","The second is the @ symbol, which lets you point the AI at something specific. As you type in the chat, typing @ pops up a menu of your files. If you write \"update the prices in @menu.html,\" you've told the AI precisely which file you mean, so it doesn't have to guess. You can also point it at a whole folder, or at documentation. This is how you keep the AI focused and accurate as your project grows — instead of hoping it finds the right file, you hand it the exact address. A small-business owner with a ten-file site will lean on @ constantly to say \"the thing I'm talking about is right here.\"","The third, and the biggest quality-of-life upgrade for beginners, is a file called .cursorrules. This is a plain-text file you create in the top level of your project folder, and inside it you write your standing preferences in ordinary English — the rules you want the AI to follow every single time, so you don't have to repeat them in every message. Once it exists, Cursor reads it automatically on every request. You might write \"Always explain what you're doing like I'm a complete beginner,\" \"Always make everything mobile-responsive so it looks good on phones,\" \"Keep the design clean and minimal,\" and \"Never use jargon without defining it.\" It's like giving your intern a one-page standing-orders sheet they re-read before every task. Below is a starter .cursorrules you can paste in and adjust."],"prompt":{"label":"Create a file named .cursorrules in your project folder and paste this in","text":"You are helping someone who has never written code before. Follow these rules on every request:\n\n- Explain what you are doing in plain, non-technical language. Define any technical term the first time you use it.\n- Build the simplest version that works first. Don't add extra features I didn't ask for.\n- Always make the design mobile-responsive so it looks good on phones as well as computers.\n- Keep the visual design clean, modern, and uncluttered.\n- Never put passwords, secret keys, or private information directly in the code. If something like that is needed, tell me and use a separate .env file.\n- After making changes, tell me in one short paragraph what changed and how I can see or test it."}},{"heading":"The build-test-refine loop, and how to actually run what you made","paras":["Vibe coding is a three-step loop you'll repeat over and over: (1) the AI builds a piece, (2) you test it by looking at it running, and (3) you refine by describing what to fix or add. Most beginners get stuck on step 2 — \"the AI made files, but how do I SEE my app?\" — so let's demystify it. For the most common beginner project, a website (files ending in .html, .css, and .js), you can literally just find the index.html file in Cursor's Explorer panel, and open that same file from your folder by double-clicking it — it opens in your web browser and you see your app. When you want to update it, ask the AI to make a change, accept the changes, then refresh the browser tab. That's the whole loop.","For anything more involved, the honest truth is you'll occasionally meet the terminal — a black text window built into Cursor (open it from the Terminal menu at the top) where you type commands instead of clicking buttons. This is the one part that feels most \"like a programmer,\" and it's the part beginners fear most. Here's the reassuring reality: you don't need to understand terminal commands. When your project needs one, just ask the AI \"what do I type in the terminal to run this?\" and it will give you the exact command to copy and paste. You paste it, press Enter, and it runs. The AI is your translator for the scary window. Never run a command you got from an untrusted source, but a command Cursor's own AI gives you for your own project is safe to run.","Refining is where the real progress happens, and the skill is describing problems concretely. \"It's broken\" gives the AI nothing. \"When I click Submit on the contact form, nothing happens — I expected a message saying thanks\" gives it everything it needs. If code produces an error message, don't panic and don't try to interpret it — copy the entire error, paste it into the chat, and say \"I got this error, what does it mean and how do we fix it?\" Debugging (the word for finding and fixing what's broken) is something the AI is genuinely good at, often better than at writing the code in the first place, because now it has a specific symptom to chase.","Keep your expectations calibrated with that eager-intern image. The AI's output is functional but unverified — it will confidently produce something that looks right and is subtly wrong, or works for the case you described but not the one you forgot to mention. That's not a failure of the tool; it's the nature of the collaboration. Test everything yourself, click every button, try the weird inputs. You are the one who knows what \"correct\" means for your project — the AI only knows what you told it."]},{"heading":"Staying safe, and publishing your finished project to the world","paras":["One security habit matters enough to state plainly, because it's the single most common way beginners get burned: never let the AI put passwords or secret keys directly into your code. A \"key\" (often called an API key) is a long secret password that lets your app use an outside service — for example, a key that lets your app send emails, or use a paid AI feature. If that secret sits inside a normal code file and you later publish your project online, the whole world can read it and run up charges on your account. The correct pattern, which the AI knows well, is to store secrets in a special file named .env (short for \"environment\") and then add that filename to a file called .gitignore, which is a list of files that should never be uploaded when you publish. If you're ever unsure, just ask Cursor: \"Am I handling my secret keys safely here?\" and follow its guidance.","When your project works and you want to show it to the world with a real web address, you'll \"deploy\" it — deploying just means putting your app on the internet so anyone can visit it at a link. Several excellent services do this for free for the kind of projects a beginner builds: GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, and Replit. Netlify is famously beginner-friendly — for a simple website you can sometimes just drag your project folder onto their web page and it hands you a live link within seconds. The others are nearly as easy, and — you guessed it — you can ask Cursor's AI to walk you through deploying to any of them step by step, including the exact commands if any are needed.","A final word of encouragement, and a real one. A year ago, building a working app meant months of learning syntax before you could make a button do anything. That barrier is largely gone. A hobbyist can build a personal habit-tracker over a weekend; a marketer can spin up a landing page to test an idea before lunch; a freelancer can build the client portal they always wanted but could never afford to commission. You do not need permission or a computer-science degree — you need a clear description of what you want and the willingness to go around the loop a few times. Download Cursor today, write one small PRD, and build the simplest thing you can imagine. The gap between \"I have an idea\" and \"it exists and it's on the internet\" has never been smaller. Go make something."]}],"keyTerms":[{"term":"Vibe coding","def":"Building software by describing what you want in plain English and letting an AI write the code, then refining it through conversation instead of writing the code yourself."},{"term":"IDE (Integrated Development Environment)","def":"The window where software is written and organized — like a supercharged text editor built specifically for code; Cursor is an AI-powered one."},{"term":"Agentic","def":"Describes an AI that can take actions on your behalf — creating files, writing and changing code, and fixing its own mistakes — not just answering questions."},{"term":"VS Code","def":"A free, extremely popular code editor from Microsoft; Cursor is built on top of it, so it inherits VS Code's polish and familiarity."},{"term":"PRD (Product Requirements Document)","def":"A plain-English blueprint describing exactly what you want to build — the screens, the buttons, the look and feel — that you hand to the AI before it starts coding."},{"term":"Terminal","def":"A black text window (built into Cursor) where you type commands instead of clicking buttons; you can ask the AI for the exact command to paste when you need one."},{"term":".cursorrules file","def":"A plain-text file in your project where you write standing preferences (like 'explain like I'm a beginner' or 'always mobile-responsive') that Cursor follows on every request."},{"term":".env file and API key","def":"An API key is a secret password that lets your app use an outside service; a .env file safely stores such secrets outside your normal code so they're never accidentally published."},{"term":"Deploy","def":"Putting your finished app on the internet so anyone can visit it at a web link; free services that do this include GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, and Replit."}],"tips":["Plan your PRD with a DIFFERENT AI than the one you build with — chat with Claude, ChatGPT, or Gemini to write the blueprint, then hand it to Cursor to build. The second perspective catches gaps.","Always tell the AI to build the simplest working version FIRST, see it running, then add features one at a time. Asking for everything at once is the fastest way to end up confused and broken.","Use the @ symbol in Cursor's chat to point at the exact file you mean (like @menu.html) instead of hoping the AI guesses right — accuracy jumps immediately as your project grows.","When you hit an error, copy the ENTIRE error message, paste it into the chat, and ask what it means and how to fix it. Never try to decode errors yourself — debugging is where the AI shines.","Treat every result like work from an eager intern: functional but unverified. Click every button and try weird inputs yourself, because you're the only one who knows what 'correct' means for your project.","Never let the AI paste passwords or API keys into your code. Have it use a .env file listed in .gitignore, and just ask 'am I handling my secrets safely?' whenever you're unsure."]},{"id":"vibe7","n":7,"g":"T","title":"Vibe Coding With Claude","tagline":"Turn a plain-English description of the app you wish existed into a working piece of software you can watch build itself in front of you — no coding experience required.","intro":"\"Vibe coding\" is a way of building software where you describe what you want in ordinary English and an AI writes the actual code, then you refine it by having a conversation — a term coined by AI researcher Andrej Karpathy. This page is your complete, hold-your-hand guide to doing that with Claude, the AI assistant made by a company called Anthropic. You do not need to have ever written a line of code or opened any special program. By the end, you will know two concrete ways to build with Claude, exactly what to type to get started, and how to avoid the beginner traps.","sections":[{"heading":"What Claude is, and why it's a great pick for your first build","paras":["Claude is a frontier AI assistant — \"frontier\" just means one of the most capable AIs available today, in the same league as ChatGPT and Google Gemini. You reach the basic version for free in your web browser at claude.ai; there is nothing to download to try it. You talk to it the same way you'd text a very knowledgeable friend: you type a message, it types back. Behind the friendly chat, Claude can write real, working code in any programming language, and it is especially good at three things that matter enormously when you're a beginner.","First, careful reasoning: it thinks a problem through step by step instead of blurting out the first idea, so its plans tend to hold together. Second, following instructions precisely — if you give it a detailed list of what you want, it actually respects that list rather than wandering off. Third, a large \"context window,\" which is the AI's short-term memory: the amount of your project it can hold in mind at once. A large context window means you can paste in a long document — like the full blueprint for your app — and Claude keeps all of it in view while it works, instead of forgetting the early parts by the time it reaches the end.","Here's a relatable picture of what you can actually make. A freelance photographer could build a small web page where clients pick a package and see the price update instantly. A café owner could make a tip-splitting calculator for the staff. A hobbyist gardener could build a watering-schedule tracker. A marketer could spin up a headline A/B tester. None of these require a big company or a budget — they're an afternoon of describing what you want and letting Claude write it.","One honest caveat to hold in mind from the very start: AI-written code is like work handed to you by an eager, fast, capable intern. It is usually functional, it's produced in seconds, and it's often genuinely good — but it is unverified. The intern is confident even when wrong. So you'll always test what it builds (we cover exactly how), and you never assume it's perfect just because it runs."]},{"heading":"The golden rule: plan with one AI, build with another","paras":["Before you build anything, you write a PRD. PRD stands for Program Requirements Document, and despite the intimidating name it is simply a plain-language blueprint: a short written description of what your app should do, who it's for, what each button does, and what it should look like. Think of it as the instructions you'd give a contractor before they build a room — the clearer the instructions, the closer the result is to what you pictured. You write this in plain English, not code.","The single most useful habit in vibe coding is this: plan the PRD with a DIFFERENT AI than the one you'll code with. Why? Because an AI reviewing its own plan tends to nod along and miss gaps, the same way a writer misses their own typos. When a second, independent AI writes or critiques the blueprint, it catches missing pieces, asks the questions you forgot, and pushes back on vague ideas. So a common winning combo is: plan the PRD in one tool (say, ChatGPT or Gemini), then hand that finished blueprint to Claude to actually build. Or flip it — plan with Claude, build with a Claude-powered code editor. The point is separation of duties: a planner and a builder that aren't the same AI.","To create your PRD, open a fresh chat with your planning AI and paste a prompt like the one below. Answer its questions in plain English — it will interview you — and in a few minutes you'll have a clean blueprint document you can copy out and save. Keep that document; it's the thing you'll hand to your builder in the next step, and you can reuse and refine it forever.","A tip that separates a frustrating first attempt from a delightful one: be specific and concrete in your PRD. \"A budget app\" is too vague and the AI will guess. \"A single web page where I type an expense amount and a category, click Add, and see a running total plus a simple bar showing spending per category, all saved in my browser so it's still there tomorrow\" gives the AI something real to build. Specificity is a superpower here."],"prompt":{"label":"Starter prompt — plan your PRD (paste into ChatGPT, Gemini, or Claude)","text":"You are my product planning partner. I want to build a small app but I am not a programmer. Ask me one question at a time to understand what I want, then write me a clear, plain-language Program Requirements Document (PRD) I can hand to an AI coding tool. Cover: what the app does, who it's for, the exact features and what each button does, what data it stores, and roughly what it should look like. Start by asking me your first question. My rough idea is: [describe your app in a sentence or two]."}},{"heading":"Way A — Build right in your browser with claude.ai and Artifacts (zero setup)","paras":["The friendliest place to start needs nothing but a web browser. Go to claude.ai, sign in (the free tier works to try this), and start a chat. Claude has a feature called Artifacts, and this is where the magic becomes visible. When you ask Claude to build a small web app, instead of only dumping code into the chat, it opens a live preview panel right beside the conversation — an actual working version of your app that you can click, type into, and use on the spot. You SEE the thing you're building, not just text about it.","This turns building into a conversation. You describe your app, it appears, and then you just talk to it: \"make the button blue,\" \"the total should update as I type instead of when I click,\" \"add a Clear All button at the bottom,\" \"it looks cramped on my phone — add more spacing.\" Each time, Claude rewrites the app and the preview refreshes so you can immediately check whether you like the change. There's no saving files, no installing anything, no jargon. For a self-contained tool — a calculator, a quiz, a countdown timer, a small tracker, a landing page — this is often the entire journey from idea to working app.","Concretely: a wedding planner could paste their PRD and get a guest-list manager with a headcount that updates as names are added; a Realtor could build a mortgage estimator where sliding the loan amount instantly recalculates the monthly payment; a fitness coach could make a workout timer that beeps between sets. All of it happens in the browser, all of it refined by chatting. To kick it off, paste your saved PRD into Claude with a build prompt like the one below.","When you're happy with it, you can copy the code Claude produced (there's a button on the Artifact to do so) and later publish it online for free so anyone can use it — we cover that near the end. For a huge number of real, useful little apps, Artifacts is genuinely all you need, and it's the lowest-risk place to feel the thrill of watching your idea come alive."],"prompt":{"label":"Starter prompt — build in claude.ai Artifacts","text":"Here is the PRD for an app I want you to build as a single self-contained web app I can preview here in an Artifact. Build the whole thing, keep the design clean and modern, make it work well on a phone screen too, and after you build it, briefly tell me in plain English how to use it and what I should click to test that it works. Here is the PRD:\n\n[paste your PRD here]"}},{"heading":"Way B — Point Claude Code at a folder on your computer (for real, multi-file projects)","paras":["When your project grows past a single page — an app that has several screens, saves data properly, or lives across many files — you graduate to Claude Code. This is a tool that runs in your terminal. The terminal is simply a plain text window on your computer where you type commands instead of clicking buttons; on a Mac it's the app called Terminal, on Windows it's Windows Terminal or PowerShell. It looks bare and old-fashioned, but it's just another way to talk to your computer, and Claude Code lives there.","What makes Claude Code different from the browser chat is that it acts as an autonomous agent working inside your actual project folder. \"Autonomous agent\" means it doesn't just hand you code to copy — it can read the files in your project, create new files, edit existing ones, and run commands to build and test the app, all by itself, while pausing to ask your approval before important steps. You point it at a folder (say, a folder on your Desktop called my-app), and it works across every file in there like a developer would, keeping the whole project consistent. This is how bigger apps get built without you ever copying and pasting code by hand.","You stay in control the whole time: Claude Code narrates what it's about to do and waits for your yes/no on meaningful actions, so nothing happens behind your back. A small-business owner could ask it to \"add a page that lists all my products and a form to add a new one,\" and it will create the new files, wire them into the existing app, and tell you how to look at the result — you approving each step. If the terminal itself feels too bare, there's a gentler on-ramp described in the next section.","If you'd rather not use a terminal at all but still want this file-editing power, use a Claude-powered code editor instead. Cursor is a popular one (free for students at cursor.com/students, otherwise a monthly subscription): it looks like a normal writing program with a chat panel on the side, and you can set it to use a Claude model so you get Claude's brains inside a friendlier window. Either path — Claude Code in the terminal or Cursor set to Claude — gives you the same core ability: an AI that edits your real project files, not just a chat that hands you snippets."],"prompt":{"label":"Starter prompt — build with Claude Code / a Claude-powered editor","text":"You are building an app for me in this project folder. I am not a programmer, so explain each step in plain English and ask before doing anything major. Read the PRD below, set up the project, and build it feature by feature. After each feature, tell me exactly how to run and test it so I can confirm it works before we move on. Here is the PRD:\n\n[paste your PRD here]"}},{"heading":"The 3-step loop that ties it all together","paras":["Everything above fits into one simple, repeatable rhythm you'll use for every project: plan, build, then test and refine. Step one, plan: write your PRD with a planning AI (that's the first prompt on this page). Step two, build: hand that PRD to Claude — either in Artifacts for a browser app or Claude Code for a bigger one — using the build prompt. Step three, test and refine: actually use the thing, find what's wrong or missing, and describe the fix in plain English so the AI corrects it. Then you loop: test again, refine again, until it's right.","Testing, for a non-programmer, means exactly what it sounds like — click every button, type into every box, try to break it. Enter a negative number where you'd expect a positive one. Leave a field blank and hit submit. Open it on your phone. When something misbehaves, you don't need to diagnose why in technical terms; you just report the symptom. \"When I click Add with the box empty, it adds a blank row — it shouldn't\" is a perfect bug report for an AI. It will find the cause and fix it. Describing what went wrong in plain words is a skill you already have.","This loop is where the \"eager intern\" reality earns its keep. The AI's first version will often be 80% right and 20% surprising — a button in the wrong spot, a total that doesn't update, a color you hate. That's normal and expected; it is not a sign you did something wrong. Each pass through the loop closes the gap. The people who succeed at vibe coding aren't the ones who get it perfect on the first prompt — they're the ones who keep calmly describing the next fix. Patience through a few rounds beats a perfect first prompt every time.","A worked example: a freelance illustrator wants a simple invoice generator. Plan — they PRD it with Gemini, which asks whether they need tax lines and multiple currencies (a gap they'd have forgotten). Build — they paste the PRD into Claude Artifacts and get a working form with a live PDF-style preview. Test — they notice the date defaults to the wrong format and there's no way to add their logo. Refine — two plain-English requests later, both are fixed. Total time: an evening, and now they own a tool built exactly for how they work."]},{"heading":"Staying safe, staying free, and putting your creation online","paras":["Two security basics protect you from the most common beginner mistakes, and they're easy. First: never let the AI put passwords, secret keys, or private access codes directly into the code. Many apps that connect to an outside service need an \"API key\" — think of it as a password that lets your app use that service. If that key sits in your code and your code ever goes public, anyone can find it and run up charges in your name. The safe pattern is to store secrets in a special file named .env (short for \"environment\") and then list that file in another file called .gitignore, which tells the publishing tools \"never upload this file.\" You don't have to set this up by hand — you can simply ask Claude to do it, and it will.","Second: the free tier has limits. Claude's free plan lets you do a real amount of work, but it caps how much you can use in a given window of time; if you hit the limit, you wait a bit or upgrade to a paid plan for more. This is normal across all these AIs (ChatGPT, Gemini, and the rest all have free tiers with caps). The practical move for a beginner is to start free, get a feel for the whole loop on a small project, and only pay once you know you'll keep going. Don't let usage limits scare you off — you can build genuinely useful things entirely within the free allowances.","When your project is finished and you want the world (or just a client) to see it at a real web address, you publish it — for free. Several services host your finished app at no cost: GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, and Replit are the common ones, and Claude can walk you through whichever you pick, step by step, in plain English. \"Hosting\" just means putting your app on a computer that's always on, so a link works for anyone, anytime, instead of only running on your own machine.","A quick honest word on limits so you go in clear-eyed: AI-built code can contain subtle mistakes it states with total confidence, it can pick a clumsy approach when a simpler one exists, and it won't know about your specific private situation unless you tell it. None of this is a reason to avoid vibe coding — it's a reason to keep a human hand on the wheel: test everything, keep secrets out of code, and treat the AI as a brilliant, tireless intern whose work you always give a second look. Do that, and you can start building something real today."],"prompt":{"label":"Prompt — ask Claude to set up your secrets safely","text":"My app needs to use an API key from an outside service. I am not a programmer. Please set this up the safe way: put the key in a .env file, add .env to a .gitignore file so it never gets uploaded, and show me exactly where to paste my key. Explain in plain English what each file does and confirm my key will never end up in any code that gets published."}}],"keyTerms":[{"term":"Vibe coding","def":"Building software by describing what you want in plain English and letting an AI write the code, then improving it through back-and-forth conversation."},{"term":"PRD (Program Requirements Document)","def":"A short, plain-language blueprint describing what your app should do, who it's for, and what each part does, written before any code exists."},{"term":"Context window","def":"An AI's short-term memory — how much of your project it can hold in mind at once; a larger one lets it keep long documents fully in view while it works."},{"term":"Artifacts","def":"A Claude feature that shows a live, clickable preview of the web app it's building right next to the chat, so you can see it and request changes conversationally."},{"term":"Terminal","def":"A plain text window on your computer where you type commands instead of clicking buttons; it's where the Claude Code agent runs."},{"term":"Autonomous agent","def":"An AI that doesn't just hand you code but actually reads, creates, and edits files and runs commands in your project by itself, pausing for your approval on important steps."},{"term":"API key","def":"A secret password-like code that lets your app use an outside service; it must be kept out of your code so no one else can find and misuse it."},{"term":".env and .gitignore files","def":"A .env file safely stores secrets like API keys, and listing it in a .gitignore file tells publishing tools never to upload it."}],"tips":["Always plan the PRD with a different AI than the one you build with — an independent second AI catches the gaps and vague spots that the builder would happily skip over.","Be ruthlessly specific in your PRD: describe each button, what happens when it's clicked, and what the screen looks like. Vague requests get guessed at; concrete ones get built right.","Treat every AI-written app like work from an eager intern — always test it yourself by clicking everything and trying to break it before you trust it, because it's confident even when it's wrong.","Report bugs by describing the symptom in plain English ('the total doesn't change when I type'), not by trying to diagnose the code — the AI will find and fix the cause from your description.","Start entirely on free tiers (claude.ai, Cursor for students) and only pay once you know you'll keep building; you can make genuinely useful tools without spending a cent."]},{"id":"vibe8","n":8,"g":"T","title":"Vibe Coding With ChatGPT","intro":"ChatGPT (at chat.openai.com) is the most widely used AI assistant in the world, and it has a free tier, which makes it the easiest possible on-ramp to \"vibe coding\" — the practice of building working software just by describing what you want in plain English and letting the AI write the actual code. There is nothing to install: you open a browser tab, type a sentence like a text message, and a functioning tool starts taking shape. This page walks a complete beginner — someone who has never opened a code editor or typed a command into a terminal (the plain black window where you type instructions to your computer) — through two distinct ways to build with ChatGPT and the exact workflow that gets you from a vague idea to a real, usable app. Every technical word is explained the first time it appears, and every prompt below has a copy button so you can paste it straight in.","tagline":"Turn a plain-English idea into a working web tool using nothing but a free ChatGPT account and the sentences you already know how to write.","sections":[{"heading":"What ChatGPT is, and why it is the friendliest place to start","paras":["ChatGPT is a chatbot: you type a message, it types back. Behind it sits a large language model, which is a program trained on an enormous amount of text so that it can predict useful, human-sounding responses — including working computer code. You reach it by going to chat.openai.com in any web browser (Chrome, Edge, Safari, Firefox) and signing in with a free account. There is no software to download and nothing to configure. That zero-setup quality is exactly why it is the best first stop for someone who has never built anything before.","'Vibe coding' is a term coined by AI researcher Andrej Karpathy for this new way of working: instead of learning a programming language, you describe the result you want in ordinary language, let the AI produce the code, run it, and then refine it through back-and-forth conversation. You are the director describing the scene; ChatGPT is the crew that actually builds it. You never have to memorize syntax (the exact punctuation and keywords a programming language requires) — if something looks wrong, you just say so in plain words and it fixes it.","Here is the honest framing to keep in your head the entire time: AI-written code is like work handed to you by an eager, fast, but junior intern. It is usually functional and often impressive, but it is unverified. The intern is confident even when wrong. So your job is not to write code — it is to describe clearly, then test what comes back and say what is off. That single habit, described near the end of this page, is the difference between a frustrating afternoon and a working tool.","A concrete picture of who this is for: a bakery owner who wants a little web page where customers pick a cake size and see the price update instantly; a freelance photographer who wants a countdown timer for their booking deadlines; a marketer who wants a one-page tool that counts characters so their ad copy fits a platform limit. None of these people write code. All of them can build these things in an afternoon with ChatGPT."]},{"heading":"Two ways to build: plain chat, and Canvas","paras":["ChatGPT gives you two different surfaces to work on, and knowing when to use each is most of the battle. The first is plain chat — the normal message-and-reply window. This is perfect for two jobs: thinking through what you want to build (your blueprint, covered in the next section), and generating a chunk of code that you then copy out and paste into another program. In plain chat, code shows up inside a gray box with a small 'Copy' button in its corner; one click puts the whole thing on your clipboard, ready to paste elsewhere.","The second surface is Canvas, and it is a genuine game-changer for beginners. Canvas is a side-by-side editor: your conversation stays on the left, and a document or code file opens on the right that you and ChatGPT edit together, live. Instead of ChatGPT dumping a fresh wall of code into the chat every time you ask for a change (forcing you to figure out what moved), it revises the same file in place, right in front of you. ChatGPT often opens Canvas on its own when it writes more than about ten lines, but you can always ask for it directly.","What makes Canvas special is targeted editing. You can highlight a specific part of the text or code with your mouse — say, just the button that is the wrong color — and tell ChatGPT to change only that, and it revises just that piece with the whole project still in mind. It keeps a version history so earlier drafts are not lost, and it saves automatically. For a beginner building one self-contained web tool, this feels less like programming and more like editing a document with a very capable assistant sitting next to you. It is the closest thing to 'watching your idea get built' that exists in a free tool.","To open Canvas on purpose, just say so in your message, or type a forward slash to bring up a command menu and choose 'canvas.' The prompt in this section is the exact phrase that reliably opens it once you already have a plan ready to build."],"bullets":["Plain chat is best for: planning your blueprint, quick questions, and generating code to copy elsewhere.","Canvas is best for: building and refining ONE web tool over many small edits, watching changes happen inline, and highlighting a specific part to fix.","You can move between them: plan in plain chat, then say 'Build this in a Canvas' to switch surfaces without losing the thread."],"prompt":{"label":"Switch from planning into Canvas to start building","text":"Build this in a Canvas so we can iterate on it together."}},{"heading":"Step 1 of the loop: write your blueprint (the PRD) — and do it in a DIFFERENT AI","paras":["Before you build anything, you write a PRD, which stands for Program Requirements Document. Do not let the formal name scare you: a PRD is simply a plain-language description of what you want, written down in one place so the AI that builds it never has to guess. Think of it as the note you would leave for a contractor — what the thing is, who uses it, what each button does, what it should look like. Skipping this step is the single most common reason a first project spirals into confusion, because the AI fills every gap you leave with its own guess.","The best way to produce a strong PRD is to let an AI interview you. You do not have to know the right questions — you let it ask them. The magic phrase is to have the AI ask you clarifying questions one at a time so you are never overwhelmed by a wall of questions at once. Answer each in plain English (or even 'I don't know, what do you suggest?'), and after eight or ten questions you will have a surprisingly complete blueprint you can hand to the builder.","Now the important professional habit: plan your PRD with a DIFFERENT AI than the one you will build with. If you are going to build in ChatGPT, do the planning conversation somewhere else — Claude (claude.ai) and Google Gemini are both excellent free choices — and vice versa. This keeps the two jobs in separate contexts (a 'context' is everything the AI is currently keeping in mind), so the planning conversation does not clutter the building conversation, and a second AI often catches gaps or assumptions the first one would have glossed over. It is like having one person write the spec and a fresh set of eyes review it.","A relatable example of the loop in action: a small-business owner wants a tip calculator for their food truck. They open Gemini, paste the PRD prompt below, and answer ten quick questions ('split between how many people?', 'round up or exact?', 'what colors match my brand?'). Out comes a tidy one-page blueprint. They copy it, open ChatGPT, and move to building. Ten minutes of planning saves an hour of 'that's not what I meant.'"],"prompt":{"label":"The PRD interview prompt (paste into your PLANNING AI first)","text":"I want to build a simple web tool. Before writing any code, act as a product manager and interview me to create a clear Program Requirements Document (PRD). Ask me 5-10 clarifying questions one at a time, waiting for my answer before asking the next. Cover what the tool does, who uses it, each feature and button, what it should look like, and anything I might be forgetting. When we're done, write the final PRD as a clean, plain-language summary I can hand to another AI to build."}},{"heading":"Step 2: hand the PRD to ChatGPT and build it","paras":["With your PRD in hand, open a fresh ChatGPT conversation, paste the whole blueprint, and ask it to build the thing in a Canvas. For a beginner, the sweet spot is a single-file web tool — a self-contained page written in the three basic web languages (HTML for the structure, CSS for the styling, and JavaScript for the interactivity) all bundled into one file. Single-file matters because it means the finished product is just one document you can save and open in any browser, with no complicated setup. Say so explicitly in your request so ChatGPT does not over-engineer.","Once Canvas opens with your tool on the right, you refine it conversationally. You do not edit code by hand. You say things like 'make the button bigger and blue,' 'add a field for a second person's name,' or 'the total is showing too many decimal places — round it to two.' Watch the right-hand panel update. If one specific spot is wrong, highlight it with your mouse and describe the fix — that tells ChatGPT exactly where to look. This tight loop of look, describe, watch, repeat is the whole craft.","To actually see and use what you have built, you need to run it, which for a single-file web tool means opening it in a browser. You can copy the code out of Canvas (the copy button), paste it into a plain text editor, save the file with a name ending in .html (for example tip-calculator.html), and then double-click that file — it opens in your browser as a real, working page. Alternatively, many people move the code into a dedicated building tool at this stage, which the next section covers.","A worked example: a freelancer pastes their PRD for a project-deadline countdown, says 'build this as a single self-contained HTML file in a Canvas,' and watches a page appear with a date picker and a live countdown. They highlight the plain gray heading and say 'make this my brand color, a warm orange, and bigger.' It updates instantly. Three more small requests later — a reset button, a friendly message when the deadline passes, a subtle background — they save it as an .html file and it is done. No syntax memorized, no setup wizard, no cost."],"prompt":{"label":"Kick off the build in ChatGPT (paste your PRD first, then this)","text":"Here is my PRD above. Build this as a single self-contained HTML file (HTML, CSS, and JavaScript all in one file) in a Canvas so we can iterate. Keep it simple and beginner-friendly, add short comments explaining each part in plain English, and don't add anything that isn't in the PRD. After you build it, tell me exactly how to open and test it."}},{"heading":"When to move to a dedicated coding tool — and Custom GPTs","paras":["ChatGPT is superb for planning and for building small, single-page tools. But once a project grows past one file — say you want several pages that link together, or you want to keep tweaking the same project over many days — a purpose-built coding tool becomes far more comfortable than a chat window. The professional rhythm many people settle into is: use ChatGPT (or another chat AI) for PLANNING, and a dedicated coding tool for BUILDING. Keeping those two contexts separate keeps each one clean and focused, exactly like using a separate planner AI for your PRD.","Your options for the building tool range from 'stay in the browser, zero setup' to 'install a real editor.' Replit and Bolt.new let you build and preview entirely in a web browser with nothing to install. Cursor and Windsurf are AI code editors — full programs you download that have an AI assistant built into the writing surface; Cursor is free for students at cursor.com/students. GitHub Copilot is an AI assistant that plugs into the popular free editor VS Code and is free for verified students and teachers at education.github.com (otherwise around ten dollars a month). Claude (claude.ai) offers Artifacts, a live preview panel much like Canvas, plus Claude Code, a more advanced assistant that works in the terminal. Google also offers Google AI Studio for experimenting with its models. To carry your work over, you copy the code ChatGPT generated and paste it into whichever tool you pick, then keep the conversation going there.","One more ChatGPT feature worth knowing: Custom GPTs. A Custom GPT is a version of ChatGPT you set up once with standing instructions, so it behaves a certain way every time without you re-explaining. For example, a hobbyist could make a 'Beginner Web Builder' GPT with instructions like 'always build single-file HTML tools, always explain every step in plain English, never assume I know any jargon.' From then on, that GPT starts every project already knowing your rules. Creating your own Custom GPTs requires a paid plan, but simply using ones others have shared is available to anyone within their normal message allowance.","How to choose, in one sentence each: stay in ChatGPT's Canvas for a quick single-page tool; move to Replit or Bolt.new when you want to stay in the browser but the project is growing; install Cursor or use Claude's Artifacts when you are ready for a more powerful, dedicated home for a project you will keep improving. And if you ever want to run an AI model entirely on your own computer, with no account and no internet, tools called Ollama and LM Studio make that possible — a more advanced path, but good to know it exists."],"bullets":["ChatGPT + Canvas: best for planning and small single-file web tools; free tier works.","Replit / Bolt.new: build and preview in the browser, no install, good for growing projects.","Cursor / Windsurf: downloadable AI code editors; Cursor free for students at cursor.com/students.","GitHub Copilot: AI inside the free VS Code editor; free for verified students and teachers at education.github.com, else ~$10/mo.","Claude (claude.ai): Artifacts gives a live preview like Canvas; Claude Code is a terminal-based agent for bigger work.","Ollama & LM Studio: run AI models locally on your own machine, no account or internet needed (more advanced).","Custom GPTs: reusable, pre-instructed versions of ChatGPT — using shared ones is free; creating your own needs a paid plan."]},{"heading":"Step 3: test, verify, and refine — because the AI is a confident intern","paras":["This is the step beginners skip and professionals never do. AI-written code runs, but 'it runs' is not the same as 'it is correct.' Your tip calculator might look perfect and still round the wrong way; your countdown might be a day off; a button might do nothing on a phone even though it works on your laptop. You must actually use the tool the way a real person would and check the results against what you expected. Do not trust the AI's assurance that it works — trust what you see when you click.","The way to test is boringly effective: open the tool and try it. Put in normal values and confirm the answer is right. Then try to break it — leave a field blank, type a word where a number goes, enter a huge number, click the button twice fast. Each time something misbehaves, you have found a bug (an error in the code), and fixing it is easy: describe exactly what you did and what went wrong, and let the AI repair it. Precise descriptions get precise fixes; 'it's broken' gets a shrug, while 'when I leave the name field empty and click Calculate, it shows the word undefined instead of a total' gets a real fix.","When a fix does not work on the first try, do not spiral. Tell the AI plainly that its change did not fix the problem and describe what still happens; if it goes in circles, ask it to explain what it thinks is wrong before changing anything, or start a fresh conversation and paste in the current code with a clean description of the bug. A fresh context often breaks a loop faster than arguing with a stuck one.","Finally, two safety basics that matter the moment your project touches anything private. First: never let the AI put passwords or secret keys directly into the code. Many tools use an API key, which is a long secret password that lets your app talk to another service — treat it like a house key. It belongs in a separate file called .env (short for 'environment'), and you add that file's name to another file called .gitignore, which is a list of files that must never be uploaded or shared. That combination keeps your secrets on your own machine. Second: read what the AI writes at least enough to understand roughly what it does before you run it on anything real. You are the responsible adult in the room; the eager intern is not."],"prompt":{"label":"Report a bug precisely so the AI can actually fix it","text":"That change didn't fix it. Here's exactly what I did and what happened: I [describe the steps you took], and instead of [what you expected], I got [what actually happened]. Before changing the code, briefly explain what you think is causing this, then fix only that."}},{"heading":"The honest limits of the free tier — and why it is still plenty to start","paras":["The free version of ChatGPT is genuinely useful, but it has real ceilings you should know before you rely on it. The most important is a message cap: free accounts get a limited number of messages on the most capable model within a rolling window (roughly a handful of top-model messages every few hours), after which ChatGPT automatically switches you to a smaller, faster, less capable 'mini' model until the limit resets. You will not be cut off entirely — but mid-project you may notice the answers get a little less sharp. That is the cap, not you doing something wrong.","A few knock-on effects for beginners: Custom GPTs do not come with their own separate pool of messages on the free tier — using them draws from the same allowance, so when you hit your limit you cannot use GPTs either until it resets. Exact numbers shift over time and vary by region and demand, so treat any specific figure as approximate. The practical takeaway is to be efficient: do your thinking in your planning AI, come to ChatGPT with a finished PRD, and spend your best-model messages on the actual building.","None of this should stop you from starting today. The free tier is more than enough to plan a PRD, build a real single-file web tool in Canvas, test it, and save a finished product you can use — the whole loop, start to finish, at no cost. And when you have something you are proud of, free hosting services like GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, and Replit can put it on the public internet at its own web address so anyone can visit it. If you find yourself building constantly and hitting the cap often, that is a signal you have outgrown the free tier and might consider a paid plan or moving your building into a dedicated tool like Replit, Cursor, or Claude's Artifacts. But that is a good problem, and it is weeks away, not today.","One last encouragement: the gap between 'I have an idea' and 'I have a working tool' has never been smaller. You do not need permission, a course, or a computer-science background. You need a browser, a free account, a clear description of what you want, and the willingness to click the thing you built and see if it works. Open chat.openai.com, paste the PRD prompt into a planning AI, and start. The first time a tool you described in plain English actually runs, something clicks — and you will not want to stop."]}],"keyTerms":[{"term":"Vibe coding","def":"Building software by describing what you want in plain English and letting an AI write and refine the code through conversation, rather than writing code yourself."},{"term":"Large language model (LLM)","def":"The kind of AI behind ChatGPT — a program trained on huge amounts of text so it can produce human-sounding responses, including working code."},{"term":"PRD (Program Requirements Document)","def":"A plain-language written blueprint describing what your tool does, who uses it, and how each part behaves, so the AI never has to guess."},{"term":"Canvas","def":"ChatGPT's side-by-side editor: the chat stays on the left while a code or document file opens on the right that you and the AI edit together live."},{"term":"Terminal","def":"The plain text window where you type typed commands to your computer instead of clicking buttons; beginners can build a lot without ever touching it."},{"term":"Single-file web tool","def":"A small web page whose structure (HTML), styling (CSS), and interactivity (JavaScript) all live in one file you can save and open in any browser."},{"term":"Custom GPT","def":"A reusable version of ChatGPT you set up once with standing instructions so it behaves the same way on every project without re-explaining."},{"term":"API key, .env, and .gitignore","def":"An API key is a secret password letting your app use another service; a .env file holds such secrets and .gitignore is the list of files that must never be uploaded."}],"tips":["Always plan your PRD in a DIFFERENT AI (Claude or Gemini) than the one you build with — separate contexts stay cleaner and a second AI catches gaps the first would miss.","Spend your limited free-tier top-model messages on building, not thinking: arrive at ChatGPT with a finished PRD already in hand.","When something breaks, describe exactly what you clicked and what happened — 'it's broken' gets a shrug, but 'leaving the name blank shows undefined instead of a total' gets a real fix.","Ask for a single self-contained HTML file so your finished tool is one document you can save and double-click open — no setup, no install.","If the AI gets stuck fixing the same bug in circles, start a fresh conversation and paste in the current code with a clean description — a fresh context breaks the loop faster than arguing.","Never let the AI paste a password or API key into the code; keep secrets in a .env file and add that file to .gitignore so they are never uploaded."]},{"id":"vibe9","n":9,"g":"T","title":"Vibe Coding With GitHub Copilot","intro":"GitHub Copilot is an AI \"pair programmer\" — think of a smart, tireless assistant that sits inside the program where code is written and drafts the code for you while you describe what you want in plain English. It is the tool professional software developers use every day at real companies, which means learning it puts an industry-standard skill directly in your hands. The best part: it is completely free for verified students and teachers, and cheap (about $10 a month) for everyone else, with a genuinely usable free tier on top of that. This guide walks a complete beginner — someone who has never opened a code editor or typed a command — from zero to a working, AI-built project.","tagline":"Install one free tool, describe your idea in plain English, and watch a professional-grade AI write the actual working code for you — the same way developers do it at real software companies.","sections":[{"heading":"What GitHub Copilot actually is (in plain English)","paras":["First, some vocabulary, because two words here matter. A \"code editor\" (also called an IDE, short for Integrated Development Environment) is simply the app where people write software — the way Microsoft Word is the app where you write documents, a code editor is the app where you write code. The most popular free one is called VS Code, made by Microsoft. GitHub Copilot is not a separate program you open; it is a \"plugin\" (a small add-on) that lives inside that code editor and adds AI superpowers to it.","Once installed, Copilot does two things. The first is autocomplete on steroids: as you type, it predicts the next lines of code and shows them in faint gray text called \"ghost text.\" If you like the suggestion, you press the Tab key and it instantly becomes real code; if you don't, you just keep typing and it vanishes. Imagine writing an email and your assistant silently drafting the next sentence in gray — press Tab to accept, ignore it to reject. That is the feel.","The second thing is Copilot Chat: a sidebar panel where you talk to the AI in ordinary English. You can say \"build me a page that shows my dog-walking prices\" or \"why isn't this button working?\" or \"explain what this code does like I'm five,\" and it answers with code, fixes, or plain explanations right there next to your project. This chat is where the real magic happens for a beginner, because you never have to write code yourself — you describe, it builds, you refine. That back-and-forth of describing something in plain language and letting the AI write and rewrite the code is exactly what people mean by \"vibe coding.\"","One honest reframe to hold onto from the very start: AI-written code is like work handed to you by an eager, fast, well-read intern. It is usually functional and often impressive, but it is unverified — it can confidently produce something that looks right and quietly doesn't work, or works today and breaks when you ask for the next feature. Your job is not to write the code; your job is to describe clearly, then test what comes back. That mindset is what separates a frustrating afternoon from a finished project."]},{"heading":"The money question: is it free? (Yes, mostly)","paras":["Here is the headline, because it is the reason to start with Copilot: it is FREE for verified students and teachers, forever, through a program called GitHub Education (at education.github.com). If you are enrolled at, or teach at, almost any school, college, or university, you pay nothing. We will walk through exactly how to prove your status in the next section.","If you are not a student or teacher, there are still two options. There is a genuinely useful Free plan (no credit card, available to anyone with a GitHub account) that gives you about 2,000 code completions and roughly 50 chat messages per month — plenty to build a small website or tool and decide whether you love this. When you outgrow that, the Pro plan is about $10 per month and removes those limits, giving unlimited completions and far more chat. There are bigger plans above that (Pro+ at around $39/month, business tiers higher still), but a beginner will never need them — the $10 Pro plan is the working baseline that real freelancers and hobbyists use.","A concrete way to think about it: a freelance graphic designer who wants to build a simple portfolio site to show clients could do the entire thing on the Free plan and never spend a cent. A small-business owner who wants an ongoing tool — say, a booking page they keep improving month after month — would hit the free limits eventually and happily pay $10/month, which is less than one streaming subscription, for unlimited use. And if you qualify through your school, you skip that decision entirely and get the full experience for free."],"table":{"headers":["Plan","Cost","Best for","Key limits"],"rows":[["Student / Teacher (via GitHub Education)","Free (verified)","Anyone enrolled at or teaching at a qualifying school","Unlimited code completions; generous chat allowance"],["Free","$0, no card","First-timers testing the waters","~2,000 completions & ~50 chats per month"],["Pro","~$10 / month","Hobbyists, freelancers, small-business owners building regularly","Unlimited completions, much larger chat allowance"]]}},{"heading":"Free forever: unlocking GitHub Education (and 100+ bonus tools)","paras":["Verifying that you are a student or teacher does more than make Copilot free — it also unlocks the GitHub Student Developer Pack (or the equivalent for educators), which is a bundle of dozens of premium developer tools and services given to you free. Think free website hosting, free design software, free cloud credits — the kind of tools professionals pay real money for. Copilot is just the crown jewel of the bundle.","The process is straightforward and often approved within minutes if your school is recognized. You need two things: a free GitHub account (a GitHub account is simply a login for github.com, the website where the world's developers store and share code — signing up takes two minutes and no payment), and ideally a school email address ending in something like .edu. Here is the path: go to education.github.com, click to start an application, choose whether you're a student or a teacher, add and verify your school email, and submit. GitHub emails a verification link to that school address; click it, and if it recognizes your school's email domain, you're often approved on the spot.","Don't have a school email? You can still qualify. GitHub accepts alternative proof of your current status — a dated student or faculty ID, a current class registration or enrollment document, a timestamped screenshot of your school portal, or a letter on school letterhead. These manual reviews take a bit longer (up to around two weeks) but work fine. The tradeoff is simple: a recognized school email is the fast lane; document uploads are the slower but reliable lane.","Once you're verified, the free Copilot access attaches to your GitHub account automatically. From then on, every time you sign into Copilot inside your code editor using that GitHub account, it's free. There is no ongoing renewal hoop beyond re-verifying occasionally when your student or teacher status is up for its periodic check."],"prompt":{"label":"Where to apply for free access","text":"https://education.github.com"}},{"heading":"Getting started: from empty computer to typing your first prompt","paras":["Let's install everything from scratch, assuming you have nothing set up. This is five short steps, and none of them require you to understand code.","Step 1 — Install the code editor. Go to code.visualstudio.com and download VS Code (it's free, and works on Windows, Mac, and Linux). Run the installer the same way you'd install any app, then open it. You'll see a fairly empty window with a row of icons down the left side — that's normal; think of it as a blank workspace waiting for your project.","Step 2 — Install the Copilot plugin. On that left-hand strip of icons, click the one that looks like four squares (with one square flying off) — that's the Extensions panel, VS Code's built-in app store for add-ons. In its search box, type \"GitHub Copilot,\" find the official one published by GitHub, and click the blue Install button. Install its companion \"GitHub Copilot Chat\" too if it doesn't come along automatically. Step 3 — Sign in. VS Code will prompt you to sign in with your GitHub account (create one free at github.com if you don't have it); a browser window pops up, you approve the connection, and you're linked. Step 4 — Verify your student or teacher status if you did the GitHub Education step above, so your access is free. Step 5 — Open your project folder and start.","To \"open a project folder,\" just make a new empty folder on your desktop (call it something like \"my-first-site\"), then in VS Code choose File then Open Folder and pick it. Now you're ready. Either start typing in a file and watch the gray ghost-text suggestions appear (press Tab to accept), or — much better for a beginner — open Copilot Chat by clicking the chat icon in the left strip, and paste in a build prompt describing what you want. The next section gives you exactly that prompt."]},{"heading":"The three-step loop: Plan, Build, Refine","paras":["Professionals don't just start typing and hope — they follow a loop, and you should too. It has three steps: Plan, Build, Refine. Skipping the Plan step is the single most common reason beginners get messy, half-working results.","Plan means writing a PRD first. A PRD (Program Requirements Document) is nothing scary — it's a plain-English blueprint of what you want, written before any code exists. It lists what the thing is, who it's for, what each part does, and what it should look like. Here's the pro move that dramatically improves results: write the PRD with a DIFFERENT AI than the one you build with. Open a separate AI chat — Claude (at claude.ai) or ChatGPT (at chat.openai.com) or Google Gemini — and have it interview you and draft the blueprint. Then you carry that blueprint over to Copilot to actually build. Using two different AIs means one catches gaps the other would miss, the way a second pair of eyes catches typos you've gone blind to.","Build means pasting your PRD into Copilot Chat and letting it generate the project. You'll get real files with real code. Refine means the conversation that follows: you look at what it built, tell Copilot what's wrong or what to change (\"the button is too small,\" \"make the header dark blue,\" \"it crashes when I click submit — fix it\"), and it revises. You repeat Build-and-Refine as many times as you like. A marketer building a campaign landing page might go through this loop a dozen times in an afternoon, each pass nudging it closer to what they pictured.","The golden rule of refining: change one thing at a time and check it before moving on. If you ask for five changes at once and something breaks, you won't know which change did it. Small steps, test after each — that's how you stay in control of an eager intern who codes faster than you can read."],"prompt":{"label":"Plan your PRD with a different AI first (paste into Claude, ChatGPT, or Gemini)","text":"You are my product planning partner. I want to build a simple website but I am not technical. Interview me one question at a time about what I want, then write me a clear, plain-English Program Requirements Document (PRD) I can hand to a coding AI. Cover: what the site is, who it's for, every page or section and what it does, the visual style, and any content or features I mentioned. Start by asking me your first question."}},{"heading":"Your first build: a starter prompt for Copilot Chat","paras":["Once you have a PRD, this is the prompt that turns it into a working project. Open Copilot Chat in VS Code and paste it in, replacing the bracketed part with your own blueprint. Notice how specific it is — it tells the AI to keep things simple, to use beginner-friendly technology, and to explain what it did. Specificity is everything: a vague request gets vague code; a detailed one gets something you can actually use.","A realistic example of what to put in the brackets: \"a one-page website for my dog-walking business called Happy Paws, with a friendly headline, a short 'About me' paragraph, a list of three service packages with prices, and a contact section with my email. Warm, playful colors. It should look good on a phone.\" That single description, handed to Copilot, produces a genuine web page you can open in your browser in seconds.","After it builds, keep talking to it. Real follow-ups that work: \"Center the headline and make it bigger.\" \"Add a photo placeholder at the top.\" \"The prices are hard to read — put them in a nice card layout.\" \"Explain, in plain English, which file I open to see this in my browser.\" That last one matters — don't be shy about asking the AI to teach you the boring logistics, because it's a patient tutor that never sighs at a basic question."],"prompt":{"label":"Starter Copilot Chat build prompt (paste into Copilot Chat)","text":"You are my coding partner. I am a non-technical beginner and have never written code. Build the following project for me using the simplest, most beginner-friendly approach (plain HTML, CSS, and JavaScript — no complicated frameworks). Here is my plain-English blueprint (PRD):\n\n[PASTE YOUR PRD HERE]\n\nPlease: 1) create all the files needed and put working code in them, 2) keep it simple and well-commented so I can read it, 3) after you're done, tell me in plain English exactly which file to open to see the result in my web browser, and 4) suggest three small improvements I could ask you for next. Go step by step and explain what you're doing."}},{"heading":"Publishing your project and staying safe","paras":["A project sitting on your computer is only visible to you. To put it on the real internet with its own web address — for free — you have several beginner-friendly options: GitHub Pages (built right into the GitHub account you already made), Netlify, Vercel, or Replit. Each lets you take a finished project and get a public link you can text to a client or add to your business cards, at no cost for small sites. When you're ready, ask Copilot Chat directly: \"Walk me through publishing this for free with GitHub Pages, step by step,\" and it will guide you through it.","Now the one safety rule you must never break, because it can cost real money or expose your accounts. Some projects use \"API keys\" or passwords — an API key is a secret password that lets your project use an outside service (like sending email or connecting to a payment or AI service), and whoever has that key can run up charges on your account. NEVER let the AI paste a password or API key directly into your code. Instead, these secrets go into a special file named .env (short for \"environment\"), which holds them separately from the code.","There's a second half to that rule. When you publish to a service like GitHub, your files get uploaded to the internet — and you do not want your .env secrets file going with them. So you add a line naming .env to a file called .gitignore, which is simply a list of files to skip when uploading. Put .env in .gitignore and your secrets stay on your machine, invisible to the public, while the rest of your project ships. If you're ever unsure, ask Copilot: \"Did you put any secret keys directly in the code? Move them to a .env file and add .env to .gitignore.\" A good habit from day one saves a painful lesson later.","Two closing reminders to keep this fun and safe. First, save often and, once you're comfortable, let GitHub keep a history of your project so you can undo mistakes — Copilot will explain how. Second, keep the intern mindset: test everything the AI builds by actually clicking through it yourself. Copilot is astonishingly capable, but it is a confident assistant, not an oracle. You describe, it drafts, you verify — and with that rhythm, a complete beginner can genuinely ship real, working software this week."],"prompt":{"label":"Ask Copilot to check for exposed secrets","text":"Did you put any passwords, secret keys, or API keys directly in the code? If so, move every secret into a file called .env, reference it safely from the code, and add .env to a .gitignore file so it never gets uploaded when I publish. Then explain in plain English what you changed and why it matters."}}],"keyTerms":[{"term":"Code editor (IDE)","def":"The app where software is written, the way a word processor is where documents are written; VS Code is the popular free one this guide uses."},{"term":"Plugin / extension","def":"A small add-on that installs into a bigger app to give it new features — Copilot is a plugin that adds AI to the VS Code editor."},{"term":"Ghost text","def":"The faint gray code Copilot shows as a live suggestion while you type; press Tab to turn it into real code, or ignore it and keep going."},{"term":"Copilot Chat","def":"A sidebar inside the editor where you talk to the AI in plain English to request code, ask for fixes, or get explanations."},{"term":"Vibe coding","def":"Building software by describing what you want in everyday language and letting the AI write the code, then refining it through conversation."},{"term":"PRD (Program Requirements Document)","def":"A short plain-English blueprint of what you want built — its purpose, parts, and look — written before any code exists."},{"term":"GitHub account","def":"A free login for github.com, the website where developers worldwide store, share, and publish their code."},{"term":"API key","def":"A secret password that lets your project use an outside paid service; anyone who gets it can run up charges, so it must be kept out of your code."},{"term":".env and .gitignore files","def":"A .env file safely holds secret keys separate from your code, and listing it in a .gitignore file stops those secrets from being uploaded when you publish."}],"tips":["Plan your PRD with a different AI (Claude, ChatGPT, or Gemini) than the one you build with in Copilot — the second set of eyes catches gaps and mistakes the first would miss.","Refine one change at a time and test it before the next. If you request five changes at once and something breaks, you won't know which one caused it.","Start on the Free plan or, better, verify your student/teacher status at education.github.com for free unlimited access plus a bundle of other premium tools.","Treat AI code like work from an eager intern: functional but unverified. Actually click through and test everything yourself before trusting it.","Never let the AI paste passwords or API keys into your code — have it move secrets to a .env file and add .env to .gitignore before you ever publish."]},{"id":"vibe10","n":10,"g":"T","title":"Local Vibe Coding (Private & Free)","intro":"Every time you chat with a cloud AI like Claude or ChatGPT, your words travel over the internet to a company's servers, and heavy use eventually costs money. There's a private alternative: you can download an AI \"brain\" onto your own computer and use it to write code that never leaves your desk. This page shows a complete beginner, step by step, how to set up free, private, offline vibe coding using an open-weight model, and exactly when to still reach for a smarter cloud AI. Vibe coding just means building software by describing what you want in plain English and letting the AI write the actual code, then refining it through conversation.","tagline":"Turn your own laptop into a private, no-cost coding partner that works even with the Wi-Fi off.","sections":[{"heading":"What \"local\" means and why you'd want it","paras":["When you use Claude at claude.ai or ChatGPT at chat.openai.com, the AI itself lives in a giant data center. You type a message, it flies across the internet, the company's computers do the thinking, and the answer flies back. That's \"the cloud.\" It's powerful, but it has three catches: everything you type is handled by someone else's servers, heavy use eventually costs money (either a subscription or a small fee per message), and it stops working the moment your internet does.","\"Local\" flips all three. You download an open-weight model, a free AI file that anyone is allowed to run, onto your own machine, and it does the thinking right there. Nothing you type leaves your computer. There is no per-message cost, ever. And it keeps working on a plane, in a cabin, or anywhere with no signal. An \"open-weight\" model just means the company that trained it published the finished brain (the \"weights,\" the millions of numbers the AI learned) for free download, instead of locking it behind a website.","Picture a freelance bookkeeper writing a small script to reconcile a client's bank statements. That data is confidential, and she'd rather it never touch an outside server. Or a small-business owner tinkering with a tool that contains a secret pricing formula he doesn't want anywhere near a third party. For work that is sensitive, proprietary, or just personal, running the AI locally means the code and the conversation stay entirely under your roof. The trade-off, which we'll be honest about below, is that a model small enough to run on your laptop is generally not as sharp as a giant cloud model on the hardest problems."]},{"heading":"The two pieces you need: an engine and a coding tool","paras":["Running a local AI takes two separate pieces of software, and it helps to keep them straight from the start. The first is the engine, the program that actually loads the AI brain and runs it. The second is the coding tool, the friendly workspace where you type your plain-English requests and watch code appear. The engine is the motor; the coding tool is the dashboard and steering wheel you actually touch.","The two most popular engines for beginners are Ollama and LM Studio, both free. Ollama runs quietly in the background and is controlled with short typed commands, which sounds intimidating but is genuinely just copy-and-paste. LM Studio gives you a clickable window with buttons and a search box, more like an app store for AI models, so if the idea of typing commands makes you nervous, start there. Both are covered end to end in this Lab's Experimentation Station, which walks you through installing them from scratch.","Once an engine is running, it quietly opens a local address on your own computer that other programs can talk to. For Ollama this address is http://localhost:11434. Don't let that string scare you: \"localhost\" literally means \"this very computer,\" and the number is just a numbered doorway (called a port) that Ollama listens on. You almost never type this address by hand; you just paste it into your coding tool once so the tool knows where to find the local brain. That's the whole trick of local vibe coding, point a normal coding tool at that local address instead of at a company's cloud."]},{"heading":"Picking a coding model that fits your computer","paras":["A general chat model can write code, but a code-specialized model does it noticeably better, because it was trained on far more programming examples. The three best-known free ones are Qwen-Coder (often written qwen2.5-coder), Code Llama, and DeepSeek-Coder. Any of them is a fine starting point; Qwen-Coder is a strong, popular default in 2026.","Here's the one number that matters most: a model comes in different sizes, measured in \"billions of parameters\" and written with a b, like 7b or 14b. Bigger means smarter but heavier, it needs more of your computer's fast working memory to run at a usable speed. That memory is your RAM (the temporary workspace your computer uses while running programs) or, if your machine has a dedicated graphics card, its VRAM (the graphics card's own separate, faster memory). A rough rule for beginners: match the model size to the memory you have. The table below is your cheat sheet.","You don't have to guess or measure anything technical. On Windows, open Task Manager and look at the Memory figure; on a Mac, click the Apple menu, choose About This Mac, and read the Memory line. Whatever number you see, start one size smaller than you think you can afford, confirm it runs smoothly, then try the next size up. A model that's too big won't break anything, it just runs painfully slowly, at which point you switch to a smaller one. Downloading a model is a one-time step (the sizes below are the download size, so a 7b model is a roughly 5 GB download you do once)."],"table":{"headers":["Your computer's memory (RAM/VRAM)","Good model size to try","Example command","Roughly what to expect"],"rows":[["8 GB","1.5b or 3b","ollama run qwen2.5-coder:3b","Fast, fine for small scripts and simple sites"],["16 GB","7b","ollama run qwen2.5-coder:7b","The sweet spot for most laptops"],["32 GB","14b","ollama run qwen2.5-coder:14b","Noticeably smarter, still comfortable"],["64 GB+ or a strong graphics card","32b","ollama run qwen2.5-coder:32b","Closest a local model gets to cloud quality"]]},"prompt":{"label":"Download and start a coding model in Ollama (paste into your terminal)","text":"ollama run qwen2.5-coder:7b"}},{"heading":"Connecting Continue in VS Code to your local model (step by step)","paras":["The cleanest way for a beginner to actually write code with a local model is a free add-on called Continue that lives inside VS Code. VS Code (short for Visual Studio Code) is the world's most popular free code editor, essentially a souped-up text editor built for writing programs, and Continue adds an AI chat panel right beside your files. An \"extension\" is just an add-on you install into VS Code, the same way you add an extension to a web browser.","Here is the whole path from nothing to a working setup. Take it one line at a time; none of it is dangerous. First, install the engine and a model. Download Ollama from ollama.com and install it like any normal app. Then open your terminal (on Windows search for \"PowerShell,\" on Mac open the \"Terminal\" app; it's the plain window where you type commands) and paste the one command that both downloads the model and starts it. Leave that running.","Second, install the editor and the extension. Download VS Code from code.visualstudio.com and install it. Open it, click the Extensions icon in the left toolbar (it looks like four small squares), type \"Continue\" in the search box, and click Install on the Continue extension. A new Continue panel appears on the side.","Third, point Continue at Ollama. Continue keeps its settings in a small file called config.yaml (a plain text file of settings, stored in a hidden folder named .continue inside your user folder). Open Continue's settings and add a model block that names the Ollama provider and your model. The snippet below is the exact shape it expects, just make sure the model line matches whatever you downloaded (here, qwen2.5-coder:7b). Save the file, and Continue will now send your requests to the model running on your own machine instead of to the cloud. That's it, you're vibe coding locally.","From then on, the loop feels the same as any AI coding: type a plain-English request into the Continue panel (\"Make a webpage with my name, a photo, and three links to my social media\"), read the code it writes, ask it to change things (\"Make the background dark and center everything\"), and repeat. The only difference is that every word stayed on your computer and cost you nothing."],"prompt":{"label":"Continue config.yaml — point it at your local Ollama model","text":"name: My local setup\nversion: 0.0.1\nschema: v1\n\nmodels:\n  - name: Qwen Coder (local)\n    provider: ollama\n    model: qwen2.5-coder:7b\n    roles:\n      - chat\n      - edit\n      - autocomplete"}},{"heading":"Other ways to point a tool at your local model","paras":["Continue-in-VS-Code is the recommended starting point, but it isn't the only door. If you already use Cursor, a popular AI-first code editor that looks and feels like VS Code, you can go into its settings, open the Models section, and add a custom or local model that points at the same Ollama address (http://localhost:11434). Cursor is normally cloud-powered, but it can be told to talk to a local engine instead, which is handy if you want one editor that switches between local and cloud depending on the job.","LM Studio, mentioned earlier as an engine, has a bonus: it can act as a local server too, exposing its own local address that coding tools connect to in the same way. If you preferred LM Studio's clickable interface for downloading models, you can keep using it and still hook a coding tool up to it. The pattern never changes: an engine opens a local address, and a coding tool is told to use that address instead of a company's servers.","One honest caveat for total beginners: local setups involve a few more moving parts than just opening a website, so expect the very first connection to take a little patience. If the coding tool says it can't reach the model, 95% of the time the fix is simply that the engine isn't running, make sure your Ollama command is still going in its terminal window, or that LM Studio's server is switched on. Once connected, it stays connected."]},{"heading":"The smart pattern: plan and build local, escalate when it's hard","paras":["The most honest thing anyone can tell you about local models is that they are genuinely private and genuinely free, but generally weaker than the frontier cloud models, the biggest, smartest AIs like Claude, GPT, and Gemini, on the hardest tasks. \"Frontier\" just means the current top of the line. A local 7b model will happily build a personal webpage, a budgeting spreadsheet script, or a simple contact form. But hand it a gnarly bug that spans a dozen files, or an unusual, tricky feature, and it may go in circles where a frontier model would nail it in one shot.","So the professional move isn't \"local versus cloud,\" it's using each where it shines. A great everyday pattern has three beats. Plan first, ideally with a different, strong AI: describe your whole project and ask it to write a PRD, a Program Requirements Document, which is just a plain-language blueprint listing what the software should do, screen by screen and feature by feature. Planning with a different AI than the one you'll build with is a deliberate trick, a second AI catches gaps and bad assumptions the builder would have run with. Then build the routine, everyday code locally with your private model, keeping your data and costs at zero. Then, only when you hit a wall the local model can't climb, copy that specific stuck piece over to a frontier model for a focused rescue.","Think of any AI-written code the way you'd think of work from an eager, fast intern: it's usually functional, but it is unverified until you actually run it and check. That's true of cloud and local alike, so always test what the AI gives you before trusting it. Local coding simply lets you do the bulk of that iterating in private, for free, and reserve the paid cloud brainpower for the moments that truly need it. The full local-setup walkthroughs, installing Ollama and LM Studio, downloading models, and troubleshooting, live in this Lab's Experimentation Station; this page is your map for turning that local engine into a coding partner."],"prompt":{"label":"Plan first with a different AI — paste this to get a PRD before you build","text":"You are my software planning partner. I want to build a simple personal webpage that shows my name, a short bio, a photo, and links to my email and two social profiles. Before any code, write me a PRD (a plain-language blueprint): list every section of the page, what goes in each, and how it should look and behave. Ask me any questions you need first. Keep it beginner-friendly and don't write code yet."}},{"heading":"Keeping secrets safe, even on your own machine","paras":["One security habit matters from day one, and it's easy. Sometimes an app needs a secret: a password, or an API key, a long random string of characters that acts like a password letting your program use an outside service. The rule is simple: never let the AI paste a password or key directly into your code. It's tempting, and the AI may even do it by default, but code often gets shared or uploaded, and a secret sitting inside it is a leak waiting to happen.","Instead, secrets go in a separate little file conventionally named .env (short for \"environment\"), which holds lines like API_KEY=your-secret-here. Your code reads the secret from that file at runtime, so the secret and the code stay apart. Then you add .env to a file called .gitignore, a plain list of files that should never be uploaded when you publish your project. Adding .env to .gitignore is the seatbelt that stops your secrets from ever being shared by accident.","This matters even for local work, because the whole point of a local model is privacy, and the day you decide to publish your finished project, to free hosts like GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, or Replit, so friends or customers can use it, that habit is already in place and no secret rides along. If you're not sure whether something is a secret, treat it like one. Ask your AI, local or cloud, \"Does this code contain anything that should go in a .env file instead?\" and let it point out the risky lines before you ever hit publish."],"prompt":{"label":"Ask your AI to make your project secret-safe","text":"Review this project for security. Move any passwords, API keys, or secrets out of the code and into a .env file, show me the .env file, and create a .gitignore that lists .env so my secrets are never uploaded when I publish. Explain in plain English what each change does."}}],"keyTerms":[{"term":"Open-weight model","def":"A free AI brain whose maker published the finished file for anyone to download and run on their own computer, instead of locking it behind a website."},{"term":"Engine (Ollama / LM Studio)","def":"The background program that loads an AI model and runs it on your machine; Ollama is command-driven and LM Studio is a clickable app."},{"term":"localhost / port","def":"\"localhost\" means this very computer, and a port is a numbered doorway on it; Ollama listens for coding tools at the address http://localhost:11434."},{"term":"RAM and VRAM","def":"Your computer's fast temporary memory (RAM), and a graphics card's own separate faster memory (VRAM); more of either lets you run a bigger, smarter model."},{"term":"Parameters (the \"b\" in 7b)","def":"The number of learned values inside a model, in billions; a larger number like 14b means smarter but heavier, needing more memory to run smoothly."},{"term":"VS Code and extensions","def":"VS Code is the most popular free code editor, and an extension like Continue is an add-on you install into it, the way you add extensions to a web browser."},{"term":"Frontier model","def":"The current top-of-the-line cloud AIs (such as Claude, GPT, and Gemini) that are the strongest available but run on company servers, not your machine."},{"term":"PRD (Program Requirements Document)","def":"A plain-language blueprint of your app that lists every screen and feature before any code is written, best created with a different AI than the one you build with."},{"term":".env and .gitignore","def":"A .env file holds secrets like passwords and API keys separately from your code, and listing it in .gitignore ensures those secrets are never uploaded when you publish."}],"tips":["Start one model size smaller than you think your computer can handle, confirm it runs smoothly, then step up; a too-big model only runs slowly, it never breaks anything.","Keep the terminal window running Ollama (or LM Studio's server) open the whole time you code; the number-one reason a coding tool says it \"can't reach the model\" is simply that the engine stopped.","Prefer a code-specialized model (Qwen-Coder, Code Llama, DeepSeek-Coder) over a general chat model for building, it writes noticeably cleaner code.","Use the three-beat pattern: plan the PRD with a strong (even cloud) AI, build routine code locally for free and private, and copy only the truly hard, stuck piece to a frontier model when needed.","Treat every AI's code like an eager intern's work, functional but unverified: run it and check it before you trust it, whether it came from a local or cloud model.","Set up the .env-plus-.gitignore secret habit on your very first project so no password or API key can ever ride along when you later publish to GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, or Replit."]},{"id":"vibe11","n":11,"g":"P","title":"Project — Personal Finance Dashboard","intro":"Imagine dragging your bank statement onto a web page and, seconds later, watching it bloom into colorful charts that show exactly where your money went last month: a fat bar for restaurants, a thinner one for gas, a line that climbs every December. Now imagine you built that tool yourself, this weekend, without writing a single line of code by hand. That is the promise of vibe coding, a term coined by AI researcher Andrej Karpathy for building software by describing what you want in plain English and letting an AI write the actual code, then refining it through back-and-forth conversation. In this project you will build a Personal Finance Dashboard: a private, single-page web app that reads a raw CSV bank or credit-card statement and turns it into beautiful, interactive spending charts. The best part: your financial data never leaves your own browser.","tagline":"Turn a boring bank-statement export into a gorgeous, private spending dashboard you built yourself, in a single weekend, without knowing how to code.","sections":[{"heading":"What you're building, and why it's genuinely useful","paras":["The finished product is a single web page you open in your browser. It has a dark, modern look and a big drop zone in the middle that says something like \"Drag your statement here.\" You grab the CSV file your bank let you download, drag it onto that zone, and let go. Instantly the page fills with two charts: a bar chart ranking your biggest spending categories (groceries, dining, subscriptions, gas) from largest to smallest, and a line chart showing how your total spending rose and fell across the weeks or months. No sign-up, no monthly fee, no company on the other end collecting your transactions.","A CSV is simpler than it sounds. It stands for Comma-Separated Values, and it is just a spreadsheet saved as plain text: each row is one transaction, and the columns (date, description, amount, sometimes a category) are separated by commas. Almost every bank and credit-card website has an \"Export\" or \"Download\" button that hands you exactly this kind of file. If you open one in a text editor it looks like a wall of lines such as 2026-03-14,STARBUCKS #1234,-5.75 — not pretty, but perfectly readable to a program.","Why bother building this instead of paying for a budgeting app? Three reasons that matter to real people. A freelancer juggling business and personal cards can finally see, at a glance, how much went to software subscriptions last quarter. A small-business owner can spot that their \"miscellaneous\" spending quietly doubled since spring. A hobbyist reselling on the side can check whether shipping costs are eating their margins. And because everything runs locally in your browser, none of these people have to trust a third-party company with their bank data. Privacy is not a bonus feature here; it is the whole point."]},{"heading":"Set up your tools (pick one path, all are beginner-friendly)","paras":["To vibe code, you need two things: an AI that writes code, and a place to run it. You do not need to install a programming language or understand what any of the code means. Below are three setups, from easiest to most private. Pick whichever matches how much you want to fiddle. Any of them can build this project.","The fastest path needs nothing installed. Go to claude.ai (Claude, Anthropic's AI assistant) or chat.openai.com (ChatGPT) in your normal browser. Both can write a complete web app and show you a live preview right inside the chat — Claude calls this feature Artifacts, ChatGPT calls it Canvas. You paste your request, the AI writes the app, a working preview appears next to the conversation, and you refine it by simply typing \"make the bars blue\" or \"the dates aren't sorting right.\" Replit (replit.com) and Bolt.new are similar browser-based build-it-live options. This is the recommended way to start.","The more powerful path uses an AI code editor. Cursor (cursor.com — free for students at cursor.com/students) and Windsurf are downloadable apps that look like a normal text editor but have an AI built in that can see all your files and edit them for you. GitHub Copilot is an AI assistant that plugs into editors and is free for verified students and teachers at education.github.com, otherwise around ten dollars a month. Connect any of these to Claude and you get a smoother experience for a multi-step project, plus the app files saved on your own computer.","The most private path runs the AI on your own machine so nothing you type ever touches the internet. Tools called Ollama and LM Studio let you download and run open-source AI models locally, such as Qwen-Coder, a model specialized in writing code. This takes the most setup and a reasonably capable computer, but it means both the AI and your finished app are fully offline. For a first project, start in the browser and graduate to local later if you enjoy it."],"table":{"headers":["Setup","Where it runs","Best for","Cost"],"rows":[["Claude (Artifacts) or ChatGPT (Canvas)","Your browser, in the chat","Absolute beginners; live preview as you go","Free tier works"],["Cursor / Windsurf + Claude","Downloaded editor app","A real project saved on your computer","Cursor free for students"],["GitHub Copilot in an editor","Downloaded editor app","Autocomplete-style help while building","Free for students/teachers, else ~$10/mo"],["Ollama / LM Studio + Qwen-Coder","Fully local, offline","Maximum privacy, no internet needed","Free, needs a capable PC"]]}},{"heading":"Step 1 of the loop: write a PRD (your plain-language blueprint)","paras":["Vibe coding works best as a three-step loop: first you write a PRD, then you build it with an AI, then you test and refine. A PRD is a Program Requirements Document — a fancy name for a short, plain-English description of what your app should do, who it's for, and what \"done\" looks like. Think of it as the note you'd hand a contractor before they build a deck: it doesn't tell them how to swing a hammer, it tells them what you want at the end.","Here is the golden rule that separates good results from frustrating ones: plan the PRD with a DIFFERENT AI than the one you'll code with. Ask one AI (say, Google Gemini or ChatGPT) to help you think through and write the requirements. Then take that finished PRD to your coding AI (say, Claude) to actually build it. Using two different AIs is like having an architect draw the plans and a separate builder construct them — the builder catches gaps the architect missed, and you end up with a clearer, more complete result.","You don't have to write the PRD from a blank page. Open your planning AI and paste the prompt below to have it interview you and draft the document. Answer its questions in plain language — \"my file has a Date column and an Amount column,\" \"I want it to look dark and modern,\" \"I mostly care about my top five spending categories\" — and it will assemble a tidy blueprint you can hand off."],"prompt":{"label":"Paste this into your PLANNING AI (a different one than you'll build with)","text":"I want to build a simple, private web app called a Personal Finance Dashboard. It should let me drag and drop a CSV file exported from my bank or credit card, read it entirely inside my browser (my data must never be uploaded anywhere), group my transactions by category, and show me charts of my spending. Act as a product manager and help me write a short, plain-English PRD (Program Requirements Document) for it. Ask me any clarifying questions one at a time — about my CSV's columns, the look I want, and which charts matter most — then give me the finished PRD I can hand to a coding AI."}},{"heading":"Step 2: give your coding AI the intent command","paras":["Once your PRD is ready, open your coding AI (Claude with Artifacts is the smoothest for this) and give it the PRD first, then follow with the single \"intent command\" below. The intent command is the precise instruction that tells the AI exactly what to build. Paste it verbatim — it has been written to hit every requirement in one shot, and it is deliberately specific about the one thing that matters most: your data stays on your machine.","Notice the important phrases packed into it. \"Single-page HTML application\" means the whole thing is one self-contained file you can open by double-clicking — no complicated installation. \"Chart.js\" is a free, popular charting library, meaning a ready-made toolkit of code other people wrote so your AI doesn't have to invent charts from scratch. \"Parse it in the browser\" means read and process the file locally. And the final sentence — do not upload my data anywhere — is the guardrail that keeps this private. Say it out loud in your prompt every time.","After you send this, watch the AI write the code and, in Claude's Artifacts or ChatGPT's Canvas, render a live, clickable preview. Drag in a real (or a fake test) CSV and see what happens. It probably won't be perfect on the first try — and that is completely normal, not a sign you did anything wrong."],"prompt":{"label":"THE INTENT COMMAND — paste your PRD first, then this, into your CODING AI","text":"Build a single-page HTML application with a dark-mode theme. Create a drag-and-drop zone where I can upload a standard CSV file (a spreadsheet exported from my bank). Parse it in the browser, group transactions by category, and use Chart.js to render a bar chart of my top spending categories and a line chart of spending over time. Everything must run locally in the browser — do not upload my data anywhere."}},{"heading":"Step 3: test and refine (talk to it like a helpful, eager intern)","paras":["Here is the honest truth about AI-written code: it's like work from an eager, fast, tireless intern. It will confidently hand you something that mostly works — and it may quietly get a detail wrong. Maybe your bank's CSV puts the amount in a column the AI didn't expect, or negative numbers (which usually mean money spent) got treated as income, or the dates sorted alphabetically instead of chronologically so December landed before February. None of this is a disaster. You fix it the same way you'd correct an intern: describe what you see, plainly, and ask for the change.","Refining is just more conversation. You don't edit code; you report symptoms. Real examples of what you'd type back: \"The bar chart is empty even though the file loaded — can you check how you're reading the Amount column?\" or \"My categories all show up as one blob called 'undefined,' my CSV's category column is named 'Type'\" or \"Round the dollar amounts to two decimals\" or \"The line chart should go left-to-right from oldest to newest month.\" The AI reads your feedback, rewrites the relevant code, and the preview updates. Repeat until it feels right — usually a handful of rounds.","Two safety habits worth building from day one, even though this particular project doesn't need them. First: never let an AI put passwords or secret keys (called API keys — the private passwords that let programs use paid online services) directly into your code. If a future project needs one, store it in a special file named .env and add that file's name to another file called .gitignore, which is a list of files to never upload. This keeps your secrets off the public internet. Second: read what the AI wrote at least loosely, and test with a copy of your data, never your only copy. For this dashboard, since nothing is uploaded and no keys are involved, you can experiment freely — worst case you refresh the page and start over."]},{"heading":"Stretch goals and publishing it to the world","paras":["Once the core dashboard works, you'll want to push it further — and adding features is the same loop: just ask. Realistic, satisfying upgrades include category filters (checkboxes or a dropdown so you can hide \"Rent\" and see how the rest of your spending really breaks down), a budget line (a horizontal reference line across the chart at, say, $2,000 so you can instantly see which months you blew past your limit), and an \"export to PNG\" button that saves your finished chart as an image you can drop into a spreadsheet or send to your accountant. Each of these is a one-sentence request to your coding AI.","When you're proud of it, you can put it online for free so it's reachable from any device — or keep it entirely on your computer, which for a finance tool is a perfectly good choice. If you do want to publish, free hosting services will take your single HTML file and give you a real web address: GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, and Replit all do this at no cost. Netlify is famously beginner-friendly — you can literally drag your file onto their website and get a live link. Because your app processes everything in the visitor's own browser and uploads nothing, publishing it doesn't expose your data; only the empty tool goes online, not your statements.","Try one stretch goal this weekend by pasting a request like the one below. Ask for changes one at a time rather than all at once — it's easier to spot what broke if you only changed one thing."],"prompt":{"label":"A stretch-goal request to paste into your coding AI","text":"This is working great. Now add three features, and show me the result after each one: (1) a set of category checkboxes above the bar chart so I can show or hide individual spending categories, (2) a horizontal budget line on the line chart at a monthly amount I can set at the top of the file, and (3) a \"Download chart as PNG\" button under each chart. Keep everything running locally in the browser with no uploads."}},{"heading":"What you'll walk away knowing","paras":["Even though the AI wrote the code, you will finish this project genuinely more capable — because you directed every part of it and watched cause and effect play out. You'll understand, in concrete terms, how a web page can read a file the user drops in without sending it anywhere, which is the foundation of privacy-respecting tools. You'll have seen how raw rows of numbers become a chart, and how a small library like Chart.js does the heavy lifting. And you'll have lived the three-step vibe-coding loop — plan a PRD with one AI, build with another, then test and refine through plain conversation — which is the exact same process behind far more ambitious apps.","Most importantly, you'll have proof that the barrier to building software has genuinely dropped. A freelancer who has never opened a code editor can now spin up a custom tool that no off-the-shelf app offers, tailored to their own bank's quirky CSV format, in an afternoon. The dashboard is small enough to actually finish and useful enough that you'll open it again next month. That combination — a real, finished, useful thing you made by describing it — is the whole reason to try. Pick your tool, write your PRD, and give it a go today."]}],"keyTerms":[{"term":"Vibe coding","def":"Building software by describing what you want in plain English and letting an AI write the code, then refining it through conversation."},{"term":"CSV file","def":"Comma-Separated Values — a spreadsheet saved as plain text, where each line is a row and columns are separated by commas; the standard format banks let you export."},{"term":"PRD (Program Requirements Document)","def":"A short, plain-language blueprint describing what your app should do, who it's for, and what a finished version looks like — written before any code."},{"term":"Intent command","def":"The precise, all-in-one instruction you hand your coding AI after the PRD, telling it exactly what to build."},{"term":"Chart.js","def":"A free, widely used charting library — a ready-made bundle of code that draws bar charts, line charts, and more so the AI doesn't build them from scratch."},{"term":"Single-page HTML application","def":"A whole app contained in one self-contained file you can open just by double-clicking it, with no installation required."},{"term":"Code editor / AI IDE","def":"A text-editor app for writing code (like Cursor or Windsurf) that has an AI built in to write and edit your files for you."},{"term":"API key","def":"A private password that lets a program use a paid online service; it must be kept secret and never written directly into code that could be shared or uploaded."},{"term":".env and .gitignore","def":"A .env file safely stores secrets like API keys outside your code, and listing it in a .gitignore file ensures it is never uploaded to the internet."}],"tips":["Always plan the PRD with a different AI than the one you build with — the second AI catches gaps the first one glossed over, giving you a sharper, more complete result.","Test with a small, fake CSV first (make up five or six rows of transactions in a spreadsheet and save as CSV) before feeding in your real statement — it's faster to spot bugs on data you already understand.","When something looks wrong, describe the symptom, not a fix: say 'the bar chart is empty even though the file loaded' rather than guessing at the code — the AI is better at diagnosing than you are, and this is exactly how you'd brief a capable intern.","Change one thing at a time when refining. Ask for a single feature or fix per message so that if something breaks, you know precisely what caused it.","Keep the sentence 'do not upload my data anywhere' in every prompt about this app — repeating the privacy requirement keeps the AI from ever reaching for a cloud service to 'help.'"]},{"id":"vibe12","n":12,"g":"P","title":"Project — Private Document Q&A Portal","tagline":"This weekend, turn a messy folder of PDFs, contracts, and notes into a private chatbot you can ask anything — running entirely on your own computer, with no confidential file ever leaving it.","intro":"Imagine dropping a pile of your own documents — client contracts, product manuals, tax paperwork, research papers, years of meeting notes — into a little app, then typing \"What's the cancellation clause in the Riverside contract?\" and getting an instant, accurate answer that even tells you which file it came from. That is what you're going to build: a private \"chat with your files\" tool. The technical name for this is RAG, short for Retrieval-Augmented Generation — a fancy label for a simple idea we'll unpack completely below. The best part: you will describe what you want in plain English and let an AI write the actual code for you. This is called \"vibe coding,\" and by the end of this page you'll believe you can build this yourself, because you can.","sections":[{"heading":"What you're building, and why it's genuinely cool","paras":["Picture a freelancer who has signed forty different client contracts over three years. Every time a payment dispute comes up, they dig through folders trying to remember which contract said what about late fees. Or picture a small-business owner with a shelf of equipment manuals and a new employee who keeps asking 'how do I reset the espresso machine?' A private Document Q&A Portal solves both problems: it reads a whole folder of your documents once, and from then on you just ask questions in plain language and get grounded, specific answers back — with a citation showing exactly which file and roughly which part the answer came from.","The magic word is 'grounded.' A normal AI chatbot like ChatGPT is confident but forgetful — it was trained on the public internet and knows nothing about YOUR contracts, and if you ask it about them it will happily invent plausible-sounding nonsense (the industry calls this 'hallucination'). Your portal is different. It answers ONLY from the documents you gave it. If the answer isn't in your files, it says so instead of making something up. That trustworthiness is the entire point.","The second reason this is cool: privacy. There are commercial 'chat with your documents' services online, but they require you to upload your confidential files to someone else's servers. If your documents contain client data, medical records, salary figures, or trade secrets, that's a non-starter. The version you'll build can run 100% locally — the AI model lives on your own laptop, the documents never touch the internet, and you could unplug your Wi-Fi mid-conversation and it would keep working. For anyone handling sensitive material, that's not a nice-to-have; it's the whole reason to build your own instead of paying for a cloud tool.","And you'll build it this weekend, without knowing how to code, by having a conversation with an AI that writes the code for you."]},{"heading":"RAG and embeddings, explained from zero","paras":["Let's demystify the two scary terms, because once they click, the whole project makes sense. Start with the problem: an AI model can only 'think about' a limited amount of text at once (its 'context window'). You cannot paste 400 pages of contracts into a chat box — it won't fit, and even if it did, it'd be slow and expensive. So how does the AI answer a question about 400 pages? It doesn't read all 400. Instead, it RETRIEVES only the handful of paragraphs that are actually relevant to your question, and then GENERATES an answer from just those. Retrieval, then generation. That two-step dance is literally what RAG — Retrieval-Augmented Generation — means. The 'augmented' part just means the AI's answer is boosted by real facts pulled from your files, instead of relying on its fuzzy memory.","Now, how does the app know which paragraphs are relevant? This is where 'embeddings' come in, and it's beautiful once you see it. An embedding is a way of turning a piece of text into a list of numbers that captures its MEANING. Think of it like a GPS coordinate, but for ideas instead of places: sentences about similar topics get placed near each other, and sentences about unrelated topics land far apart. 'The dog chased the ball' and 'a puppy ran after the toy' would get nearly identical coordinates even though they share almost no words, because they mean nearly the same thing. 'Quarterly revenue rose 12%' would land in a completely different neighborhood.","So here's the full pipeline your app performs. First, when you upload documents, it CHUNKS them — chops each document into bite-sized pieces (say, a paragraph or two each), because whole files are too big to work with. Second, it turns every chunk into an embedding (those meaning-coordinates) and stores them in a searchable index. Third, when you type a question, it turns your question into an embedding too, and finds the chunks whose coordinates sit closest to your question's coordinates — those are the most relevant passages. Fourth, it hands only those few relevant chunks to the AI along with your question and says, in effect, 'answer this using only this text.' The AI writes a clean answer, and your app shows you which file each chunk came from.","That's it. RAG is 'find the relevant bits, then answer from them.' Embeddings are 'turn text into meaning-numbers so 'relevant' can be measured.' You don't have to implement any of this by hand — the AI coding tools will write it — but understanding the shape of it means you can tell when something's wrong and ask for the right fix."]},{"heading":"The exact tool setup — pick your path","paras":["You have two roads to the same destination, and you should choose based on how private your documents are. Both are beginner-friendly.","Road A — the browser build with Replit. Replit (replit.com) is a website where you build and run software entirely in your browser — nothing to install, no terminal (that intimidating black window where programmers type commands). Replit has an 'Agent' feature: you describe the app you want in plain English, and it writes, runs, and hosts it for you. This is the fastest way to SEE your portal working — you could have a live version in twenty minutes. The trade-off: your documents get uploaded to Replit's servers while the app runs, so use this road for documents that aren't truly sensitive (public manuals, your own notes, research papers) or just to learn the ropes before going private.","Road B — the fully-private local build. Here the AI model that generates answers lives on your own computer, so no document ever leaves it. The engine that runs the model is called Ollama (ollama.com) — a free program you install once that downloads and runs open AI models locally. Your app talks to Ollama on your machine, and the whole thing works with your Wi-Fi off. This is the road for contracts, client data, or anything confidential. To build it, you'll use an AI code editor on your computer — Cursor (cursor.com, an AI-powered code editor, free for students at cursor.com/students) or Claude Code (Anthropic's terminal-based coding agent) are excellent — and describe the app the same way you would to Replit.","Either road produces the same kind of app, built with two beginner-friendly technologies your AI will use automatically: Python (a programming language famous for being readable) and Streamlit (a tool that turns a plain Python script into a simple, clickable web app with buttons, file uploaders, and chat boxes — no web-design knowledge required). You will not write Python yourself. You just need to know these words so you understand what the AI is doing.","One more essential companion: before you code, download Ollama and install a small local model with a single command. This gives your app a private brain to think with."],"prompt":{"label":"One-time terminal command to give your local build a private AI brain (after installing Ollama)","text":"ollama pull llama3.2"}},{"heading":"Plan first: write a PRD with a DIFFERENT AI than the one that codes","paras":["Here's the single habit that separates a smooth build from a frustrating one: plan before you build, and plan with a different AI than the one you'll code with. A PRD — Program Requirements Document — is just a plain-language blueprint describing what your app should do, who it's for, and what 'done' looks like. It's a page of English, not code. Writing one forces you to make decisions up front instead of discovering halfway through that you never decided what file types to accept.","Why a different AI? Because using a second AI to plan gives you a fresh perspective that catches gaps and bad assumptions before they get baked into code — the way a friend proofreading your email spots the typo you've read past ten times. A practical combo: plan the PRD with ChatGPT (chat.openai.com) or Google Gemini, then hand that finished PRD to your coding AI (Cursor, Claude, or Replit's Agent) to actually build. The planner thinks about the 'what' and 'why'; the coder handles the 'how.'","To generate your PRD, open a planning AI and paste the prompt below. Answer its follow-up questions (it will ask things like 'how many documents?' and 'do you need to handle scanned PDFs?'), and it will hand you back a tidy blueprint. Keep that blueprint — you'll paste it to your coding AI in the next step, right before the build command."],"prompt":{"label":"Paste into a planning AI (ChatGPT or Gemini) to generate your PRD","text":"You are my product planner. Help me write a short, plain-language PRD (Program Requirements Document) for a beginner-friendly app I'll build by describing it to a coding AI. The app is a PRIVATE Document Q&A Portal: it indexes a folder of my own documents (PDFs and text files like contracts, manuals, and notes) and answers my questions using ONLY those documents, showing which file each answer came from. It must run locally for privacy, using Python, Streamlit, a local embedding model, and a local Ollama model. Ask me any clarifying questions first (how many documents, what file types, any must-have features), then produce the PRD with these sections: Goal, Who it's for, Core features, What it should NOT do, and a simple definition of 'done.' Keep it under one page and free of jargon."}},{"heading":"The build: the exact intent command to give your coding AI","paras":["Now the fun part. Open your coding AI — Replit Agent for the browser build, or Cursor / Claude for the local build. First paste your PRD from the previous step so the AI has context, then paste the 'intent command' below. An intent command is one clear paragraph describing the whole app in plain English; the AI reads it and writes all the code, wires the pieces together, and starts the app running.","The command below is deliberately complete: it names every part of the pipeline you learned about — the file uploader, the chunking, the local embeddings, the storage, and the chat box that answers only from your files and cites its sources. That specificity is what gets you a working app instead of a vague half-thing. Paste it exactly as written.","When you run it, watch the AI work like an eager, fast intern. It will create files, install the tools it needs, and launch a little web page — usually opening automatically in your browser or giving you a link to click. Within a few minutes you'll see a real app: a sidebar with an 'upload' button on the left, and a chat box in the middle. Do NOT expect perfection on the first try. If something errors out, copy the red error message, paste it back to the AI, and say 'this happened, please fix it.' This back-and-forth IS vibe coding — you're refining through conversation, not debugging by hand.","A crucial honesty note: AI-written code is like work from a talented but unsupervised intern — it's usually functional, but you must verify it does what you think. Test it with a document whose contents you already know, and check that the citations point to the right file. Never trust an answer you can't trace back to a source."],"prompt":{"label":"THE INTENT COMMAND — paste into your coding AI (after your PRD)","text":"Create a Python web app using Streamlit. Add a sidebar file uploader that accepts PDFs and text files. When files are uploaded, split their text into small chunks, turn the chunks into embeddings with a LOCAL model, and store them so I can ask questions. Give me a chat box that answers ONLY from the uploaded documents and shows which file each answer came from."}},{"heading":"What the finished thing looks like — and how to test it","paras":["When it's working, you'll have a clean web page open in your browser. Down the left side is a sidebar with a file uploader — you click it, select your PDFs and text files, and a little progress note tells you it's reading and indexing them (that's the chunking-and-embedding pipeline running). In the middle is a chat box exactly like ChatGPT. You type a question, hit enter, and a moment later a grounded answer appears — followed by a small note like 'Source: Riverside_Contract.pdf.' That citation is the trust signal: it means the answer came from your actual document, not the AI's imagination.","Give it a real test drive. A marketer might upload a folder of past campaign briefs and ask 'which campaigns targeted customers under 30, and what was the budget?' A hobbyist restoring an old car might upload three shop manuals and ask 'what's the torque spec for the head bolts on the 1972 engine?' A consultant might load every proposal they've written and ask 'summarize how I've priced discovery workshops in the past.' In each case the app finds the relevant chunks and answers from them — no re-reading hundreds of pages.","Here's the most important test of all, because it proves the app isn't lying to you: ask it something that is definitely NOT in your documents. Ask your contract portal 'what's the capital of France?' A well-built RAG app will say something like 'I couldn't find that in your documents' rather than confidently answering from general knowledge. If it DOES answer off-topic questions, that's a bug — paste this correction to your coding AI and it will tighten the behavior."],"prompt":{"label":"Fix prompt if the app answers questions that aren't in your documents","text":"When my question can't be answered from the retrieved document chunks, the app should clearly say it couldn't find the answer in my documents, instead of using the model's general knowledge. Please update the prompt sent to the model so it only answers from the provided chunks, and add a short note under each answer showing which file the information came from."}},{"heading":"Stretch goals, publishing, and staying safe","paras":["Once the basic portal works, there's a natural ladder of upgrades — each one a single new conversation with your AI. Ask it to 'remember the conversation' so you can ask follow-up questions ('and what about the SECOND contract?'). Ask it to add a filter so you can search within just one folder or one client. Ask it to handle scanned PDFs (documents that are really pictures of text) by adding OCR — Optical Character Recognition, which reads text out of images. Ask it to show a short preview of the exact sentence a citation came from, so you can double-check. Ask it to let you download the whole conversation as a text file. Each of these is a one-paragraph request; the AI does the work.","If you want to share your creation — say the Replit browser version, built from public documents — you can publish it free. GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, and Replit all offer free hosting for finished projects; Replit's is a one-click 'Deploy' button, the gentlest for beginners. (Note: the truly-private local version is meant to run only on your own machine — that's the whole point — so you generally would NOT publish that one.)","Two security basics that matter even for beginners. First, if any version of your app ever uses an online service that requires an API key — a long secret password that identifies you to that service — NEVER let the AI paste that key directly into the code. Instead, keep it in a special file named .env (a plain text file that holds secrets), and add that filename to another file called .gitignore (a list of files that should never be uploaded when you share your code). This keeps your secret out of anything you publish. Just tell your AI 'store the API key in a .env file and add it to .gitignore' and it will handle it. Second, remember the whole reason you chose the local road: for confidential documents, use the Ollama-based build so nothing leaves your computer. When in doubt about privacy, watch your network activity indicator during a chat — on the local build, it stays silent.","And if this whole project feels like more than you want to code — even the vibe-coded way — there's a genuinely excellent no-code alternative that does exactly this out of the box: AnythingLLM (a private 'chat with your documents' app, covered in the Experimentation Station of this Lab). You install it, point it at your local Ollama engine, drop in your files, and start asking questions — zero code. Building your own portal teaches you how the machinery works; AnythingLLM is the instant, batteries-included version. Both are worth trying, and knowing the concepts from this page will make AnythingLLM feel obvious."],"prompt":{"label":"Ask your AI to secure any API keys (only needed if you add an online service)","text":"Do not put any API keys or passwords directly in the code. Store them in a .env file, load them from there at runtime, and add .env to a .gitignore file so my secrets are never uploaded when I share this project."}},{"heading":"What you'll walk away knowing","paras":["This one weekend project quietly teaches you the four skills behind a huge share of today's practical AI tools. First, RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) — the dominant pattern for making an AI answer accurately from a specific body of knowledge instead of guessing; every 'chat with your docs,' internal company assistant, and customer-support bot is built on it. Understand RAG and you understand how most useful business AI actually works.","Second, embeddings — turning text into meaning-numbers so a computer can measure how related two pieces of text are. This same idea powers semantic search, recommendation systems, and 'find similar' features everywhere. Third, file handling — taking messy real-world documents (PDFs, text files, maybe scans) and turning them into something a program can work with, which is unglamorous but foundational to almost every data project. And fourth, keeping data local and private — a skill that becomes more valuable, not less, as more of life moves to the cloud, and one that lets you confidently work with sensitive material AI-powered without handing it to a stranger.","But the biggest thing you'll walk away with isn't on that list. It's the realization, in your gut rather than in theory, that you can build real, useful software by describing it in plain English and refining through conversation. Once you've watched an AI turn your paragraph into a working app that answers questions about your own files, 'I can't code' stops being true. The next project — a personal finance tracker, a habit dashboard, a tool that summarizes your inbox — becomes just another conversation. That confidence is the real deliverable."]}],"keyTerms":[{"term":"RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation)","def":"A method where the AI first retrieves the few relevant passages from your own documents, then generates an answer using only those passages, so it stays accurate instead of making things up."},{"term":"Embedding","def":"A way of turning a piece of text into a list of numbers that captures its meaning, so the app can measure which passages are most related to your question — like a GPS coordinate for ideas."},{"term":"Chunking","def":"Chopping each document into small, bite-sized pieces (roughly a paragraph each) so the AI can work with manageable amounts of text instead of an entire file at once."},{"term":"Hallucination","def":"When an AI confidently states something false because it's filling gaps from fuzzy memory rather than real facts — exactly what RAG is designed to prevent."},{"term":"Streamlit","def":"A tool that turns a plain Python script into a simple, clickable web app — complete with buttons, file uploaders, and chat boxes — without any web-design knowledge."},{"term":"Ollama","def":"A free program you install once that downloads and runs open AI models directly on your own computer, so answers can be generated with no internet and no data leaving your machine."},{"term":"Terminal","def":"The plain text window where you type commands to your computer instead of clicking buttons; the browser-based build lets you avoid it entirely, while the local build uses it just once or twice."},{"term":".env file and .gitignore","def":"A .env file is a plain text file that safely holds secrets like passwords or API keys, and .gitignore is a list telling the computer never to upload those secret files when you share your code."},{"term":"PRD (Program Requirements Document)","def":"A short, plain-language blueprint describing what your app should do, who it's for, and what 'finished' looks like — written before any code, ideally with a different AI than the one that builds it."}],"tips":["Plan the PRD with one AI (ChatGPT or Gemini) and build with a different one (Cursor, Claude, or Replit Agent) — the fresh second perspective catches bad assumptions before they get baked into your code.","Always test your portal with a question whose answer is NOT in your documents; a trustworthy RAG app admits it can't find the answer instead of inventing one, and that's your best signal that it's built correctly.","Treat every error message as a gift, not a failure — copy the exact red text, paste it back to your AI, and say 'this happened, please fix it.' That conversation IS the building process.","For anything confidential (contracts, client data, medical notes), use the local Ollama build, not the browser one — then confirm privacy by watching your network indicator stay silent during a chat.","Verify AI-written code like you'd verify an eager intern's work: test with a document you already know cold, and never trust an answer whose citation you can't trace back to the right file.","If coding it yourself feels like too much, install AnythingLLM (in the Experimentation Station) for the same 'chat with your documents' result with zero code — the concepts you learned here make it instantly familiar."]},{"id":"vibe13","n":13,"g":"P","title":"Project — Lead-Gen Web Scraper","intro":"Imagine describing a boring, repetitive task out loud — \"go to these 30 websites, grab the important text, find any email addresses, and dump it all into a spreadsheet\" — and then having a computer actually do it while you make coffee. That is exactly what you're going to build on this page, and you'll do it without writing a single line of code yourself. Instead, you'll describe what you want in plain English and let an AI write the code for you. This is called vibe coding (a term coined by AI researcher Andrej Karpathy): you supply the intent, the AI supplies the syntax, and the two of you refine it together through conversation. By the end of this weekend you could have a small, reusable tool — a \"web scraper\" — that turns hours of copy-pasting into a 90-second click.","tagline":"Build a real, working tool this weekend that visits a list of websites, cleans out the clutter, harvests contact emails, and hands you a tidy spreadsheet — all by describing it in plain English.","sections":[{"heading":"What you're building and why it's genuinely useful","paras":["A \"web scraper\" is a program that visits web pages automatically and pulls out specific pieces of information, the same way you might open a page, skim past the ads and menus, and copy the one paragraph or email address you actually care about. The difference is that the program never gets tired, never gets distracted, and can do a hundred pages in the time it takes you to do one. The scraper you'll build reads a plain list of web addresses (called URLs — the \"https://...\" strings in your browser's address bar), visits each one, strips away the junk (ads, navigation menus, footers, cookie banners), keeps the meaningful body text, hunts for any email addresses on the page, and writes everything into an Excel spreadsheet with neat columns.","Picture who this helps. A freelance web designer wants to reach small restaurants in her city — she has a directory page listing 40 of them and needs each one's contact email and a sentence about what they do. A hobbyist beekeeper is compiling a reading list from a dozen gardening blogs and wants the article titles and text saved so he can search them offline. A small-business owner selling custom mugs wants to find craft-fair organizers to pitch, and there's a regional events site with 60 listings. In every case the work is identical, mind-numbing, and perfect for a machine: open page, find the useful bits, paste into a row, repeat. That repetition is the signal that a tiny script will pay for itself almost immediately.","The output is deliberately humble and that's the point: not a flashy app, just a spreadsheet file (a .xlsx, the format Microsoft Excel and Google Sheets both open) with columns for the URL, the page title, the cleaned-up text, and any emails found. You can sort it, filter it, hand it to a colleague, or paste it into your email tool. Small, boring, and quietly powerful — the best kind of first project because you'll immediately see it doing real work you used to do by hand."]},{"heading":"The exact setup — the tools and where the code will run","paras":["You need three things, and none of them cost money to start. First, a coding AI — the assistant that actually writes the code. The best fit for this project is a \"terminal agent,\" meaning an AI that can not only write code but also run it and fix its own mistakes. Two great options: Claude Code (from Anthropic, the same family as the Claude you chat with at claude.ai) or the Gemini CLI (from Google). Both live in your \"terminal.\" The terminal is simply a plain text window where you type commands instead of clicking buttons — it looks intimidating because it's usually black with monospaced text, but you'll only type a handful of things into it, and the AI does the rest. If a terminal feels like too much for a first try, you can instead use Replit (replit.com), which gives you a full coding workspace inside your web browser with an AI built in, so there's nothing to install at all.","Second, you need a place for the code to actually run. This project uses Node.js — a free program that lets JavaScript (the language of the web) run on your own computer instead of only inside a web page. You install it once from nodejs.org (pick the version labeled \"LTS,\" which means Long-Term Support — the stable one). When someone says your script is a \"Node.js utility,\" they just mean a small program you launch by typing its name in the terminal. The AI will handle the actual JavaScript; you mostly need Node.js sitting there ready.","Third, the scraper needs a \"headless browser.\" A normal browser like Chrome shows you a window with pixels. A headless browser is the exact same web-browsing engine with the window switched off — invisible, controlled entirely by your program. It's essential here because modern websites often build their content with JavaScript after the page loads, so simply downloading the raw page misses text a human would see. The headless browser loads the page fully, just like Chrome would, so your script sees what you'd see. You do not install this yourself — when you give the AI the command below, it will pick a well-known headless-browser library (likely Puppeteer or Playwright) and set it up for you. Your job is just to say what you want; the AI wires up the plumbing.","A quick word on other tools you'll hear about, so the names don't confuse you: Cursor and Windsurf are AI-powered code editors (free for students at cursor.com/students); GitHub Copilot is an AI autocomplete that lives inside editors (free for verified students and teachers at education.github.com, otherwise about $10/month); Bolt.new and Google AI Studio build apps in the browser; and Ollama and LM Studio let you run AI models entirely on your own machine with no internet. For this scraper, a terminal agent (Claude Code or Gemini CLI) or Replit is the sweet spot, so start there and ignore the rest for now."],"bullets":["Coding AI (writes and runs the code): Claude Code or Gemini CLI in the terminal, OR Replit entirely in your browser.","Node.js LTS from nodejs.org — the free engine that runs the script on your computer (Replit already has it built in).","A headless browser (invisible Chrome the program drives) — the AI installs this for you; you never touch it directly.","A plain text file of links, one URL per line — you'll create this in seconds with any text editor (even Notepad)."]},{"heading":"Step 1 — Plan it first with a PRD (and use a DIFFERENT AI to plan than to build)","paras":["Before you ask an AI to build anything, write a PRD — a Program Requirements Document. Don't let the fancy name scare you: a PRD is just a plain-English blueprint that says what the thing should do, who it's for, what it needs to handle, and what \"done\" looks like. It's the difference between telling a contractor \"build me a house\" and handing them a one-page sketch with the number of rooms and where the doors go. The PRD costs you ten minutes and saves you an hour of the AI guessing wrong.","Here's the powerful trick that professionals use: plan the PRD with a DIFFERENT AI than the one you'll build with. Ask ChatGPT (chat.openai.com) or Google Gemini (gemini.google.com) to help you write the blueprint, then take that blueprint to Claude Code or the Gemini CLI to actually build it. Why two different AIs? Because the planning AI acts as a fresh, skeptical second opinion — it asks clarifying questions, spots gaps you didn't think of (\"What happens if a website is down?\"), and produces a cleaner spec than the building AI would if it just started coding from a one-line request. Two perspectives catch more problems than one.","To generate your blueprint, open ChatGPT or Gemini and paste the planning prompt below. It will interview you a bit and hand back a tidy PRD. Read it, tweak anything that's wrong, and keep it — you'll feed it to the coding AI in the next step. This habit alone will make everything you ever vibe-code dramatically more reliable."],"prompt":{"label":"Paste into ChatGPT or Gemini to co-write your PRD","text":"I want to build a small command-line tool and I need help writing a clear, plain-English PRD (Program Requirements Document) for it before I hand it to a coding AI. The tool: a Node.js script that reads a text file of web links (one URL per line), uses a headless browser to visit each link, extracts the main body text while ignoring ads/navigation/footers, finds any email addresses on the page, and exports the results (URL, page title, extracted text, emails) into an Excel .xlsx file. It must behave ethically: only scrape sites the user is permitted to, respect each site's robots.txt and terms, add a polite delay between requests, and never collect personal data the user has no right to. I am a complete beginner with no coding experience. Ask me any clarifying questions you need, then write the PRD with these sections: Goal, Who it's for, Inputs, Outputs, Step-by-step behavior, Error handling, Ethical/safety rules, and Definition of done. Keep it in plain language."}},{"heading":"Step 2 — Give the coding AI the one intent command that builds it","paras":["Now the fun part. Open your terminal agent (Claude Code or Gemini CLI) — or a new Replit project — and give it the single \"intent command\" below. An intent command is exactly what it sounds like: one clear paragraph describing your intent, written in plain English, that the AI turns into working code. You are not writing code; you are writing a wish, precisely. Paste the command, press Enter, and watch the AI think out loud, install the headless browser and spreadsheet libraries, and write the script file. This is the vibe-coding loop in its purest form.","When it finishes, the AI will tell you how to run it — usually something like typing node scraper.js links.txt in the terminal, where scraper.js is the program it wrote and links.txt is your file of URLs. If you don't have that links file yet, just tell the AI \"create a sample links.txt with three example URLs so I can test it,\" and it will. If anything breaks — and with AI-written code, something often does on the first run — you don't need to understand the error. Copy the red error text, paste it back to the AI, and say \"this happened, please fix it.\" The AI reads its own mistakes and repairs them. That copy-the-error, paste-it-back rhythm is the single most important skill in this whole guide, and it requires zero coding knowledge.","Treat the result the way you'd treat work from an eager, talented intern: it's genuinely functional, but it is unverified. The intern is fast and enthusiastic and will confidently hand you something that looks right — your job is to actually run it on a couple of pages you know well and check that the emails and text it pulled are correct before you trust it on all 60. Never assume; always spot-check."],"prompt":{"label":"The intent command — paste into Claude Code, Gemini CLI, or Replit","text":"Write a Node.js command-line script that reads a text file of web links (one URL per line). Use a headless-browser library to visit each link, extract the main body text (ignore ads, navigation, and footers), find any email addresses, and export the cleaned results — URL, page title, extracted text, emails — into an Excel (.xlsx) file."}},{"heading":"Scrape responsibly — the ethics and safety rules that keep you out of trouble","paras":["Scraping is a power tool, and like any power tool it comes with rules that protect both you and the people whose websites you visit. The first rule: only scrape sites you're actually allowed to. Many websites publish a file called robots.txt (you can see any site's by adding /robots.txt to its address, like example.com/robots.txt) — it's the site's posted sign saying which pages automated visitors may and may not touch. Respect it. Also read a site's Terms of Service; some explicitly forbid automated collection, and ignoring that can get your access blocked or worse. When you write your intent, or when the AI asks, tell it plainly: \"respect robots.txt and skip anything disallowed.\"","The second rule: be a polite guest. Every page you load is a small cost to someone else's server, and hammering a site with rapid-fire requests can slow it down or look like an attack. Always add a delay between requests — a couple of seconds is a good, considerate default — so your script sips rather than gulps. It's the difference between one person browsing and a crowd stampeding through a door. You can literally tell the AI \"add a two-second pause between each page.\"","The third rule, and the most important: never collect personal data you don't have a right to use. Finding a business's public contact email on its own \"Contact Us\" page for a legitimate outreach purpose is ordinary business practice; scraping private individuals' details, or gathering data to spam people who never asked to hear from you, is not — and in many places it's illegal under privacy laws like the GDPR (Europe) or CAN-SPAM (US email rules). The technology makes the collection easy; that's exactly why the judgment about what you should collect has to come from you. A good gut check: if you'd be uncomfortable telling the person to their face how you got their address and why you're contacting them, don't."],"bullets":["Check example.com/robots.txt and the site's Terms of Service before scraping — skip anything they disallow.","Add a delay (about 2 seconds) between requests so you never overload someone's server.","Only gather public, business-appropriate contacts for a legitimate purpose — never private data or spam lists.","When in doubt, scrape less: a handful of pages you're clearly permitted to beats a giant harvest you can't justify."]},{"heading":"What the finished tool looks like, and how to keep any secrets safe","paras":["When it all works, the experience is almost anticlimactically smooth — which is the goal. You have a folder with two files: the script the AI wrote (say scraper.js) and your list of links (links.txt). You type one line into the terminal, hit Enter, and watch a little progress readout scroll by: \"Visiting page 1 of 40... found 2 emails... Visiting page 2 of 40...\" A minute or two later, a fresh .xlsx file appears in the folder. You open it in Excel or Google Sheets and there it is: a clean table, one row per page, with columns for the URL, the page's title, the cleaned body text, and the emails found. Work that used to eat an afternoon now takes the length of a coffee break, and you can re-run it any time by swapping in a new links.txt.","One security habit matters even on a small project like this. Sometimes a tool needs a secret — an API key (a private password-like code that lets your script use an outside paid service, for example a service that solves tricky pages or looks up company info). The rule is absolute: never let the AI paste a password or API key directly into the code. Instead, store secrets in a special file named .env (that's a dot, then the letters e-n-v), which holds lines like SERVICE_KEY=your-secret-here, and the code reads them from there. Then create a file called .gitignore and list .env inside it. The .gitignore file is a do-not-upload list; it ensures that if you ever share your project online (say, to GitHub), your secrets stay on your machine and never get published for the world to copy. Just tell the AI: \"put any keys in a .env file and add .env to .gitignore\" — it knows exactly what to do.","This scraper is a script you run for yourself, so it doesn't need to be \"published\" the way a website does. But it's worth knowing that when you do build something meant for others to visit — a web page, a little app — you can host it free on GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, or Replit, each of which turns your files into a live link you can share. File that away for your next project."],"table":{"headers":["Column in your spreadsheet","What it contains","Example"],"rows":[["URL","The web address the row came from","https://citycrafts.example/vendors/riverside-pottery"],["Page title","The headline the browser shows in its tab","Riverside Pottery — Handmade Ceramics"],["Extracted text","The cleaned main content, ads and menus removed","Family-run studio since 2009, specializing in..."],["Emails","Any email addresses found on the page","hello@riversidepottery.example"]]}},{"heading":"Stretch goals and the skills you'll walk away with","paras":["Once the basic version works, you'll feel the itch to make it better — and because you're conversing with an AI, upgrades are just more plain-English requests. Realistic next steps, each of which is a one-sentence ask to your coding AI: have it also grab phone numbers and social-media links, not just emails; add a \"words found\" or summary column so you can skim results faster; make it skip any URL it has already scraped so you can safely re-run it; write a short log file noting which pages failed and why; or add a friendly summary at the end like \"Done — 40 pages visited, 31 emails found, 3 pages skipped.\" You could even ask it to have a second AI-style pass write a one-line summary of each page's content. Each improvement teaches you that software is never \"finished\" — it grows one conversation at a time.","A bigger stretch: turn the whole thing into a tiny web page where you paste a list of links into a box and click a button, instead of using the terminal — then host it free on Netlify or Vercel so a non-technical colleague could use it too. That's a genuine leap, but it's the same loop you already know: write a PRD with one AI, build with another, test and refine. If this first project clicks for you, that one is a very reachable second weekend.","Step back and notice what you actually learned by building this, because these skills transfer to almost anything you'll ever want to automate. You learned automation — making a computer do repetitive work on its own. You learned what a headless browser is and why programs use invisible browsers to read the modern web. You learned to export data into formats real people use, like Excel. You learned responsible scraping — the ethics and etiquette that separate a professional from a nuisance. And underneath all of it, you learned the core vibe-coding loop: describe your intent clearly, plan with one AI and build with another, run it, and when something breaks, hand the error right back to the AI and let it fix itself. That loop is the whole game, and you now know how to play it."],"bullets":["Ask the AI to also capture phone numbers, social links, or a short summary per page.","Add a skip-already-scraped feature and an end-of-run summary so re-running is safe and clear.","Level up later: wrap it in a simple web page and host it free on Netlify or Vercel for others to use.","Skills banked: automation, headless browsers, exporting data, responsible scraping, and the plan-build-refine loop."]}],"keyTerms":[{"term":"Vibe coding","def":"Building software by describing what you want in plain English and letting an AI write the code, then refining it through back-and-forth conversation."},{"term":"Web scraper","def":"A program that automatically visits web pages and pulls out specific information, so you don't have to copy and paste it by hand."},{"term":"URL","def":"A web address — the 'https://...' string in your browser's address bar that points to a specific page."},{"term":"Terminal","def":"A plain text window where you type commands to your computer instead of clicking buttons; usually black with monospaced text."},{"term":"Node.js","def":"A free program that lets JavaScript (the language of the web) run directly on your own computer instead of only inside a web page."},{"term":"Headless browser","def":"A normal web browser with its window turned off, invisible and controlled entirely by a program so it can load pages exactly as a person would see them."},{"term":"PRD (Program Requirements Document)","def":"A short plain-English blueprint that spells out what your tool should do, who it's for, and what 'done' looks like, written before any code."},{"term":"robots.txt","def":"A file a website publishes (at its-address/robots.txt) that tells automated visitors which pages they may and may not access."},{"term":".env file and .gitignore","def":"A .env file safely stores secrets like passwords or API keys outside your code, and listing it in .gitignore keeps it from ever being uploaded when you share your project."},{"term":"API key","def":"A private, password-like code that lets your script use an outside online service; it must be kept secret, never pasted into the code itself."}],"tips":["Always plan your PRD with one AI (ChatGPT or Gemini) and build with a different one (Claude Code or Gemini CLI) — the second opinion catches gaps a single AI would miss.","When code breaks, don't try to understand the error: copy the red text, paste it back to the AI, say 'this happened, please fix it,' and let it repair itself.","Test on two or three pages you already know well before trusting the scraper on all of them — AI code is like an eager intern's work: functional but unverified.","Tell the AI in plain words to respect robots.txt, add a 2-second delay between pages, and put any keys in a .env file added to .gitignore — it will handle all three.","Start absurdly small: get it working on three links before you point it at three hundred. A tiny win you can see beats a big plan that never runs."]},{"id":"vibe14","n":14,"g":"P","title":"Project — Spaced-Repetition Flashcard App","intro":"Imagine sitting down this weekend and, without writing a single line of code yourself, building a real web app that helps you memorize absolutely anything: the vocabulary of a new language, the facts behind a professional certification, the names and prices in your product catalog, or the trivia you keep forgetting at pub quiz night. You describe what you want in plain English, an AI writes the actual working code, and you refine it through conversation until it does exactly what you pictured. That is \"vibe coding,\" and this page walks you through it start to finish, assuming you have never opened a code editor in your life.","tagline":"Build a real, working \"smart flashcard\" app this weekend that quizzes you on anything and gets smarter about what you struggle with — no coding experience required.","sections":[{"heading":"What you're building, and why it's genuinely clever","paras":["A flashcard is the oldest study trick there is: a question or word on the front, the answer on the back. You look at the front, try to recall the answer, then flip the card to check. What makes THIS app special is a technique called spaced repetition — a scientifically proven method (backed by over a century of memory research) where the app tracks how well you know each card and schedules it to come back at the right moment. Cards you find hard reappear soon, while cards you nail get pushed further and further into the future. Instead of wasting time re-reading things you already know, you spend your minutes exactly where your memory is weakest. It is the engine behind popular study apps like Anki and Duolingo.","Here is the everyday magic of it. Say a freelance web designer is learning Spanish to work with clients in Mexico. She adds a card with 'presupuesto' on the front and 'budget' on the back. The first time it comes up she blanks — so she rates her confidence a 1 out of 5, and the app shows it to her again in ten minutes. A few sessions later she recalls it instantly and rates it a 5, so the app waits a week before testing her. Multiply that across 300 words and the app quietly builds an efficient study plan she never had to design herself.","The beauty is that the exact same app works for anything, because YOU decide what goes on the cards. A small-business owner can drill the SKU numbers and prices of a new product line before a trade show. A new marketing hire can memorize the company's brand guidelines and competitor names during onboarding. A hobbyist can learn every constellation in the night sky, or the chord shapes on a guitar. You are not building a language app or a trivia app — you are building a memorization machine, and the content is up to whoever uses it.","Under the hood, the app remembers everything on YOUR device using something called 'local storage' — a small private space inside your web browser where a web page is allowed to save data on your own computer. That means no sign-up, no account, no server bill, and your cards stay with you. Close the tab, come back tomorrow, and your deck and your entire study history are still there."]},{"heading":"Your zero-install toolkit: what to open and why","paras":["You do not need to install anything to build this. The whole project can be done inside a web browser using a 'build-in-the-browser' AI tool. The two easiest for a first-timer are Bolt.new (bolt.new) and Google AI Studio (aistudio.google.com). Both let you type a description of an app and watch the AI generate it live, with a preview you can click on immediately and a button to publish it to a real web address. Replit (replit.com) is a third excellent browser option and is especially friendly for beginners. There is genuinely nothing to download — you open a tab, sign in with a Google or email account, and start describing.","It helps to know the vocabulary these tools use. Your app will be built as a 'React app.' React is simply a very popular free tool (made by Meta) for building interactive web pages — the kind where clicking a button instantly changes what you see, without the whole page reloading. You will never have to learn React yourself; you just need to know that when the AI says 'I built this in React,' that is a normal, professional choice and exactly what you want for something clicky and interactive like flashcards.","If you would rather work in a more traditional setup (a real code editor on your own machine), the leading AI coding tools are Cursor (cursor.com, a code editor with AI built in that is free for students at cursor.com/students) and GitHub Copilot (an AI assistant that lives inside an editor, free for verified students and teachers at education.github.com and about ten dollars a month otherwise). You can also just chat with a general assistant: Claude (claude.ai) can write code and show you a live preview of it right in the conversation using a feature called Artifacts, and ChatGPT (chat.openai.com) does the same through a feature called Canvas. For a first project though, stick with Bolt.new or Google AI Studio — the browser tools remove every possible obstacle so you can focus on the fun part.","One term you will hear is 'terminal' — the black window where programmers type commands instead of clicking buttons. The wonderful news for this project is that with Bolt.new, Google AI Studio, or Replit you will likely never touch a terminal at all. If a tool ever does show you one, it is just running the app for you; you can treat it as scenery."],"table":{"headers":["Tool","What it is","Best for","Cost"],"rows":[["Bolt.new","Build a full app in the browser from a description","Fastest path from idea to live app","Free tier, generous"],["Google AI Studio","Google's in-browser AI builder","Zero-install, instant hosting","Free"],["Replit","Browser code workspace with an AI helper","Beginners who want a bit more control","Free tier"],["Cursor","AI-powered code editor on your computer","When you want a real local setup","Free for students; paid tiers"],["Claude / ChatGPT","Chat assistants that write + preview code","Planning, and quick experiments","Free tiers available"]]}},{"heading":"Step 1 — Plan first: write a PRD with a DIFFERENT AI","paras":["Before you ask an AI to build anything, spend fifteen minutes writing a PRD. That stands for Program Requirements Document, which is a fancy name for a simple thing: a plain-English blueprint of what your app should do, written before any code exists. Think of it like the sketch a homeowner brings to a contractor. You would not walk up and say 'build me a house' — you would say how many bedrooms, where the kitchen goes, what the budget is. A PRD does the same for software, and it dramatically improves what the AI builds because the AI is no longer guessing at your intentions.","Here is the single most useful pro move on this whole page: plan your PRD with a DIFFERENT AI than the one you will build with. If you are going to build in Bolt.new (which uses one AI model behind the scenes), do your planning by chatting with Claude or ChatGPT or Google Gemini first. Why? Because a second, independent AI acts like a fresh pair of eyes — it will ask you questions you didn't think of, catch gaps, and produce a cleaner blueprint. Then you hand that polished blueprint to your builder tool. It is the difference between a good result and a great one.","To get your PRD, open a chat AI and paste the planning prompt below. It asks the AI to interview you and then hand you a tidy document. Answer its questions in plain language — 'I want people to import a whole list of cards at once,' 'I'd love a dark mode for studying at night' — and it will fold your answers into the blueprint. When you are happy, copy the finished PRD; that is what you will feed to your builder in the next step.","Do not skip this because it feels like extra work. Fifteen minutes of planning routinely saves an hour of the frustrating back-and-forth that happens when an AI builds the wrong thing because you were vague. The PRD is where you get to be picky and thorough at zero cost."],"prompt":{"label":"Paste this into a planning AI (Claude, ChatGPT, or Gemini) to co-write your PRD","text":"I'm a non-technical beginner and I want to build a spaced-repetition flashcard web app that helps someone memorize anything — a language, facts for a certification, product knowledge, or trivia. Act as a product manager and help me write a clear, plain-English Program Requirements Document (PRD) for it. First, ask me 5-8 short questions one at a time to pin down the features, who it's for, and what 'done' looks like. After I answer, produce a clean PRD with these sections: Overview, Who it's for, Core features (as a numbered list), How spaced repetition should work, What the screens look like, Data that gets saved and where, and Nice-to-have stretch goals. Keep it simple enough that I could hand it to an AI app builder. Don't write any code yet."}},{"heading":"Step 2 — Build it: the one command that creates the whole app","paras":["Now the exciting part. Open Bolt.new (or Google AI Studio, or Replit), find the big text box where it invites you to describe your app, and paste the 'intent command' below. An intent command is just a clear, complete description of what you want built, written as one instruction. This one is carefully worded to hit every important feature: adding cards, flipping them, rating your confidence, saving to local storage, and the spaced-repetition scheduling. Paste it, press enter, and watch the AI write the code and show you a working preview — usually within a minute or two.","After you paste it, hand the AI the PRD you made in Step 1 too. A good way to do this is to send the intent command first, let it build, then say 'Here's my full PRD with more detail — please make sure the app matches it:' and paste the document. The intent command gets you a working app fast; the PRD fills in the finer points and preferences you captured during planning.","Watch it come to life in the preview pane. You will see a card appear, a button to flip it, and buttons to rate how well you knew it. Click around. It is completely normal — expected, even — that the very first version is not perfect. Maybe the flip animation is clunky, or the rating buttons are in a confusing order. That is fine. The whole point of vibe coding is that you fix these things by just... asking, which is exactly what Step 3 covers.","A crucial mindset for this moment: treat AI-written code like work handed to you by an eager, fast, slightly overconfident intern. It is genuinely capable and it produced something real in seconds — but it is unverified until YOU click through it and confirm it behaves. The AI is not lying to you; it simply cannot know whether the result matches what was in your head until you look. So look, click everything, and be ready to say what is wrong."],"prompt":{"label":"Paste this 'intent command' into your builder (Bolt.new / Google AI Studio) to generate the app","text":"Create a React app for a smart flashcard deck. Let me add cards (a term on the front, the answer on the back). Show one card at a time; I guess, click to flip, then rate my confidence 1-5. Use the browser's local storage to remember my history, and schedule low-confidence cards to reappear sooner and high-confidence cards later (spaced repetition). Include a simple screen to add and edit cards."}},{"heading":"Step 3 — Test and refine: talk your way to the app you wanted","paras":["This is where vibe coding really shines and where beginners often feel like wizards. You do not fix problems by editing code — you fix them by describing the change in plain English, and the AI rewrites the code for you. The loop is simple: try the app, notice something you want different, tell the AI, watch it update, try again. Repeat until you love it. Every one of the tools mentioned keeps the conversation going, so you can pile up dozens of small refinements over a single afternoon.","Be specific and concrete, because specific requests get specific results. Instead of 'make it nicer,' say exactly what you see and what you want instead. Real examples of refinement requests: 'When I rate a card 5, it should not come back for at least four days — right now it reappears too soon.' Or 'The flip should be a smooth animation, not an instant jump.' Or 'Add a counter at the top showing how many cards are due today.' Or 'The Add Card screen loses my typing when I click away — please fix that.' The AI handles each one and you just keep clicking.","Test the things that matter most for THIS app. First, add three or four cards and study them, deliberately rating some low and some high, then check that the low ones come back sooner — that is the core promise of the app working. Second, refresh the page or close and reopen the tab, and confirm your cards and history are still there; that proves local storage is doing its job. Third, try the edit screen: change a card, delete one, add one. If any of these misbehave, describe the misbehavior to the AI in one clear sentence and let it patch the code.","When it works and looks good, publish it. Every builder tool has a 'Deploy' or 'Publish' button that puts your app on a real web address you can bookmark on your phone or share. 'Deploy' just means taking your finished app and putting it online where anyone with the link can open it. If you built somewhere without one-click publishing, free hosts that do the job are GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, and Replit — you can literally ask your AI, 'Give me step-by-step instructions to publish this for free on Netlify,' and follow along."],"prompt":{"label":"A refinement request to copy, tweak, and send to your AI while testing","text":"I tested the app and have a few changes. 1) When I rate a card 5 out of 5, it comes back too soon — high-confidence cards should wait much longer than low-confidence ones. 2) Add a small counter at the top showing how many cards are due right now. 3) Make the card flip a smooth animation instead of an instant switch. 4) Make sure my cards and study history survive a page refresh. Please make these changes and briefly tell me what you updated."}},{"heading":"Stretch goals: level up once the basics work","paras":["Once your core app is solid, you can add features one at a time — and because you refine by chatting, each upgrade is just another sentence to your AI. Do these one at a time and re-test after each, so if something breaks you know exactly which request caused it. The classic three upgrades below turn a simple weekend project into something you'd genuinely use every day.","Importing from a CSV is the biggest quality-of-life win. A CSV (Comma-Separated Values) file is just a plain table you can make in Excel or Google Sheets: one column for the fronts of your cards, one column for the backs. Instead of typing 200 cards one by one, you paste or upload a spreadsheet and the app creates them all at once. For a business owner loading an entire product catalog, or someone importing a ready-made vocabulary list they found online, this single feature saves hours.","Dark mode is a soft, dark color scheme that is easier on the eyes for studying at night or in a dim room — a toggle flips the app between light and dark. And a daily streak is the little motivator that keeps you coming back: the app counts how many days in a row you've studied and shows the number, the same trick that makes Duolingo weirdly addictive. Both are small asks for the AI and both make the app feel finished and professional.","A word on safety while you build. This particular app is unusually safe because it stores everything on your own device and needs no passwords or online accounts. But it is worth learning the golden rule now, because your next project might need it: never let an AI put passwords or secret keys directly into your code. A 'key' is like a password that lets your app use a paid online service. The correct home for secrets is a special hidden file called a .env file, and you add that file's name to another file called .gitignore, which tells the publishing system 'never upload this.' You will not need any of that for the flashcard app — but tuck the rule away for later."],"prompt":{"label":"Ask your AI to add the three classic stretch features (do these after the basics work)","text":"The core app works well. Now add these features one at a time, and after each one tell me what changed so I can test it: 1) Let me import many cards at once from a CSV file (two columns: front and back), with an upload button and a paste-a-spreadsheet option. 2) Add a dark mode toggle that remembers my choice in local storage. 3) Add a daily streak counter that increases each day I study and resets if I skip a day. Keep everything saving to local storage so nothing is lost on refresh."}},{"heading":"What you'll walk away knowing","paras":["By the time your flashcard app is live, you will have quietly learned the core ideas behind most modern web apps — not as theory, but because you watched them work in something you built. That is a real portfolio piece and a real skill, earned in a weekend.","You'll understand 'interactivity and state,' which is the idea that an app remembers what's happening right now — which card is showing, whether it's flipped, what you rated it — and updates the screen the instant you click. Nearly every app you use, from your banking site to your favorite game, is built on exactly this. You'll understand saving data in the browser, so an app can remember you between visits without any server or account. And you'll have implemented a real learning algorithm — the spaced-repetition scheduling that decides when each card returns is a genuine piece of decision-making logic, the same category of thing that powers recommendation feeds and smart reminders.","Most importantly, you'll have proven to yourself that you can go from a plain-English idea to a working, published app by having a conversation. That is the whole promise of vibe coding, and once it clicks for one project, you'll start seeing dozens of small tools you could build for yourself and the people around you. The flashcard app is just the one that shows you it's possible."]}],"keyTerms":[{"term":"Vibe coding","def":"Building software by describing what you want in plain English and letting an AI write the actual code, then improving it through back-and-forth conversation."},{"term":"Spaced repetition","def":"A proven study method where cards you find hard come back sooner and cards you know well come back later, so you spend your time where your memory is weakest."},{"term":"Local storage","def":"A small private space inside your web browser where a web app can save data directly on your own device, so it remembers your information between visits with no account or server."},{"term":"React","def":"A very popular free tool for building interactive web pages where clicking instantly changes what you see, without the whole page reloading — the AI uses it for you."},{"term":"PRD (Program Requirements Document)","def":"A short plain-English blueprint of what your app should do, written before any code exists, that you hand to the AI so it builds the right thing."},{"term":"Intent command","def":"One clear, complete instruction describing the app you want, which you paste into an AI builder to generate a first working version."},{"term":"Deploy / publish","def":"Taking your finished app and putting it online at a real web address so you (or anyone with the link) can open it in a browser."},{"term":"CSV file","def":"A plain table of data — Comma-Separated Values — that you can make in Excel or Google Sheets, used here to import many flashcards at once instead of typing them individually."},{"term":"Terminal","def":"The black text window where programmers type commands instead of clicking buttons; the browser-based builders in this guide let you avoid it almost entirely."},{"term":".env file / .gitignore","def":"A hidden file that safely stores secret passwords or keys, plus a list that tells the publishing system never to upload that file — so your secrets never leak online."}],"tips":["Always plan your PRD with a DIFFERENT AI than the one you build with — a fresh, independent model catches gaps and asks better questions, giving you a cleaner blueprint.","Be concrete when you ask for changes. 'When I rate a card 5, don't show it again for four days' gets a fix; 'make it better' gets a shrug. Describe what you see and what you want instead.","Test the three things that actually matter: hard cards come back sooner, your data survives a page refresh (proving local storage works), and you can add/edit/delete cards without losing your typing.","Add stretch features one at a time and re-test after each — if something breaks, you'll know exactly which request caused it instead of hunting through several changes at once.","Treat AI-written code like work from an eager intern: fast and functional, but unverified until you click through every feature yourself and confirm it does what you meant."]},{"id":"vibe15","n":15,"g":"P","title":"Project — Tone-Shift Writing Assistant","tagline":"Build your own private, offline \"tone rewriter\" this weekend — paste messy notes, pick a vibe, and get back a polished message, all powered by an AI running on your own computer where nothing you type ever touches the internet.","intro":"Imagine a tiny app that lives on your computer: you dump in rough, half-formed notes, choose a tone from a dropdown — \"Executive Memo,\" \"Technical Update,\" or \"Diplomatic Refusal\" — click one button, and out comes a clean, professional rewrite you can copy and paste anywhere. No monthly subscription, no sign-up, and (this is the magic part) your text never leaves your machine. This page walks a total beginner — someone who has never written a line of code — through building exactly that, using \"vibe coding\": describing what you want in plain English and letting an AI write the actual code for you. By the end you'll understand the whole recipe, have the exact words to paste, and know what \"done\" looks like. You really can finish this in a weekend.","sections":[{"heading":"What you're building — and why it's genuinely useful","paras":["Picture a freelance consultant who fires off twenty client emails a day, or a small-business owner who dreads writing the polite-but-firm reply that says \"no\" without burning the relationship, or a marketer turning bullet-point brain-dumps into crisp update posts. They all do the same invisible chore over and over: take rough thoughts and reshape them into the right tone for the right audience. A Tone-Shift Writing Assistant does that reshaping in one click.","The finished tool is a single web page that runs on your own computer. It has one big text box labeled \"Raw Thoughts\" where you paste whatever's in your head — typos, fragments, all of it. Next to it sits a dropdown menu (a little list you click to open) where you pick the target tone. You click a \"Rewrite\" button, and a moment later a clean, rewritten version appears in an output box with a \"Copy\" button. That's the entire experience. Simple on the surface, but it removes a real, repetitive tax on your day.","Here's what makes this version special and different from just using ChatGPT in a browser: the AI doing the rewriting runs privately on your own computer. Nothing you paste — no client names, no half-finished complaints, no confidential numbers — is ever sent over the internet to a company's servers. For anyone who handles sensitive messages (a bookkeeper, a therapist writing client updates, a lawyer, an HR contractor), that privacy isn't a nice-to-have; it's the whole point. And because the AI is running locally, it's completely free to use as much as you want, with no per-message billing.","This project is deliberately small. You are not building the next big startup. You're building a personal power-tool that does one thing extremely well — and in the process you'll learn how software actually gets made in the age of AI. That skill transfers to everything else you might want to build later."]},{"heading":"First, the big ideas in plain English (don't skip this)","paras":["Before we build, let's define the handful of terms you'll keep hearing, because everything downstream depends on them. Take these slowly — none of it is hard once someone explains it without jargon.","A model is the actual artificial intelligence — the thing that reads your text and writes the rewrite. When you use ChatGPT, the model lives on OpenAI's computers far away. In this project, you'll download a model and run it on your own machine instead, so it works offline and privately. Think of it as your own personal copy of a smart writing assistant.","A local server is the part people find spooky until it clicks, so here's the plain version: a \"server\" is just a program that sits quietly and waits for other programs to ask it questions, then answers them. \"Local\" means it's running on your own computer, not somewhere on the internet. So a local server is your own private helper program, running on your machine, ready to answer requests. The word localhost is simply a nickname a computer uses for \"me, myself\" — this very machine. When your web page talks to http://localhost:1234, it's talking to a program on your own computer. Nothing goes out to the internet. That single idea — localhost means \"right here on this machine\" — is the heart of the whole project.","An API (Application Programming Interface) sounds technical but means something ordinary: it's the agreed-upon way for two programs to talk to each other, like a waiter taking your order to the kitchen and bringing food back. Your web page will send your notes and chosen tone to the local AI through an API, and the AI will send the rewrite back the same way. You'll hear the phrase \"OpenAI-compatible API\" — that just means your local AI speaks the same standard 'language' that the famous ChatGPT service uses, so any code written for ChatGPT works with your private model too, just pointed at localhost instead.","Finally, vibe coding (a term coined by AI researcher Andrej Karpathy) is the method this whole section is about: instead of learning to type code, you describe what you want in plain English, an AI writes the code, and you refine it through back-and-forth conversation. You are the director; the AI is the crew. You never have to memorize a single line of programming."]},{"heading":"The tool setup: LM Studio + a simple web page","paras":["You need exactly two things, and both are free. The first is LM Studio — a friendly, point-and-click app (no terminal, no typing commands) that lets you browse, download, and run AI models on your own computer. You may already have met it over in the Experimentation Station on this site, which walks through installing it click by click; if you haven't set it up yet, start there, then come back. Grab LM Studio only from its official site, lmstudio.ai, because open AI tools are a favorite disguise for lookalike sites bundling malware.","Inside LM Studio you'll do two quick things. First, download a small chat model — LM Studio suggests good starter options, and something in the 3-to-8 'billion-parameter' range (a rough measure of a model's size and smarts) rewrites text just fine on an ordinary laptop. Second, and this is the crucial trick that makes the whole project possible: LM Studio has a built-in \"local server\" mode. When you switch it on, LM Studio starts pretending to be a private, personal version of the ChatGPT service, sitting quietly at the address http://localhost:1234 on your own computer, ready to answer requests. Look for the \"Local Server\" or \"Developer\" tab in LM Studio and click \"Start Server.\" That's it — you now have your own private AI service running, and no data leaves your machine.","The second thing you need is the web page itself — the box-with-a-dropdown interface. You will not write it by hand. You'll describe it to a coding AI and let it generate the code. The very easiest starting point for a complete beginner is Claude (at claude.ai): it has a feature called Artifacts that shows a live, working preview of your web page right beside the chat, so you can watch it come to life and ask for changes in the same window. Other great free options for beginners are ChatGPT with its Canvas feature (chat.openai.com), Google Gemini, or an in-the-browser builder like Replit or Bolt.new where you don't install anything at all. If you'd rather work in a real code editor, Cursor (an AI-powered editor, free for students at cursor.com/students) or the free GitHub Copilot (free for verified students and teachers at education.github.com, otherwise about $10/month) both let you chat with an AI that edits files for you.","That's the entire toolkit: LM Studio running your private model on localhost, plus one AI that writes the web page. Two free pieces, and you're ready to build."],"bullets":["LM Studio (lmstudio.ai) — your private AI, running a model locally and serving it at http://localhost:1234.","A coding AI to generate the web page — Claude (Artifacts), ChatGPT (Canvas), Gemini, Replit, or Bolt.new. Pick one; all have free tiers.","That's it. No paid accounts, no servers to rent, nothing installed beyond LM Studio."]},{"heading":"Plan it first: write a one-page PRD (with a different AI)","paras":["The single habit that separates a smooth build from a frustrating one is planning before you build. In vibe coding the plan is called a PRD — a Program Requirements Document. Don't let the fancy name scare you: a PRD is just a plain-language blueprint that says, in ordinary sentences, what the thing should do, what it should look like, and how someone uses it. One page is plenty for a project this size.","Here's the pro move that feels counterintuitive at first: plan the PRD with a different AI than the one you'll build with. Ask one AI (say, ChatGPT or Gemini) to help you think through and write the blueprint, then hand that blueprint to a second AI (say, Claude) to actually write the code. Why? Because the planning AI acts like a thoughtful architect who asks 'have you considered what happens if the box is empty?', and the building AI acts like the contractor who follows the approved plans. Using two different AIs gives you a built-in second opinion and catches gaps early, before they're baked into code.","Your PRD doesn't need to be formal. Tell the planning AI what you're making — a private, local tone-rewriting web page — and ask it to help you list the pieces: the 'Raw Thoughts' input box, the tone dropdown and exactly which tones to offer, the Rewrite button, the output box, the Copy button, and the fact that it talks to a local AI at http://localhost:1234. Ask it to flag anything you forgot, like 'what should the button say while it's thinking?' or 'what happens if the local server isn't running?' Ten minutes of this saves an hour of confusion later. Save the result — that blueprint is what you'll paste into your building AI next."],"prompt":{"label":"Paste this into a PLANNING AI (e.g. ChatGPT or Gemini) to draft your blueprint","text":"Help me write a one-page plain-language blueprint (a PRD) for a small personal tool I'm going to build with an AI coding assistant. I am a complete beginner and won't be writing code myself. The tool is a single web page that runs on my own computer. It has: a large text box labeled 'Raw Thoughts' where I paste rough notes; a dropdown to pick a target tone (Executive Memo, Technical Update, or Diplomatic Refusal); a 'Rewrite' button; a clean output box that shows the rewritten message; and a 'Copy' button on the output. When I click Rewrite, it should send my text plus the chosen tone to a private AI model already running on my own computer at http://localhost:1234 (an OpenAI-compatible local server, like LM Studio), and show the result. Nothing should ever be sent over the internet. Ask me any clarifying questions, point out anything I've forgotten (like what the button should show while it's working, or what to do if the local server isn't running), and then write the finished one-page blueprint in plain English."}},{"heading":"The intent command: the exact words that build it","paras":["Now the fun part. You take your blueprint to the building AI and give it what we'll call the intent command — a clear, specific description of what to build. The clearer your description, the better the result; a vague request gets a vague app. Below is a complete, ready-to-use intent command written for a beginner. Open Claude (and turn on Artifacts if prompted), or ChatGPT with Canvas, paste this in, and watch a working web page appear beside the chat.","One important note before you paste: your local AI must be running for the finished page to work. Make sure LM Studio is open and its local server is started (that 'Start Server' step from earlier), so the address http://localhost:1234 is actually live. The web page is just the front counter; LM Studio is the kitchen. If the kitchen's closed, the counter has nothing to serve.","After the first version appears, you refine by conversation — this is the loop that makes vibe coding feel like magic. If the output box is cramped, say 'make the output box taller.' If you want it to feel warmer, say 'add a soft rounded card style and a little more spacing.' If clicking Rewrite seems to do nothing, tell the AI exactly what happened ('I clicked Rewrite and nothing appeared') and let it diagnose. You describe the problem in plain English; the AI fixes the code. Repeat until it feels right. There's no limit to how many times you can ask."],"prompt":{"label":"Paste this into your CODING AI (Claude with Artifacts, or ChatGPT with Canvas)","text":"Build a minimalist single-page web interface. Create a large text box labeled 'Raw Thoughts' and a dropdown to pick a target tone: Executive Memo, Technical Update, or Diplomatic Refusal. When I click 'Rewrite,' send my text plus the chosen tone to my local model server at http://localhost:1234 (OpenAI-compatible API) and display the rewritten message in a clean output box with a Copy button."}},{"heading":"What the finished thing looks like — and how to test it","paras":["When it's working, you'll have a clean single page with two panels. On the left: the big 'Raw Thoughts' box and the tone dropdown and the Rewrite button. On the right: an output box that fills in with the polished version, topped by a Copy button that puts the result on your clipboard so you can paste it straight into your email. Type a genuinely messy note to test it — something like 'hey so the launch is gonna slip like 2 weeks, vendor issue, not our fault really, need more $ maybe, will know friday' — pick 'Executive Memo,' and click Rewrite. You should get back something that reads like a composed, professional update. Then switch the dropdown to 'Diplomatic Refusal' with a different note and watch the same text machinery produce a graceful 'no.' Seeing your own tool transform your words is the moment this all becomes real.","Test like a skeptic, because AI-written code is like work handed in by an eager, talented intern: it's usually functional, but it hasn't been double-checked, and it will confidently do the wrong thing sometimes. Click every button. Try an empty box (does it complain gracefully, or break?). Paste a very long note. Try each tone. If something misbehaves, you don't fix it yourself — you describe exactly what went wrong to the AI and let it patch the code. 'When I leave Raw Thoughts empty and click Rewrite, it shows an error — please make it show a friendly message instead' is a perfectly good bug report.","The most common first-time snag has a simple cause: the page loads fine but Rewrite does nothing, or shows a connection error. Ninety percent of the time that means LM Studio's local server isn't running, or the model isn't loaded. Pop back into LM Studio, confirm a model is loaded and the server is started at localhost:1234, and try again. This is the one place beginners get stuck, and now you know the fix before it happens."]},{"heading":"Stretch goals, safety, and the skills you just earned","paras":["Once the basics work, the fun is in the small upgrades — each is one more plain-English request to your AI. Add more tones ('Warm Thank-You,' 'Firm Follow-Up,' 'Plain-English Explainer'). Add a length control ('let me choose short, medium, or detailed'). Add a 'Try Again' button that regenerates a fresh version. Add a little history list of your last few rewrites. Add a slider for formality. Each of these is a sentence to the AI, not a coding project — that's the whole promise of building this way.","A word on safety, because it matters even for a small tool. In this particular project your privacy is strong by design: because the AI runs locally, your text stays on your machine. But as you build more ambitious things later, you'll run into secrets — passwords or API keys, which are like private access codes that let a program use a paid service. The rule is simple and non-negotiable: never let an AI paste a real password or key directly into your code. Instead, secrets go in a separate hidden file called a .env file (short for 'environment'), and you add that file's name to another file called .gitignore, which is a list of things that should never be uploaded when you publish your project online. If any AI ever writes a real secret straight into your code, ask it to move it to a .env file instead. For this local-only tool you won't need keys at all — which is one more reason it's a perfect first build.","When you're proud of it and want it live on the internet for others (note: the AI part will only run against your own local server, but the page itself can be published), free hosting services like GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, and Replit will put a web page online for free in a few clicks. That's a project for another day, but it's good to know the door is open.","Step back and notice what you've actually learned by finishing this: how to call a local AI's API (make one program ask another for an answer), how to build a simple user interface with an input, a control, and an output, and how to keep sensitive text completely private by running everything on your own machine. Those three skills are the backbone of a huge amount of practical software. You started as someone who'd never written code, and you'll end the weekend with a private AI tool you built yourself — and the confidence to build the next one."],"bullets":["Easy wins: more tones, a length or formality control, a 'Try Again' button, a history of recent rewrites.","Safety rule: real passwords/keys go in a .env file, and .env goes in .gitignore so it's never uploaded — never let an AI hard-code a secret.","Go live later (the page, not your private model): GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, or Replit host web pages for free.","Skills earned: calling a local AI API, building a simple UI, and keeping text fully private."]}],"keyTerms":[{"term":"Vibe coding","def":"Building software by describing what you want in plain English and letting an AI write and refine the code for you, instead of typing it yourself."},{"term":"Model","def":"The actual artificial intelligence that reads your text and writes the rewrite; in this project it's a copy you download and run on your own computer."},{"term":"Local server","def":"A program running on your own computer that quietly waits for other programs to ask it questions and sends back answers — here, your private AI serving rewrites."},{"term":"localhost","def":"A computer's nickname for 'this same machine,' so an address like http://localhost:1234 means 'a program running right here,' with nothing going over the internet."},{"term":"API","def":"The agreed-upon way for two programs to talk to each other, like a waiter carrying your order to the kitchen and bringing the food back."},{"term":"OpenAI-compatible","def":"A local AI that speaks the same standard request-and-response 'language' as the ChatGPT service, so code written for ChatGPT works with your private model too."},{"term":"PRD","def":"Program Requirements Document — a short, plain-language blueprint describing what your tool should do, look like, and how someone uses it, written before any code."},{"term":".env file and .gitignore","def":"A hidden file that safely holds secret passwords or keys, plus a list (.gitignore) of files that should never be uploaded when you publish your project."}],"tips":["Turn LM Studio's local server ON before testing your page — 90% of first-time 'it does nothing' problems are just the server not running or no model loaded.","Plan the PRD with one AI and build with a different one; the second opinion catches gaps before they're baked into code.","Treat AI-written code like an eager intern's work: functional but unverified. Click every button, try an empty box, and report bugs in plain English for the AI to fix.","Be specific in your intent command — name the exact tones, the exact button labels, and the exact localhost address. Vague requests produce vague apps.","Never let an AI write a real password or key into your code; if it does, tell it to move the secret into a .env file and add that file to .gitignore."]}];
